.TH "YQ" "1" "" ""
.SH NAME
\f[I]yq\f[R] is a portable command\-line data file processor
.SH SYNOPSIS
yq [eval/eval\-all] [expression] files..
.PP
eval/e \- (default) Apply the expression to each document in each yaml
file in sequence
.PP
eval\-all/ea \- Loads all yaml documents of all yaml files and runs
expression once
.SH DESCRIPTION
a lightweight and portable command\-line data file processor.
\f[CR]yq\f[R] uses \c
.UR https://github.com/stedolan/jq
jq
.UE \c
\ like syntax but works with yaml, json, xml, csv, properties and TOML
files.
It doesn\(cqt yet support everything \f[CR]jq\f[R] does \- but it does
support the most common operations and functions, and more is being
added continuously.
.PP
This documentation is also available at https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/
# QUICK GUIDE
.SS Read a value:
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.b[0].c\(aq file.yaml
.EE
.SS Pipe from STDIN:
.IP
.EX
cat file.yaml \f[B]|\f[R] yq \(aq.a.b[0].c\(aq
.EE
.SS Update a yaml file, in place
.IP
.EX
yq \-i \(aq.a.b[0].c = \(dqcool\(dq\(aq file.yaml
.EE
.SS Update using environment variables
.IP
.EX
NAME=mike yq \-i \(aq.a.b[0].c = strenv(NAME)\(aq file.yaml
.EE
.SS Merge multiple files
.IP
.EX
yq ea \(aq. as $item ireduce ({}; . * $item )\(aq path/to/*.yml
.EE
.PP
Note the use of \f[CR]ea\f[R] to evaluate all files at once (instead of
in sequence.)
.SS Multiple updates to a yaml file
.IP
.EX
yq \-i \(aq
  .a.b[0].c = \(dqcool\(dq |
  .x.y.z = \(dqfoobar\(dq |
  .person.name = strenv(NAME)
\(aq file.yaml
.EE
.PP
See the \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/
documentation
.UE \c
\ for more.
.SH KNOWN ISSUES / MISSING FEATURES
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]yq\f[R] attempts to preserve comment positions and whitespace as
much as possible, but it does not handle all scenarios (see
https://github.com/go\-yaml/yaml/tree/v3 for details)
.IP \(bu 2
Powershell has its own\&...opinions:
https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/usage/tips\-and\-tricks#quotes\-in\-windows\-powershell
.SH BUGS / ISSUES / FEATURE REQUESTS
Please visit the GitHub page https://github.com/mikefarah/yq/.
.SH HOW IT WORKS
In \f[CR]yq\f[R], expressions are made up of operators and pipes.
A context of nodes is passed through the expression, and each operation
takes the context as input and returns a new context as output.
That output is piped in as input for the next operation in the
expression.
.PP
Let\(cqs break down the process step by step using a diagram.
We\(cqll start with a single YAML document, apply an expression, and
observe how the context changes at each step.
.PP
Given a document like:
.IP
.EX
root\f[B]:\f[R]
  items\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] apple
      type\f[B]:\f[R] fruit
    \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] carrot
      type\f[B]:\f[R] vegetable
    \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] banana
      type\f[B]:\f[R] fruit
.EE
.PP
You can use dot notation to access nested structures.
For example, to access the \f[CR]name\f[R] of the first item, you would
use the expression \f[CR].root.items[0].name\f[R], which would return
\f[CR]apple\f[R].
.PP
But lets see how we could find all the fruit under \f[CR]items\f[R]
.SS Step 1: Initial Context
The context starts at the root of the YAML document.
In this case, the entire document is the initial context.
.IP
.EX
root
└── items
    ├── name: apple
    │   type: fruit
    ├── name: carrot
    │   type: vegetable
    └── name: banana
        type: fruit
.EE
.SS Step 2: Splatting the Array
Using the expression \f[CR].root.items[]\f[R], we \(lqsplat\(rq the
items array.
This means each element of the array becomes its own node in the
context:
.IP
.EX
Node 1: { name: apple, type: fruit }
Node 2: { name: carrot, type: vegetable }
Node 3: { name: banana, type: fruit }
.EE
.SS Step 3: Filtering the Nodes
Next, we apply a filter to select only the nodes where type is fruit.
The expression \f[CR].root.items[] | select(.type == \(dqfruit\(dq)\f[R]
filters the nodes:
.IP
.EX
Filtered Node 1: { name: apple, type: fruit }
Filtered Node 2: { name: banana, type: fruit }
.EE
.SS Step 4: Extracting a Field
Finally, we extract the name field from the filtered nodes using
\f[CR].root.items[] | select(.type == \(dqfruit\(dq) | .name\f[R] This
results in:
.IP
.EX
apple
banana
.EE
.SS Simple assignment example
Given a document like:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
with an expression:
.IP
.EX
\&.a = .b
.EE
.PP
Like math expressions \- operator precedence is important.
.PP
The \f[CR]=\f[R] operator takes two arguments, a \f[CR]lhs\f[R]
expression, which in this case is \f[CR].a\f[R] and \f[CR]rhs\f[R]
expression which is \f[CR].b\f[R].
.PP
It pipes the current, lets call it `root' context through the
\f[CR]lhs\f[R] expression of \f[CR].a\f[R] to return the node
.IP
.EX
cat
.EE
.PP
Side note: this node holds not only its value `cat', but comments and
metadata too, including path and parent information.
.PP
The \f[CR]=\f[R] operator then pipes the `root' context through the
\f[CR]rhs\f[R] expression of \f[CR].b\f[R] to return the node
.IP
.EX
dog
.EE
.PP
Both sides have now been evaluated, so now the operator copies across
the value from the RHS (\f[CR].b\f[R]) to the LHS (\f[CR].a\f[R]), and
it returns the now updated context:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] dog
b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.SS Complex assignment, operator precedence rules
Just like math expressions \- \f[CR]yq\f[R] expressions have an order of
precedence.
The pipe \f[CR]|\f[R] operator has a low order of precedence, so
operators with higher precedence will get evaluated first.
.PP
Most of the time, this is intuitively what you\(cqd want, for instance
\f[CR].a = \(dqcat\(dq | .b = \(dqdog\(dq\f[R] is effectively:
\f[CR](.a = \(dqcat\(dq) | (.b = \(dqdog\(dq)\f[R].
.PP
However, this is not always the case, particularly if you have a complex
LHS or RHS expression, for instance if you want to select particular
nodes to update.
.PP
Lets say you had:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] bob
  fruit\f[B]:\f[R] apple
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] sally
  fruit\f[B]:\f[R] orange
.EE
.PP
Lets say you wanted to update the \f[CR]sally\f[R] entry to have fruit:
`mango'.
The \f[I]incorrect\f[R] way to do that is:
\f[CR].[] | select(.name == \(dqsally\(dq) | .fruit = \(dqmango\(dq\f[R].
.PP
Because \f[CR]|\f[R] has a low operator precedence, this will be
evaluated (\f[I]incorrectly\f[R]) as :
\f[CR](.[]) | (select(.name == \(dqsally\(dq)) | (.fruit = \(dqmango\(dq)\f[R].
What you\(cqll see is only the updated segment returned:
.IP
.EX
name\f[B]:\f[R] sally
fruit\f[B]:\f[R] mango
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Important\f[R]: To properly update this YAML, you must wrap the
entire LHS in parentheses.
Think of it like using brackets in math to ensure the correct order of
operations.
\f[CR](.[] | select(.name == \(dqsally\(dq) | .fruit) = \(dqmango\(dq\f[R]
.PP
Now that entire LHS expression is passed to the `assign' (\f[CR]=\f[R])
operator, and the yaml is correctly updated and returned:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] bob
  fruit\f[B]:\f[R] apple
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] sally
  fruit\f[B]:\f[R] mango
.EE
.SS Relative update (e.g.\ \f[CR]|=\f[R])
There is another form of the \f[CR]=\f[R] operator which we call the
relative form.
It\(cqs very similar to \f[CR]=\f[R] but with one key difference when
evaluating the RHS expression.
.PP
In the plain form, we pass in the `root' level context to the RHS
expression.
In relative form, we pass in \f[I]each result of the LHS\f[R] to the RHS
expression.
Let\(cqs go through an example.
.PP
Given a document like:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 1
b\f[B]:\f[R] thing
.EE
.PP
with an expression:
.IP
.EX
\&.a |= . + 1
.EE
.PP
Similar to the \f[CR]=\f[R] operator, \f[CR]|=\f[R] takes two operands,
the LHS and RHS.
.PP
It pipes the current context (the whole document) through the LHS
expression of \f[CR].a\f[R] to get the node value:
.IP
.EX
1
.EE
.PP
Now it pipes \f[I]that LHS context\f[R] into the RHS expression
\f[CR]. + 1\f[R] (whereas in the \f[CR]=\f[R] plain form it piped the
original document context into the RHS) to yield:
.IP
.EX
2
.EE
.PP
The assignment operator then copies across the value from the RHS to the
value on the LHS, and it returns the now updated `root' context:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 2
b\f[B]:\f[R] thing
\(ga\(ga\(ga\f[I]# Add\f[R]

Add behaves differently according to the type of the LHS\f[B]:\f[R]
* arrays\f[B]:\f[R] concatenate
* number scalars\f[B]:\f[R] arithmetic addition
* string scalars\f[B]:\f[R] concatenate
* maps\f[B]:\f[R] shallow merge (use the multiply operator (\(ga*\(ga) to deeply merge)

Use \(ga+=\(ga as a relative append assign for things like increment. Note that \(ga.a += .x\(ga is equivalent to running \(ga.a = .a + .x\(ga.

\f[I]## Concatenate arrays\f[R]
Given a sample.yml file of\f[B]:\f[R]
\(ga\(ga\(gayaml
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 1
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 2
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 3
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 4
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a + .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
\f[B]\-\f[R] 4
.EE
.SS Concatenate to existing array
Note that the styling of \f[CR]a\f[R] is kept.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]1\f[B],\f[R]2\f[B]]\f[R]
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 3
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 4
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a += .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]1\f[B],\f[R] 2\f[B],\f[R] 3\f[B],\f[R] 4\f[B]]\f[R]
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 3
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 4
.EE
.SS Concatenate null to array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 1
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 2
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a + null\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
.EE
.SS Append to existing array
Note that the styling is copied from existing array elements
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]\(aqdog\(aq\f[B]]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a += \(dqcat\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]\(aqdog\(aq\f[B],\f[R] \(aqcat\(aq\f[B]]\f[R]
.EE
.SS Prepend to existing array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a = [\(dqcat\(dq] + .a\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] dog
.EE
.SS Add new object to array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] dog\f[B]:\f[R] woof
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a + {\(dqcat\(dq: \(dqmeow\(dq}\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] dog\f[B]:\f[R] woof
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat\f[B]:\f[R] meow
.EE
.SS Relative append
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  a1\f[B]:\f[R]
    b\f[B]:\f[R]
      \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  a2\f[B]:\f[R]
    b\f[B]:\f[R]
      \f[B]\-\f[R] dog
  a3\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B]{}\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a[].b += [\(dqmouse\(dq]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  a1\f[B]:\f[R]
    b\f[B]:\f[R]
      \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
      \f[B]\-\f[R] mouse
  a2\f[B]:\f[R]
    b\f[B]:\f[R]
      \f[B]\-\f[R] dog
      \f[B]\-\f[R] mouse
  a3\f[B]:\f[R]
    b\f[B]:\f[R]
      \f[B]\-\f[R] mouse
.EE
.SS String concatenation
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] meow
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a += .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] catmeow
b\f[B]:\f[R] meow
.EE
.SS Number addition \- float
If the lhs or rhs are floats then the expression will be calculated with
floats.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 3
b\f[B]:\f[R] 4.9
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a = .a + .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 7.9
b\f[B]:\f[R] 4.9
.EE
.SS Number addition \- int
If both the lhs and rhs are ints then the expression will be calculated
with ints.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 3
b\f[B]:\f[R] 4
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a = .a + .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 7
b\f[B]:\f[R] 4
.EE
.SS Increment numbers
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 3
b\f[B]:\f[R] 5
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] += 1\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 4
b\f[B]:\f[R] 6
.EE
.SS Date addition
You can add durations to dates.
Assumes RFC3339 date time format, see \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/date-time-operators
date\-time operators
.UE \c
\ for more information.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 2021\-01\-01T00:00:00Z
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a += \(dq3h10m\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 2021\-01\-01T03:10:00Z
.EE
.SS Date addition \- custom format
You can add durations to dates.
See \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/date-time-operators
date\-time operators
.UE \c
\ for more information.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] Saturday, 15\-Dec\-01 at 2:59AM GMT
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqwith_dtf(\(dqMonday, 02\-Jan\-06 at 3:04PM MST\(dq, .a += \(dq3h1m\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] Saturday, 15\-Dec\-01 at 6:00AM GMT
.EE
.SS Add to null
Adding to null simply returns the rhs
.PP
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aqnull + \(dqcat\(dq\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cat
.EE
.SS Add maps to shallow merge
Adding objects together shallow merges them.
Use \f[CR]*\f[R] to deeply merge.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  thing\f[B]:\f[R]
    name\f[B]:\f[R] Astuff
    value\f[B]:\f[R] x
  a1\f[B]:\f[R] cool
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  thing\f[B]:\f[R]
    name\f[B]:\f[R] Bstuff
    legs\f[B]:\f[R] 3
  b1\f[B]:\f[R] neat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a += .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  thing\f[B]:\f[R]
    name\f[B]:\f[R] Bstuff
    legs\f[B]:\f[R] 3
  a1\f[B]:\f[R] cool
  b1\f[B]:\f[R] neat
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  thing\f[B]:\f[R]
    name\f[B]:\f[R] Bstuff
    legs\f[B]:\f[R] 3
  b1\f[B]:\f[R] neat
.EE
.SS Custom types: that are really strings
When custom tags are encountered, yq will try to decode the underlying
type.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !horse cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] !goat _meow
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a += .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !horse cat_meow
b\f[B]:\f[R] !goat _meow
.EE
.SS Custom types: that are really numbers
When custom tags are encountered, yq will try to decode the underlying
type.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !horse 1.2
b\f[B]:\f[R] !goat 2.3
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a += .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !horse 3.5
b\f[B]:\f[R] !goat 2.3
.EE
.SH Alternative (Default value)
This operator is used to provide alternative (or default) values when a
particular expression is either null or false.
.SS LHS is defined
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] bridge
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a // \(dqhello\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
bridge
.EE
.SS LHS is not defined
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{}\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a // \(dqhello\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
hello
.EE
.SS LHS is null
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] \(ti
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a // \(dqhello\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
hello
.EE
.SS LHS is false
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] false
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a // \(dqhello\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
hello
.EE
.SS RHS is an expression
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] false
b\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a // .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cat
.EE
.SS Update or create \- entity exists
This initialises \f[CR]a\f[R] if it\(cqs not present
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 1
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq(.a // (.a = 0)) += 1\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 2
.EE
.SS Update or create \- entity does not exist
This initialises \f[CR]a\f[R] if it\(cqs not present
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
b\f[B]:\f[R] camel
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq(.a // (.a = 0)) += 1\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
b\f[B]:\f[R] camel
a\f[B]:\f[R] 1
.EE
.SH Anchor and Alias Operators
Use the \f[CR]alias\f[R] and \f[CR]anchor\f[R] operators to read and
write yaml aliases and anchors.
The \f[CR]explode\f[R] operator normalises a yaml file (dereference (or
expands) aliases and remove anchor names).
.PP
\f[CR]yq\f[R] supports merge aliases (like \f[CR]<<: *blah\f[R]) however
this is no longer in the standard yaml spec (1.2) and so \f[CR]yq\f[R]
will automatically add the \f[CR]!!merge\f[R] tag to these nodes as it
is effectively a custom tag.
.SS NOTE \(enyaml\-fix\-merge\-anchor\-to\-spec flag
\f[CR]yq\f[R] doesn\(cqt merge anchors \f[CR]<<:\f[R] to spec, in some
circumstances it incorrectly overrides existing keys when the spec
documents not to do that.
.PP
To minimise disruption while still fixing the issue, a flag has been
added to toggle this behaviour.
This will first default to false; and log warnings to users.
Then it will default to true (and still allow users to specify false if
needed).
.PP
This flag also enables advanced merging, like inline maps, as well as
fixes to ensure when exploding a particular path, neighbours are not
affect ed.
.PP
Long story short, you should be setting this flag to true.
.PP
See examples of the flag differences below, where LEGACY is with the
flag off; and FIXED is with the flag on.
.SS Merge one map
see https://yaml.org/type/merge.html
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] &CENTRE
  x\f[B]:\f[R] 1
  y\f[B]:\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] &LEFT
  x\f[B]:\f[R] 0
  y\f[B]:\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] &BIG
  r\f[B]:\f[R] 10
\f[B]\-\f[R] &SMALL
  r\f[B]:\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] !!merge <<\f[B]:\f[R] *CENTRE
  r\f[B]:\f[R] 10
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[4] | explode(.)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
x\f[B]:\f[R] 1
y\f[B]:\f[R] 2
r\f[B]:\f[R] 10
.EE
.SS Get anchor
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] &billyBob cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a | anchor\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
billyBob
.EE
.SS Set anchor
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a anchor = \(dqfoobar\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] &foobar cat
.EE
.SS Set anchor relatively using assign\-update
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a anchor |= .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] &cat
  b\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS Get alias
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
b\f[B]:\f[R] &billyBob meow
a\f[B]:\f[R] *billyBob
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a | alias\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
