.SH Array to Map
Use this operator to convert an array to..a map.
The indices are used as map keys, null values in the array are skipped
over.
.PP
Behind the scenes, this is implemented using reduce:
.IP
.EX
(.[] | select(. != null) ) as $i ireduce({}; .[$i | key] = $i)
.EE
.SS Simple example
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
cool\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] null
  \f[B]\-\f[R] null
  \f[B]\-\f[R] hello
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.cool |= array_to_map\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cool\f[B]:\f[R]
  2\f[B]:\f[R] hello
.EE
.SH Assign (Update)
This operator is used to update node values.
It can be used in either the:
.SS plain form: \f[CR]=\f[R]
Which will set the LHS node values equal to the RHS node values.
The RHS expression is run against the matching nodes in the pipeline.
.SS relative form: \f[CR]|=\f[R]
This will do a similar thing to the plain form, but the RHS expression
is run with \f[I]each LHS node as context\f[R].
This is useful for updating values based on old values, e.g.\ increment.
.SS Flags
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]c\f[R] clobber custom tags
.SS Create yaml file
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq.a.b = \(dqcat\(dq | .x = \(dqfrog\(dq\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] cat
x\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.SS Update node to be the child value
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    g\f[B]:\f[R] foof
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a |= .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  g\f[B]:\f[R] foof
.EE
.SS Double elements in an array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] |= . * 2\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] 4
\f[B]\-\f[R] 6
.EE
.SS Update node from another file
Note this will also work when the second file is a scalar
(string/number)
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] apples
.EE
.PP
And another sample another.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
b\f[B]:\f[R] bob
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq eval\-all \(aqselect(fileIndex==0).a = select(fileIndex==1) | select(fileIndex==0)\(aq sample.yml another.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] bob
.EE
.SS Update node to be the sibling value
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] child
b\f[B]:\f[R] sibling
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a = .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] sibling
b\f[B]:\f[R] sibling
.EE
.SS Updated multiple paths
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] fieldA
b\f[B]:\f[R] fieldB
c\f[B]:\f[R] fieldC
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq(.a, .c) = \(dqpotato\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] potato
b\f[B]:\f[R] fieldB
c\f[B]:\f[R] potato
.EE
.SS Update string value
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.b = \(dqfrog\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.SS Update string value via |=
Note there is no difference between \f[CR]=\f[R] and \f[CR]|=\f[R] when
the RHS is a scalar
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.b |= \(dqfrog\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.SS Update deeply selected results
Note that the LHS is wrapped in brackets!
This is to ensure we don\(cqt first filter out the yaml and then update
the snippet.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] apple
  c\f[B]:\f[R] cactus
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq(.a[] | select(. == \(dqapple\(dq)) = \(dqfrog\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] frog
  c\f[B]:\f[R] cactus
.EE
.SS Update array values
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] candy
\f[B]\-\f[R] apple
\f[B]\-\f[R] sandy
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq(.[] | select(. == \(dq*andy\(dq)) = \(dqbogs\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] bogs
\f[B]\-\f[R] apple
\f[B]\-\f[R] bogs
.EE
.SS Update empty object
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{}\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.b |= \(dqbogs\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] bogs
.EE
.SS Update node value that has an anchor
Anchor will remain
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] &cool cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a = \(dqdog\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] &cool dog
.EE
.SS Update empty object and array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{}\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.b.[0] |= \(dqbogs\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] bogs
.EE
.SS Custom types are maintained by default
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !cat meow
b\f[B]:\f[R] !dog woof
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a = .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !cat woof
b\f[B]:\f[R] !dog woof
.EE
.SS Custom types: clobber
Use the \f[CR]c\f[R] option to clobber custom tags
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !cat meow
b\f[B]:\f[R] !dog woof
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a =c .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !dog woof
b\f[B]:\f[R] !dog woof
.EE
.SH Boolean Operators
The \f[CR]or\f[R] and \f[CR]and\f[R] operators take two parameters and
return a boolean result.
.PP
\f[CR]not\f[R] flips a boolean from true to false, or vice versa.
.PP
\f[CR]any\f[R] will return \f[CR]true\f[R] if there are any
\f[CR]true\f[R] values in an array sequence, and \f[CR]all\f[R] will
return true if \f[I]all\f[R] elements in an array are true.
.PP
\f[CR]any_c(condition)\f[R] and \f[CR]all_c(condition)\f[R] are like
\f[CR]any\f[R] and \f[CR]all\f[R] but they take a condition expression
that is used against each element to determine if it\(cqs
\f[CR]true\f[R].
Note: in \f[CR]jq\f[R] you can simply pass a condition to \f[CR]any\f[R]
or \f[CR]all\f[R] and it simply works \- \f[CR]yq\f[R] isn\(cqt that
clever..yet
.PP
These are most commonly used with the \f[CR]select\f[R] operator to
filter particular nodes.
.SS Related Operators
.IP \(bu 2
equals / not equals (\f[CR]==\f[R], \f[CR]!=\f[R]) operators \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/equals
here
.UE \c
.IP \(bu 2
comparison (\f[CR]>=\f[R], \f[CR]<\f[R] etc) operators \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/compare
here
.UE \c
.IP \(bu 2
select operator \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/select
here
.UE \c
.SS \f[CR]or\f[R] example
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aqtrue or false\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
.EE
.SS \(lqyes\(rq and \(lqno\(rq are strings
In the yaml 1.2 standard, support for yes/no as booleans was dropped \-
they are now considered strings.
See `10.2.1.2.
Boolean' in https://yaml.org/spec/1.2.2/
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] yes
\f[B]\-\f[R] no
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | tag\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
!!str
!!str
.EE
.SS \f[CR]and\f[R] example
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aqtrue and false\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
false
.EE
.SS Matching nodes with select, equals and or
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] bird
  b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] frog
  b\f[B]:\f[R] bird
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
  b\f[B]:\f[R] fly
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq[.[] | select(.a == \(dqcat\(dq or .b == \(dqdog\(dq)]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] bird
  b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
  b\f[B]:\f[R] fly
.EE
.SS \f[CR]any\f[R] returns true if any boolean in a given array is true
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] false
\f[B]\-\f[R] true
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqany\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
.EE
.SS \f[CR]any\f[R] returns false for an empty array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqany\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
false
.EE
.SS \f[CR]any_c\f[R] returns true if any element in the array is true for the given condition.
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] rad
  \f[B]\-\f[R] awesome
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] meh
  \f[B]\-\f[R] whatever
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] |= any_c(. == \(dqawesome\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] true
b\f[B]:\f[R] false
.EE
.SS \f[CR]all\f[R] returns true if all booleans in a given array are true
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] true
\f[B]\-\f[R] true
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqall\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
.EE
.SS \f[CR]all\f[R] returns true for an empty array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqall\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
.EE
.SS \f[CR]all_c\f[R] returns true if all elements in the array are true for the given condition.
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] rad
  \f[B]\-\f[R] awesome
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] meh
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 12
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] |= all_c(tag == \(dq!!str\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] true
b\f[B]:\f[R] false
.EE
.SS Not true is false
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aqtrue | not\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
false
.EE
.SS Not false is true
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aqfalse | not\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
.EE
.SS String values considered to be true
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq\(dqcat\(dq | not\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
false
.EE
.SS Empty string value considered to be true
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq\(dq\(dq | not\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
false
.EE
.SS Numbers are considered to be true
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq1 | not\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
false
.EE
.SS Zero is considered to be true
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq0 | not\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
false
.EE
.SS Null is considered to be false
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq\(ti | not\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
.EE
.SH Collect into Array
This creates an array using the expression between the square brackets.
.SS Collect empty
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq[]\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.SS Collect single
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq[\(dqcat\(dq]\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS Collect many
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq[.a, .b]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] dog
.EE
.SH Column
Returns the column of the matching node.
Starts from 1, 0 indicates there was no column data.
.PP
Column is the number of characters that precede that node on the line it
starts.
.SS Returns column of \f[I]value\f[R] node
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] bob
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.b | column\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
4
.EE
.SS Returns column of \f[I]key\f[R] node
Pipe through the key operator to get the column of the key
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] bob
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.b | key | column\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
1
.EE
.SS First column is 1
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a | key | column\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
1
.EE
.SS No column data is 0
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq{\(dqa\(dq: \(dqnew entry\(dq} | column\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
0
.EE
.SH Comment Operators
Use these comment operators to set or retrieve comments.
Note that line comments on maps/arrays are actually set on the
\f[I]key\f[R] node as opposed to the \f[I]value\f[R] (map/array).
See below for examples.
.PP
Like the \f[CR]=\f[R] and \f[CR]|=\f[R] assign operators, the same
syntax applies when updating comments:
.SS plain form: \f[CR]=\f[R]
This will set the LHS nodes\(cq comments equal to the expression on the
RHS.
The RHS is run against the matching nodes in the pipeline
.SS relative form: \f[CR]|=\f[R]
This is similar to the plain form, but it evaluates the RHS with
\f[I]each matching LHS node as context\f[R].
This is useful if you want to set the comments as a relative expression
of the node, for instance its value or path.
.SS Set line comment
Set the comment on the key node for more reliability (see below).
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a line_comment=\(dqsingle\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat\f[I] # single\f[R]
.EE
.SS Set line comment of a maps/arrays
For maps and arrays, you need to set the line comment on the
\f[I]key\f[R] node.
This will also work for scalars.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] things
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq(.a | key) line_comment=\(dqsingle\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]\f[I] # single\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] things
.EE
.SS Use update assign to perform relative updates
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.. line_comment |= .\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat\f[I] # cat\f[R]
b\f[B]:\f[R] dog\f[I] # dog\f[R]
.EE
.SS Where is the comment \- map key example
The underlying yaml parser can assign comments in a document to
surprising nodes.
Use an expression like this to find where you comment is.
`p' indicates the path, `isKey' is if the node is a map key (as opposed
to a map value).
From this, you can see the `hello\-world\-comment' is actually on the
`hello' key
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
hello\f[B]:\f[R]\f[I] # hello\-world\-comment\f[R]
  message\f[B]:\f[R] world
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq[... | {\(dqp\(dq: path | join(\(dq.\(dq), \(dqisKey\(dq: is_key, \(dqhc\(dq: headComment, \(dqlc\(dq: lineComment, \(dqfc\(dq: footComment}]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] p\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  isKey\f[B]:\f[R] false
  hc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  lc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  fc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
\f[B]\-\f[R] p\f[B]:\f[R] hello
  isKey\f[B]:\f[R] true
  hc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  lc\f[B]:\f[R] hello\-world\-comment
  fc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
\f[B]\-\f[R] p\f[B]:\f[R] hello
  isKey\f[B]:\f[R] false
  hc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  lc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  fc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
\f[B]\-\f[R] p\f[B]:\f[R] hello.message
  isKey\f[B]:\f[R] true
  hc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  lc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  fc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
\f[B]\-\f[R] p\f[B]:\f[R] hello.message
  isKey\f[B]:\f[R] false
  hc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  lc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  fc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
.EE
.SS Retrieve comment \- map key example
From the previous example, we know that the comment is on the `hello'
\f[I]key\f[R] as a lineComment
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
hello\f[B]:\f[R]\f[I] # hello\-world\-comment\f[R]
  message\f[B]:\f[R] world
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.hello | key | line_comment\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
hello\-world\-comment
.EE
.SS Where is the comment \- array example
The underlying yaml parser can assign comments in a document to
surprising nodes.
Use an expression like this to find where you comment is.
`p' indicates the path, `isKey' is if the node is a map key (as opposed
to a map value).
From this, you can see the `under\-name\-comment' is actually on the
first child
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
name\f[B]:\f[R]
\f[I]  # under\-name\-comment\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] first\-array\-child
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq[... | {\(dqp\(dq: path | join(\(dq.\(dq), \(dqisKey\(dq: is_key, \(dqhc\(dq: headComment, \(dqlc\(dq: lineComment, \(dqfc\(dq: footComment}]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] p\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  isKey\f[B]:\f[R] false
  hc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  lc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  fc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
\f[B]\-\f[R] p\f[B]:\f[R] name
  isKey\f[B]:\f[R] true
  hc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  lc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  fc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
\f[B]\-\f[R] p\f[B]:\f[R] name
  isKey\f[B]:\f[R] false
  hc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  lc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  fc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
\f[B]\-\f[R] p\f[B]:\f[R] name.0
  isKey\f[B]:\f[R] false
  hc\f[B]:\f[R] under\-name\-comment
  lc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  fc\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
.EE
.SS Retrieve comment \- array example
From the previous example, we know that the comment is on the first
child as a headComment
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
name\f[B]:\f[R]
\f[I]  # under\-name\-comment\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] first\-array\-child
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.name[0] | headComment\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
under\-name\-comment
.EE
.SS Set head comment
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq. head_comment=\(dqsingle\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# single\f[R]
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS Set head comment of a map entry
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
f\f[B]:\f[R] foo
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq(.a | key) head_comment=\(dqsingle\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
f\f[B]:\f[R] foo
\f[I]# single\f[R]
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS Set foot comment, using an expression
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq. foot_comment=.a\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\f[I]# cat\f[R]
.EE
.SS Remove comment
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat\f[I] # comment\f[R]
b\f[B]:\f[R] dog\f[I] # leave this\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a line_comment=\(dq\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] dog\f[I] # leave this\f[R]
.EE
.SS Remove (strip) all comments
Note the use of \f[CR]...\f[R] to ensure key nodes are included.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# hi\f[R]

a\f[B]:\f[R] cat\f[I] # comment\f[R]
\f[I]# great\f[R]
b\f[B]:\f[R]\f[I] # key comment\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq... comments=\(dq\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R]
.EE
.SS Get line comment
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# welcome!\f[R]

a\f[B]:\f[R] cat\f[I] # meow\f[R]
\f[I]# have a great day\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a | line_comment\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
meow
.EE
.SS Get head comment
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# welcome!\f[R]

a\f[B]:\f[R] cat\f[I] # meow\f[R]

\f[I]# have a great day\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq. | head_comment\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
welcome!
.EE
.SS Head comment with document split
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# welcome!\f[R]
\-\-\-
\f[I]# bob\f[R]
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat\f[I] # meow\f[R]

\f[I]# have a great day\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqhead_comment\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
welcome!
bob
.EE
.SS Get foot comment
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# welcome!\f[R]

a\f[B]:\f[R] cat\f[I] # meow\f[R]

\f[I]# have a great day\f[R]
\f[I]# no really\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq. | foot_comment\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
have a great day
no really
.EE
.SH Compare Operators
Comparison operators (\f[CR]>\f[R], \f[CR]>=\f[R], \f[CR]<\f[R],
\f[CR]<=\f[R]) can be used for comparing scalar values of the same time.
.PP
The following types are currently supported:
.IP \(bu 2
numbers
.IP \(bu 2
strings
.IP \(bu 2
datetimes
.SS Related Operators
.IP \(bu 2
equals / not equals (\f[CR]==\f[R], \f[CR]!=\f[R]) operators \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/equals
here
.UE \c
.IP \(bu 2
boolean operators (\f[CR]and\f[R], \f[CR]or\f[R], \f[CR]any\f[R] etc) \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/boolean-operators
here
.UE \c
.IP \(bu 2
select operator \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/select
here
.UE \c
.SS Compare numbers (>)
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 5
b\f[B]:\f[R] 4
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a > .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
.EE
.SS Compare equal numbers (>=)
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 5
b\f[B]:\f[R] 5
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a >= .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
.EE
.SS Compare strings
Compares strings by their bytecode.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] zoo
b\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a > .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
.EE
.SS Compare date times
You can compare date times.
Assumes RFC3339 date time format, see \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/date-time-operators
date\-time operators
.UE \c
\ for more information.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 2021\-01\-01T03:10:00Z
b\f[B]:\f[R] 2020\-01\-01T03:10:00Z
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a > .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
.EE
.SS Both sides are null: > is false
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq.a > .b\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
false
.EE
.SS Both sides are null: >= is true
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq.a >= .b\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
.EE
.SH Contains
This returns \f[CR]true\f[R] if the context contains the passed in
parameter, and false otherwise.
For arrays, this will return true if the passed in array is contained
within the array.
For strings, it will return true if the string is a substring.
.PP
{% hint style=\(lqwarning\(rq %}
.PP
\f[I]Note\f[R] that, just like jq, when checking if an array of strings
\f[CR]contains\f[R] another, this will use \f[CR]contains\f[R] and
\f[I]not\f[R] equals to check each string.
This means an expression like \f[CR]contains([\(dqcat\(dq])\f[R] will
return true for an array \f[CR][\(dqcats\(dq]\f[R].
.PP
See the \(lqArray has a subset array\(rq example below on how to check
for a subset.
.PP
{% endhint %}
.SS Array contains array
Array is equal or subset of
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] foobar
\f[B]\-\f[R] foobaz
\f[B]\-\f[R] blarp
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqcontains([\(dqbaz\(dq, \(dqbar\(dq])\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
.EE
.SS Array has a subset array
Subtract the superset array from the subset, if there\(cqs anything
left, it\(cqs not a subset
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] foobar
\f[B]\-\f[R] foobaz
\f[B]\-\f[R] blarp
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq[\(dqbaz\(dq, \(dqbar\(dq] \- . | length == 0\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
false
.EE
.SS Object included in array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\(dqfoo\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] 12
\(dqbar\(dq\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 1
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 2
  \f[B]\-\f[R] \(dqbarp\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] 12
    \(dqblip\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] 13
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqcontains({\(dqbar\(dq: [{\(dqbarp\(dq: 12}]})\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
.EE
.SS Object not included in array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\(dqfoo\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] 12
\(dqbar\(dq\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 1
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 2
  \f[B]\-\f[R] \(dqbarp\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] 12
    \(dqblip\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] 13
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqcontains({\(dqfoo\(dq: 12, \(dqbar\(dq: [{\(dqbarp\(dq: 15}]})\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
false
.EE
.SS String contains substring
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
foobar
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqcontains(\(dqbar\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
.EE
.SS String equals string
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
meow
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqcontains(\(dqmeow\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
.EE
.SH Create, Collect into Object
This is used to construct objects (or maps).
This can be used against existing yaml, or to create fresh yaml
documents.
.SS Collect empty object
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq{}\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{}\f[R]
.EE
.SS Wrap (prefix) existing object
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
name\f[B]:\f[R] Mike
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq{\(dqwrap\(dq: .}\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
wrap\f[B]:\f[R]
  name\f[B]:\f[R] Mike
.EE
.SS Using splat to create multiple objects
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
name\f[B]:\f[R] Mike
pets\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq{.name: .pets.[]}\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Mike\f[B]:\f[R] cat
Mike\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.SS Working with multiple documents
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
name\f[B]:\f[R] Mike
pets\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] dog
\-\-\-
name\f[B]:\f[R] Rosey
pets\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] monkey
  \f[B]\-\f[R] sheep
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq{.name: .pets.[]}\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Mike\f[B]:\f[R] cat
Mike\f[B]:\f[R] dog
\-\-\-
Rosey\f[B]:\f[R] monkey
Rosey\f[B]:\f[R] sheep
.EE
.SS Creating yaml from scratch
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq{\(dqwrap\(dq: \(dqfrog\(dq}\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
wrap\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.SS Creating yaml from scratch with multiple objects
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq(.a.b = \(dqfoo\(dq) | (.d.e = \(dqbar\(dq)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] foo
d\f[B]:\f[R]
  e\f[B]:\f[R] bar
.EE
.SH Date Time
Various operators for parsing and manipulating dates.
.SS Date time formatting
This uses Golang\(cqs built in time library for parsing and formatting
date times.
.PP
When not specified, the RFC3339 standard is assumed
\f[CR]2006\-01\-02T15:04:05Z07:00\f[R] for parsing.
.PP
To specify a custom parsing format, use the \f[CR]with_dtf\f[R]
operator.
The first parameter sets the datetime parsing format for the expression
in the second parameter.
The expression can be any valid \f[CR]yq\f[R] expression tree.
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqwith_dtf(\(dqmyformat\(dq; .a + \(dq3h\(dq | tz(\(dqAustralia/Melbourne\(dq))\(aq
.EE
.PP
See the \c
.UR https://pkg.go.dev/time#pkg-constants
library docs
.UE \c
\ for examples of formatting options.
.SS Timezones
This uses Golang\(cqs built in LoadLocation function to parse timezones
strings.
See the \c
.UR https://pkg.go.dev/time#LoadLocation
library docs
.UE \c
\ for more details.
.SS Durations
Durations are parsed using Golang\(cqs built in \c
.UR https://pkg.go.dev/time#ParseDuration
ParseDuration
.UE \c
\ function.
.PP
You can add durations to time using the \f[CR]+\f[R] operator.
.SS Format: from standard RFC3339 format
Providing a single parameter assumes a standard RFC3339 datetime format.
If the target format is not a valid yaml datetime format, the result
will be a string tagged node.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 2001\-12\-15T02:59:43.1Z
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a |= format_datetime(\(dqMonday, 02\-Jan\-06 at 3:04PM\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] Saturday, 15\-Dec\-01 at 2:59AM
.EE
.SS Format: from custom date time
Use with_dtf to set a custom datetime format for parsing.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] Saturday, 15\-Dec\-01 at 2:59AM
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a |= with_dtf(\(dqMonday, 02\-Jan\-06 at 3:04PM\(dq; format_datetime(\(dq2006\-01\-02\(dq))\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 2001\-12\-15
.EE
.SS Format: get the day of the week
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 2001\-12\-15
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a | format_datetime(\(dqMonday\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Saturday
.EE
.SS Now
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cool
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.updated = now\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cool
updated\f[B]:\f[R] 2021\-05\-19T01:02:03Z
.EE
.SS From Unix
Converts from unix time.
Note, you don\(cqt have to pipe through the tz operator :)
.PP
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq1675301929 | from_unix | tz(\(dqUTC\(dq)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
2023\-02\-02T01:38:49Z
.EE
.SS To Unix
Converts to unix time
.PP
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aqnow | to_unix\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
1621386123
.EE
.SS Timezone: from standard RFC3339 format
Returns a new datetime in the specified timezone.
Specify standard IANA Time Zone format or `utc', `local'.
When given a single parameter, this assumes the datetime is in RFC3339
format.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cool
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.updated = (now | tz(\(dqAustralia/Sydney\(dq))\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cool
updated\f[B]:\f[R] 2021\-05\-19T11:02:03+10:00
.EE
.SS Timezone: with custom format
Specify standard IANA Time Zone format or `utc', `local'
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] Saturday, 15\-Dec\-01 at 2:59AM GMT
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a |= with_dtf(\(dqMonday, 02\-Jan\-06 at 3:04PM MST\(dq; tz(\(dqAustralia/Sydney\(dq))\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] Saturday, 15\-Dec\-01 at 1:59PM AEDT
.EE
.SS Add and tz custom format
Specify standard IANA Time Zone format or `utc', `local'
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] Saturday, 15\-Dec\-01 at 2:59AM GMT
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a |= with_dtf(\(dqMonday, 02\-Jan\-06 at 3:04PM MST\(dq; tz(\(dqAustralia/Sydney\(dq))\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] Saturday, 15\-Dec\-01 at 1:59PM AEDT
.EE
.SS Date addition
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 2021\-01\-01T00:00:00Z
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a += \(dq3h10m\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 2021\-01\-01T03:10:00Z
.EE
.SS Date subtraction
You can subtract durations from dates.
Assumes RFC3339 date time format, see \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/datetime#date-time-formattings
date\-time operators
.UE \c
\ for more information.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 2021\-01\-01T03:10:00Z
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a \-= \(dq3h10m\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 2021\-01\-01T00:00:00Z
.EE
.SS Date addition \- custom format
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] Saturday, 15\-Dec\-01 at 2:59AM GMT
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqwith_dtf(\(dqMonday, 02\-Jan\-06 at 3:04PM MST\(dq; .a += \(dq3h1m\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] Saturday, 15\-Dec\-01 at 6:00AM GMT
.EE
.SS Date script with custom format
You can embed full expressions in with_dtf if needed.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] Saturday, 15\-Dec\-01 at 2:59AM GMT
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqwith_dtf(\(dqMonday, 02\-Jan\-06 at 3:04PM MST\(dq; .a = (.a + \(dq3h1m\(dq | tz(\(dqAustralia/Perth\(dq)))\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] Saturday, 15\-Dec\-01 at 2:00PM AWST
.EE
.SH Delete
Deletes matching entries in maps or arrays.
.SS Delete entry in map
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqdel(.b)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS Delete nested entry in map
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  a1\f[B]:\f[R] fred
  a2\f[B]:\f[R] frood
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqdel(.a.a1)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  a2\f[B]:\f[R] frood
.EE
.SS Delete entry in array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqdel(.[1])\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
.EE
.SS Delete nested entry in array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
  b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqdel(.[0].a)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.SS Delete no matches
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqdel(.c)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.SS Delete matching entries
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
c\f[B]:\f[R] bat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqdel( .[] | select(. == \(dq*at\(dq) )\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.SS Recursively delete matching keys
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  name\f[B]:\f[R] frog
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    name\f[B]:\f[R] blog
    age\f[B]:\f[R] 12
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqdel(.. | select(has(\(dqname\(dq)).name)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    age\f[B]:\f[R] 12
.EE
.SH Divide
Divide behaves differently according to the type of the LHS: * strings:
split by the divider * number: arithmetic division
.SS String split
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat_meow
b\f[B]:\f[R] _
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.c = .a / .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat_meow
b\f[B]:\f[R] _
c\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] meow
.EE
.SS Number division
The result during division is calculated as a float
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 12
b\f[B]:\f[R] 2.5
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a = .a / .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 4.8
b\f[B]:\f[R] 2.5
.EE
.SS Number division by zero
Dividing by zero results in +Inf or \-Inf
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 1
b\f[B]:\f[R] \-1
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a = .a / 0 | .b = .b / 0\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !!float +Inf
b\f[B]:\f[R] !!float \-Inf
.EE
.SH Document Index
Use the \f[CR]documentIndex\f[R] operator (or the \f[CR]di\f[R]
shorthand) to select nodes of a particular document.
.SS Retrieve a document index
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\-\-\-
a\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a | document_index\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
0
\-\-\-
1
.EE
.SS Retrieve a document index, shorthand
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\-\-\-
a\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a | di\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
0
\-\-\-
1
.EE
.SS Filter by document index
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\-\-\-
a\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqselect(document_index == 1)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.SS Filter by document index shorthand
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\-\-\-
a\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqselect(di == 1)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.SS Print Document Index with matches
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\-\-\-
a\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a | ({\(dqmatch\(dq: ., \(dqdoc\(dq: document_index})\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
match\f[B]:\f[R] cat
doc\f[B]:\f[R] 0
\-\-\-
match\f[B]:\f[R] frog
doc\f[B]:\f[R] 1
.EE
.SH Encoder / Decoder
Encode operators will take the piped in object structure and encode it
as a string in the desired format.
The decode operators do the opposite, they take a formatted string and
decode it into the relevant object structure.
.PP
Note that you can optionally pass an indent value to the encode
functions (see below).
.PP
These operators are useful to process yaml documents that have
stringified embedded yaml/json/props in them.
.PP
