.PP
See CSV and TSV \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/usage/csv-tsv
documentation
.UE \c
\ for accepted formats.
.PP
XML uses the \f[CR]\-\-xml\-attribute\-prefix\f[R] and
\f[CR]xml\-content\-name\f[R] flags to identify attributes and content
fields.
.PP
Base64 assumes \c
.UR https://rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc4648.html
rfc4648
.UE \c
\ encoding.
Encoding and decoding both assume that the content is a utf\-8 string
and not binary content.
.SS Encode value as json string
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  cool\f[B]:\f[R] thing
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.b = (.a | to_json)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  cool\f[B]:\f[R] thing
b\f[B]: \f[R]|
  {
    \(dqcool\(dq: \(dqthing\(dq
  }
.EE
.SS Encode value as json string, on one line
Pass in a 0 indent to print json on a single line.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  cool\f[B]:\f[R] thing
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.b = (.a | to_json(0))\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  cool\f[B]:\f[R] thing
b\f[B]:\f[R] \(aq{\(dqcool\(dq:\(dqthing\(dq}\(aq
.EE
.SS Encode value as json string, on one line shorthand
Pass in a 0 indent to print json on a single line.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  cool\f[B]:\f[R] thing
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.b = (.a | \(atjson)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  cool\f[B]:\f[R] thing
b\f[B]:\f[R] \(aq{\(dqcool\(dq:\(dqthing\(dq}\(aq
.EE
.SS Decode a json encoded string
Keep in mind JSON is a subset of YAML.
If you want idiomatic yaml, pipe through the style operator to clear out
the JSON styling.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] \(aq{\(dqcool\(dq:\(dqthing\(dq}\(aq
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a | from_json | ... style=\(dq\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cool\f[B]:\f[R] thing
.EE
.SS Encode value as props string
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  cool\f[B]:\f[R] thing
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.b = (.a | \(atprops)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  cool\f[B]:\f[R] thing
b\f[B]: \f[R]|
  cool = thing
.EE
.SS Decode props encoded string
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]: \f[R]|\-
  cats=great
  dogs=cool as well
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a |= \(atpropsd\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  cats\f[B]:\f[R] great
  dogs\f[B]:\f[R] cool as well
.EE
.SS Decode csv encoded string
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]: \f[R]|\-
  cats,dogs
  great,cool as well
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a |= \(atcsvd\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] cats\f[B]:\f[R] great
    dogs\f[B]:\f[R] cool as well
.EE
.SS Decode tsv encoded string
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]: \f[R]|\-
  cats  dogs
  great cool as well
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a |= \(attsvd\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] cats\f[B]:\f[R] great
    dogs\f[B]:\f[R] cool as well
.EE
.SS Encode value as yaml string
Indent defaults to 2
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  cool\f[B]:\f[R]
    bob\f[B]:\f[R] dylan
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.b = (.a | to_yaml)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  cool\f[B]:\f[R]
    bob\f[B]:\f[R] dylan
b\f[B]: \f[R]|
  cool:
    bob: dylan
.EE
.SS Encode value as yaml string, with custom indentation
You can specify the indentation level as the first parameter.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  cool\f[B]:\f[R]
    bob\f[B]:\f[R] dylan
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.b = (.a | to_yaml(8))\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  cool\f[B]:\f[R]
    bob\f[B]:\f[R] dylan
b\f[B]: \f[R]|
  cool:
          bob: dylan
.EE
.SS Decode a yaml encoded string
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] \(aqfoo: bar\(aq
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.b = (.a | from_yaml)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] \(aqfoo: bar\(aq
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  foo\f[B]:\f[R] bar
.EE
.SS Update a multiline encoded yaml string
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]: \f[R]|
  foo: bar
  baz: dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a |= (from_yaml | .foo = \(dqcat\(dq | to_yaml)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]: \f[R]|
  foo: cat
  baz: dog
.EE
.SS Update a single line encoded yaml string
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] \(aqfoo: bar\(aq
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a |= (from_yaml | .foo = \(dqcat\(dq | to_yaml)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] \(aqfoo: cat\(aq
.EE
.SS Encode array of scalars as csv string
Scalars are strings, numbers and booleans.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] thing1,thing2
\f[B]\-\f[R] true
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3.40
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq\(atcsv\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cat,\(dqthing1,thing2\(dq,true,3.40
.EE
.SS Encode array of arrays as csv string
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] thing1,thing2
  \f[B]\-\f[R] true
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 3.40
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] dog
  \f[B]\-\f[R] thing3
  \f[B]\-\f[R] false
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 12
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq\(atcsv\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cat,\(dqthing1,thing2\(dq,true,3.40
dog,thing3,false,12
.EE
.SS Encode array of arrays as tsv string
Scalars are strings, numbers and booleans.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] thing1,thing2
  \f[B]\-\f[R] true
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 3.40
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] dog
  \f[B]\-\f[R] thing3
  \f[B]\-\f[R] false
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 12
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq\(attsv\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cat thing1,thing2   true    3.40
dog thing3  false   12
.EE
.SS Encode value as xml string
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  cool\f[B]:\f[R]
    foo\f[B]:\f[R] bar
    +\(atid\f[B]:\f[R] hi
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a | to_xml\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
<cool id=\(dqhi\(dq>
  <foo>bar</foo>
</cool>
.EE
.SS Encode value as xml string on a single line
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  cool\f[B]:\f[R]
    foo\f[B]:\f[R] bar
    +\(atid\f[B]:\f[R] hi
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a | \(atxml\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
<cool id=\(dqhi\(dq><foo>bar</foo></cool>
.EE
.SS Encode value as xml string with custom indentation
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  cool\f[B]:\f[R]
    foo\f[B]:\f[R] bar
    +\(atid\f[B]:\f[R] hi
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq{\(dqcat\(dq: .a | to_xml(1)}\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cat\f[B]: \f[R]|
  <cool id=\(dqhi\(dq>
   <foo>bar</foo>
  </cool>
.EE
.SS Decode a xml encoded string
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] <foo>bar</foo>
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.b = (.a | from_xml)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] <foo>bar</foo>
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  foo\f[B]:\f[R] bar
.EE
.SS Encode a string to base64
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
coolData\f[B]:\f[R] a special string
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.coolData | \(atbase64\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
YSBzcGVjaWFsIHN0cmluZw==
.EE
.SS Encode a yaml document to base64
Pipe through \(atyaml first to convert to a string, then use \(atbase64
to encode it.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq\(atyaml | \(atbase64\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
YTogYXBwbGUK
.EE
.SS Encode a string to uri
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
coolData\f[B]:\f[R] this has & special () characters *
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.coolData | \(aturi\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
this+has+%26+special+%28%29+characters+%2A
.EE
.SS Decode a URI to a string
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
this+has+%26+special+%28%29+characters+%2A
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq\(aturid\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
this has & special () characters *
.EE
.SS Encode a string to sh
Sh/Bash friendly string
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
coolData\f[B]:\f[R] strings with spaces and a \(aqquote\(aq
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.coolData | \(atsh\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
strings\(aq with spaces and a \(aq\(rs\(aqquote\(rs\(aq
.EE
.SS Decode a base64 encoded string
Decoded data is assumed to be a string.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
coolData\f[B]:\f[R] V29ya3Mgd2l0aCBVVEYtMTYg8J+Yig==
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.coolData | \(atbase64d\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Works with UTF\-16 😊
.EE
.SS Decode a base64 encoded yaml document
Pipe through \f[CR]from_yaml\f[R] to parse the decoded base64 string as
a yaml document.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
coolData\f[B]:\f[R] YTogYXBwbGUK
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.coolData |= (\(atbase64d | from_yaml)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
coolData\f[B]:\f[R]
  a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.SH Entries
Similar to the same named functions in \f[CR]jq\f[R] these functions
convert to/from an object and an array of key\-value pairs.
This is most useful for performing operations on keys of maps.
.PP
Use \f[CR]with_entries(op)\f[R] as a syntactic sugar for doing
\f[CR]to_entries | op | from_entries\f[R].
.SS to_entries Map
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 1
b\f[B]:\f[R] 2
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqto_entries\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] key\f[B]:\f[R] a
  value\f[B]:\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] key\f[B]:\f[R] b
  value\f[B]:\f[R] 2
.EE
.SS to_entries Array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a
\f[B]\-\f[R] b
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqto_entries\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] key\f[B]:\f[R] 0
  value\f[B]:\f[R] a
\f[B]\-\f[R] key\f[B]:\f[R] 1
  value\f[B]:\f[R] b
.EE
.SS to_entries null
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
null
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqto_entries\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
.EE
.SS from_entries map
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 1
b\f[B]:\f[R] 2
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqto_entries | from_entries\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 1
b\f[B]:\f[R] 2
.EE
.SS from_entries with numeric key indices
from_entries always creates a map, even for numeric keys
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a
\f[B]\-\f[R] b
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqto_entries | from_entries\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
0\f[B]:\f[R] a
1\f[B]:\f[R] b
.EE
.SS Use with_entries to update keys
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 1
b\f[B]:\f[R] 2
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqwith_entries(.key |= \(dqKEY_\(dq + .)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
KEY_a\f[B]:\f[R] 1
KEY_b\f[B]:\f[R] 2
.EE
.SS Use with_entries to update keys recursively
We use (..
| select(tag=\(lqmap\(rq)) to find all the maps in the doc, then |= to
update each one of those maps.
In the update, with_entries is used.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 1
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  b_a\f[B]:\f[R] nested
  b_b\f[B]:\f[R] thing
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq(.. | select(tag==\(dq!!map\(dq)) |= with_entries(.key |= \(dqKEY_\(dq + .)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
KEY_a\f[B]:\f[R] 1
KEY_b\f[B]:\f[R]
  KEY_b_a\f[B]:\f[R] nested
  KEY_b_b\f[B]:\f[R] thing
.EE
.SS Custom sort map keys
Use to_entries to convert to an array of key/value pairs, sort the array
using sort/sort_by/etc, and convert it back.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 1
c\f[B]:\f[R] 3
b\f[B]:\f[R] 2
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqto_entries | sort_by(.key) | reverse | from_entries\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
c\f[B]:\f[R] 3
b\f[B]:\f[R] 2
a\f[B]:\f[R] 1
.EE
.SS Use with_entries to filter the map
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] bird
c\f[B]:\f[R]
  d\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqwith_entries(select(.value | has(\(dqb\(dq)))\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] bird
.EE
.SH Env Variable Operators
These operators are used to handle environment variables usage in
expressions and documents.
While environment variables can, of course, be passed in via your CLI
with string interpolation, this often comes with complex quote escaping
and can be tricky to write and read.
.PP
There are three operators:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]env\f[R] which takes a single environment variable name and parse
the variable as a yaml node (be it a map, array, string, number of
boolean)
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]strenv\f[R] which also takes a single environment variable name,
and always parses the variable as a string.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]envsubst\f[R] which you pipe strings into and it interpolates
environment variables in strings using \c
.UR https://github.com/a8m/envsubst
envsubst
.UE \c
\&.
.SS EnvSubst Options
You can optionally pass envsubst any of the following options:
.IP \(bu 2
nu: NoUnset, this will fail if there are any referenced variables that
are not set
.IP \(bu 2
ne: NoEmpty, this will fail if there are any referenced variables that
are empty
.IP \(bu 2
ff: FailFast, this will abort on the first failure (rather than collect
all the errors)
.PP
E.g: \f[CR]envsubst(ne, ff)\f[R] will fail on the first empty variable.
.PP
See \c
.UR https://github.com/a8m/envsubst#imposing-restrictions
Imposing Restrictions
.UE \c
\ in the \f[CR]envsubst\f[R] documentation for more information, and
below for examples.
.SS Tip
To replace environment variables across all values in a document,
\f[CR]envsubst\f[R] can be used with the recursive descent operator as
follows:
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq(.. | select(tag == \(dq!!str\(dq)) |= envsubst\(aq file.yaml
.EE
.SS Disabling env operators
If required, you can use the \f[CR]\-\-security\-disable\-env\-ops\f[R]
to disable env operations.
.SS Read string environment variable
Running
.IP
.EX
myenv=\(dqcat meow\(dq yq \-\-null\-input \(aq.a = env(myenv)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat meow
.EE
.SS Read boolean environment variable
Running
.IP
.EX
myenv=\(dqtrue\(dq yq \-\-null\-input \(aq.a = env(myenv)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] true
.EE
.SS Read numeric environment variable
Running
.IP
.EX
myenv=\(dq12\(dq yq \-\-null\-input \(aq.a = env(myenv)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 12
.EE
.SS Read yaml environment variable
Running
.IP
.EX
myenv=\(dq{b: fish}\(dq yq \-\-null\-input \(aq.a = env(myenv)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B]{\f[R]b\f[B]:\f[R] fish\f[B]}\f[R]
.EE
.SS Read boolean environment variable as a string
Running
.IP
.EX
myenv=\(dqtrue\(dq yq \-\-null\-input \(aq.a = strenv(myenv)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqtrue\(dq
.EE
.SS Read numeric environment variable as a string
Running
.IP
.EX
myenv=\(dq12\(dq yq \-\-null\-input \(aq.a = strenv(myenv)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq12\(dq
.EE
.SS Dynamically update a path from an environment variable
The env variable can be any valid yq expression.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] dog
    \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
pathEnv=\(dq.a.b[0].name\(dq  valueEnv=\(dqmoo\(dq yq \(aqeval(strenv(pathEnv)) = strenv(valueEnv)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] moo
    \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS Dynamic key lookup with environment variable
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
cat\f[B]:\f[R] meow
dog\f[B]:\f[R] woof
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
myenv=\(dqcat\(dq yq \(aq.[env(myenv)]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
meow
.EE
.SS Replace strings with envsubst
Running
.IP
.EX
myenv=\(dqcat\(dq yq \-\-null\-input \(aq\(dqthe ${myenv} meows\(dq | envsubst\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
the cat meows
.EE
.SS Replace strings with envsubst, missing variables
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq\(dqthe ${myenvnonexisting} meows\(dq | envsubst\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
the  meows
.EE
.SS Replace strings with envsubst(nu), missing variables
(nu) not unset, will fail if there are unset (missing) variables
.PP
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq\(dqthe ${myenvnonexisting} meows\(dq | envsubst(nu)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Error: variable ${myenvnonexisting} not set
.EE
.SS Replace strings with envsubst(ne), missing variables
(ne) not empty, only validates set variables
.PP
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq\(dqthe ${myenvnonexisting} meows\(dq | envsubst(ne)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
the  meows
.EE
.SS Replace strings with envsubst(ne), empty variable
(ne) not empty, will fail if a references variable is empty
.PP
Running
.IP
.EX
myenv=\(dq\(dq yq \-\-null\-input \(aq\(dqthe ${myenv} meows\(dq | envsubst(ne)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Error: variable ${myenv} set but empty
.EE
.SS Replace strings with envsubst, missing variables with defaults
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq\(dqthe ${myenvnonexisting\-dog} meows\(dq | envsubst\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
the dog meows
.EE
.SS Replace strings with envsubst(nu), missing variables with defaults
Having a default specified skips over the missing variable.
.PP
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq\(dqthe ${myenvnonexisting\-dog} meows\(dq | envsubst(nu)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
the dog meows
.EE
.SS Replace strings with envsubst(ne), missing variables with defaults
Fails, because the variable is explicitly set to blank.
.PP
Running
.IP
.EX
myEmptyEnv=\(dq\(dq yq \-\-null\-input \(aq\(dqthe ${myEmptyEnv\-dog} meows\(dq | envsubst(ne)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Error: variable ${myEmptyEnv} set but empty
.EE
.SS Replace string environment variable in document
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
v\f[B]:\f[R] ${myenv}
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
myenv=\(dqcat meow\(dq yq \(aq.v |= envsubst\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
v\f[B]:\f[R] cat meow
.EE
.SS (Default) Return all envsubst errors
By default, all errors are returned at once.
.PP
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq\(dqthe ${notThere} ${alsoNotThere}\(dq | envsubst(nu)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Error: variable ${notThere} not set
variable ${alsoNotThere} not set
.EE
.SS Fail fast, return the first envsubst error (and abort)
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq\(dqthe ${notThere} ${alsoNotThere}\(dq | envsubst(nu,ff)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Error: variable ${notThere} not set
.EE
.SS env() operation fails when security is enabled
Use \f[CR]\-\-security\-disable\-env\-ops\f[R] to disable env operations
for security.
.PP
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aqenv(\(dqMYENV\(dq)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Error: env operations have been disabled
.EE
.SS strenv() operation fails when security is enabled
Use \f[CR]\-\-security\-disable\-env\-ops\f[R] to disable env operations
for security.
.PP
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aqstrenv(\(dqMYENV\(dq)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Error: env operations have been disabled
.EE
.SS envsubst() operation fails when security is enabled
Use \f[CR]\-\-security\-disable\-env\-ops\f[R] to disable env operations
for security.
.PP
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq\(dqvalue: ${MYENV}\(dq | envsubst\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Error: env operations have been disabled
.EE
.SH Equals / Not Equals
This is a boolean operator that will return \f[CR]true\f[R] if the LHS
is equal to the RHS and \f[CR]false\f[R] otherwise.
.IP
.EX
\&.a == .b
.EE
.PP
It is most often used with the select operator to find particular nodes:
.IP
.EX
select(.a == .b)
.EE
.PP
The not equals \f[CR]!=\f[R] operator returns \f[CR]false\f[R] if the
LHS is equal to the RHS.
.SS Related Operators
.IP \(bu 2
comparison (\f[CR]>=\f[R], \f[CR]<\f[R] etc) operators \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/compare
here
.UE \c
.IP \(bu 2
boolean operators (\f[CR]and\f[R], \f[CR]or\f[R], \f[CR]any\f[R] etc) \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/boolean-operators
here
.UE \c
.IP \(bu 2
select operator \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/select
here
.UE \c
.SS Match string
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] goat
\f[B]\-\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | (. == \(dq*at\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
true
false
.EE
.SS Don\(cqt match string
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] goat
\f[B]\-\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | (. != \(dq*at\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
false
false
true
.EE
.SS Match number
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
\f[B]\-\f[R] 4
\f[B]\-\f[R] 5
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | (. == 4)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
false
true
false
.EE
.SS Don\(cqt match number
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
\f[B]\-\f[R] 4
\f[B]\-\f[R] 5
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | (. != 4)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
false
true
.EE
.SS Match nulls
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aqnull == \(ti\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
.EE
.SS Non existent key doesn\(cqt equal a value
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqselect(.b != \(dqthing\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.SS Two non existent keys are equal
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqselect(.b == .c)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.SH Error
Use this operation to short\-circuit expressions.
Useful for validation.
.SS Validate a particular value
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] hello
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqselect(.a == \(dqhowdy\(dq) or error(\(dq.a [\(dq + .a + \(dq] is not howdy!\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Error: .a [hello] is not howdy!
.EE
.SS Validate the environment variable is a number \- invalid
Running
.IP
.EX
numberOfCats=\(dqplease\(dq yq \-\-null\-input \(aqenv(numberOfCats) | select(tag == \(dq!!int\(dq) or error(\(dqnumberOfCats is not a number :(\(dq)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Error: numberOfCats is not a number :\f[B](\f[R]
.EE
.SS Validate the environment variable is a number \- valid
\f[CR]with\f[R] can be a convenient way of encapsulating validation.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
name\f[B]:\f[R] Bob
favouriteAnimal\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
numberOfCats=\(dq3\(dq yq \(aq
    with(env(numberOfCats); select(tag == \(dq!!int\(dq) or error(\(dqnumberOfCats is not a number :(\(dq)) | 
    .numPets = env(numberOfCats)
\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
name\f[B]:\f[R] Bob
favouriteAnimal\f[B]:\f[R] cat
numPets\f[B]:\f[R] 3
.EE
.SH Eval
Use \f[CR]eval\f[R] to dynamically process an expression \- for instance
from an environment variable.
.PP
\f[CR]eval\f[R] takes a single argument, and evaluates that as a
\f[CR]yq\f[R] expression.
Any valid expression can be used, be it a path
\f[CR].a.b.c | select(. == \(dqcat\(dq)\f[R], or an update
\f[CR].a.b.c = \(dqgogo\(dq\f[R].
.PP
Tip: This can be a useful way to parameterise complex scripts.
.SS Dynamically evaluate a path
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
pathExp\f[B]:\f[R] .a.b[] | select(.name == \(dqcat\(dq)
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] dog
    \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqeval(.pathExp)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
name\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS Dynamically update a path from an environment variable
The env variable can be any valid yq expression.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] dog
    \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
pathEnv=\(dq.a.b[0].name\(dq  valueEnv=\(dqmoo\(dq yq \(aqeval(strenv(pathEnv)) = strenv(valueEnv)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] moo
    \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SH File Operators
File operators are most often used with merge when needing to merge
specific files together.
Note that when doing this, you will need to use \f[CR]eval\-all\f[R] to
ensure all yaml documents are loaded into memory before performing the
merge (as opposed to \f[CR]eval\f[R] which runs the expression once per
document).
.PP
Note that the \f[CR]fileIndex\f[R] operator has a short alias of
\f[CR]fi\f[R].
.SS Merging files
Note the use of eval\-all to ensure all documents are loaded into
memory.
.IP
.EX
yq eval\-all \(aqselect(fi == 0) * select(filename == \(dqfile2.yaml\(dq)\(aq file1.yaml file2.yaml
.EE
.SS Get filename
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfilename\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
sample.yml
.EE
.SS Get file index
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfile_index\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
0
.EE
.SS Get file indices of multiple documents
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
And another sample another.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq eval\-all \(aqfile_index\(aq sample.yml another.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
0
1
.EE
.SS Get file index alias
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfi\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
0
.EE
.SH Filter
Filters an array (or map values) by the expression given.
Equivalent to doing \f[CR]map(select(exp))\f[R].
.SS Filter array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfilter(. < 3)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
.EE
.SS Filter map values
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
c\f[B]:\f[R]
  things\f[B]:\f[R] cool
  frog\f[B]:\f[R] yes
d\f[B]:\f[R]
  things\f[B]:\f[R] hot
  frog\f[B]:\f[R] false
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfilter(.things == \(dqcool\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] things\f[B]:\f[R] cool
  frog\f[B]:\f[R] yes
.EE
.SH First
Returns the first matching element in an array, or first matching value
in a map.
.PP
Can be given an expression to match with, otherwise will just return the
first.
.SS First matching element from array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfirst(.a == \(dqcat\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS First matching element from array with multiple matches
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
  b\f[B]:\f[R] firstCat
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
  b\f[B]:\f[R] secondCat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfirst(.a == \(dqcat\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] firstCat
.EE
.SS First matching element from array with numeric condition
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] 10
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] 100
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] 101
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfirst(.a > 50)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 100
.EE
.SS First matching element from array with boolean condition
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] false
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] true
  b\f[B]:\f[R] firstTrue
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] false
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] true
  b\f[B]:\f[R] secondTrue
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfirst(.a == true)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] true
b\f[B]:\f[R] firstTrue
.EE
.SS First matching element from array with null values
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] null
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfirst(.a != null)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS First matching element from array with complex condition
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] dog
  b\f[B]:\f[R] 7
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
  b\f[B]:\f[R] 3
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
  b\f[B]:\f[R] 5
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfirst(.b > 4 and .b < 6)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
b\f[B]:\f[R] 5
.EE
.SS First matching element from map
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
x\f[B]:\f[R]
  a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
y\f[B]:\f[R]
  a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
z\f[B]:\f[R]
  a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfirst(.a == \(dqcat\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS First matching element from map with numeric condition
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
x\f[B]:\f[R]
  a\f[B]:\f[R] 10
y\f[B]:\f[R]
  a\f[B]:\f[R] 100
z\f[B]:\f[R]
  a\f[B]:\f[R] 101
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfirst(.a > 50)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 100
.EE
.SS First matching element from nested structure
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
items\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.items | first(.a == \(dqcat\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS First matching element with no matches
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfirst(.a == \(dqdog\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
.EE
.SS First matching element from empty array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfirst(.a == \(dqcat\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
.EE
.SS First matching element from scalar node
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
hello
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfirst(. == \(dqhello\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
.EE
.SS First matching element from null node
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
null
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfirst(. == \(dqhello\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
.EE
.SS First matching element with string condition
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfirst(.a | test(\(dq\(hac\(dq))\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS First matching element with length condition
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] hi
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] hello
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] world
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfirst(.a | length > 4)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] hello
.EE
.SS First matching element from array of strings
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] banana
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfirst(. == \(dqcat\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cat
.EE
.SS First matching element from array of numbers
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 10
\f[B]\-\f[R] 100
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfirst(. > 50)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
100
.EE
.SS First element with no filter from array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 10
\f[B]\-\f[R] 100
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfirst\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
10
.EE
.SS First element with no filter from array of maps
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] 10
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] 100
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqfirst\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 10
.EE
.SH Flatten
This recursively flattens arrays.
.SS Flatten
Recursively flattens all arrays
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] 3
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqflatten\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
.EE
.SS Flatten with depth of one
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] 3
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqflatten(1)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] 3
.EE
.SS Flatten empty array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqflatten\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.SS Flatten array of objects
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] bar
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] baz
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqflatten\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] bar
\f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] baz
.EE
.SH Group By
This is used to group items in an array by an expression.
.SS Group by field
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] 1
  bar\f[B]:\f[R] 10
\f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] 3
  bar\f[B]:\f[R] 100
\f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] 1
  bar\f[B]:\f[R] 1
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqgroup_by(.foo)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] 1
    bar\f[B]:\f[R] 10
  \f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] 1
    bar\f[B]:\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] 3
    bar\f[B]:\f[R] 100
.EE
.SS Group by field, with nulls
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat\f[B]:\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] 1
  bar\f[B]:\f[R] 10
\f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] 3
  bar\f[B]:\f[R] 100
\f[B]\-\f[R] no\f[B]:\f[R] foo for you
\f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] 1
  bar\f[B]:\f[R] 1
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqgroup_by(.foo)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] cat\f[B]:\f[R] dog
  \f[B]\-\f[R] no\f[B]:\f[R] foo for you
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] 1
    bar\f[B]:\f[R] 10
  \f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] 1
    bar\f[B]:\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] 3
    bar\f[B]:\f[R] 100
.EE
.SH Has
This operation returns true if the key exists in a map (or index in an
array), false otherwise.
.SS Has map key
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] yes
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] \(ti
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R]
\f[B]\-\f[R] b\f[B]:\f[R] nope
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | has(\(dqa\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
true
true
false
.EE
.SS Select, checking for existence of deep paths
Simply pipe in parent expressions into \f[CR]has\f[R]
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R]
    b\f[B]:\f[R]
      c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R]
    b\f[B]:\f[R]
      d\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | select(.a.b | has(\(dqc\(dq))\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS Has array index
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]1\f[B]]\f[R]
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]1\f[B],\f[R] 2\f[B]]\f[R]
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]1\f[B],\f[R] null\f[B]]\f[R]
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]1\f[B],\f[R] 2\f[B],\f[R] 3\f[B]]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | has(1)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
false
false
true
true
true
.EE
.SH Keys
Use the \f[CR]keys\f[R] operator to return map keys or array indices.
.SS Map keys
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
dog\f[B]:\f[R] woof
cat\f[B]:\f[R] meow
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqkeys\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS Array keys
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] apple
\f[B]\-\f[R] banana
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqkeys\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 0
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
.EE
.SS Retrieve array key
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[1] | key\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
1
.EE
.SS Retrieve map key
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] thing
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a | key\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a
.EE
.SS No key
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{}\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqkey\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
.EE
.SS Update map key
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  x\f[B]:\f[R] 3
  y\f[B]:\f[R] 4
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq(.a.x | key) = \(dqmeow\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  meow\f[B]:\f[R] 3
  y\f[B]:\f[R] 4
.EE
.SS Get comment from map key
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
\f[I]  # comment on key\f[R]
  x\f[B]:\f[R] 3
  y\f[B]:\f[R] 4
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.x | key | headComment\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
comment on key
.EE
.SS Check node is a key
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  c\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq[... | { \(dqp\(dq: path | join(\(dq.\(dq), \(dqisKey\(dq: is_key, \(dqtag\(dq: tag }]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] p\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
  isKey\f[B]:\f[R] false
  tag\f[B]:\f[R] \(aq!!map\(aq
\f[B]\-\f[R] p\f[B]:\f[R] a
  isKey\f[B]:\f[R] true
  tag\f[B]:\f[R] \(aq!!str\(aq
\f[B]\-\f[R] p\f[B]:\f[R] a
  isKey\f[B]:\f[R] false
  tag\f[B]:\f[R] \(aq!!map\(aq
\f[B]\-\f[R] p\f[B]:\f[R] a.b
  isKey\f[B]:\f[R] true
  tag\f[B]:\f[R] \(aq!!str\(aq
\f[B]\-\f[R] p\f[B]:\f[R] a.b
  isKey\f[B]:\f[R] false
  tag\f[B]:\f[R] \(aq!!seq\(aq
\f[B]\-\f[R] p\f[B]:\f[R] a.b.0
  isKey\f[B]:\f[R] false
  tag\f[B]:\f[R] \(aq!!str\(aq
\f[B]\-\f[R] p\f[B]:\f[R] a.c
  isKey\f[B]:\f[R] true
  tag\f[B]:\f[R] \(aq!!str\(aq
\f[B]\-\f[R] p\f[B]:\f[R] a.c
  isKey\f[B]:\f[R] false
  tag\f[B]:\f[R] \(aq!!str\(aq
.EE
.SH Kind
The \f[CR]kind\f[R] operator identifies the type of a node as either
\f[CR]scalar\f[R], \f[CR]map\f[R], or \f[CR]seq\f[R].
.PP
This can be used for filtering or transforming nodes based on their
type.
.PP
Note that \f[CR]null\f[R] values are treated as \f[CR]scalar\f[R].
.SS Get kind
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] 5
c\f[B]:\f[R] 3.2
e\f[B]:\f[R] true
f\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
g\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B]{}\f[R]
h\f[B]:\f[R] null
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.. | kind\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
map
scalar
scalar
scalar
scalar
seq
map
scalar
.EE
.SS Get kind, ignores custom tags
Unlike tag, kind is not affected by custom tags.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !!thing cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] !!foo \f[B]{}\f[R]
c\f[B]:\f[R] !!bar \f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.. | kind\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
map
scalar
map
seq
.EE
.SS Add comments only to scalars
An example of how you can use kind
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] 5
  c\f[B]:\f[R] 3.2
e\f[B]:\f[R] true
f\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
g\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B]{}\f[R]
h\f[B]:\f[R] null
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq(.. | select(kind == \(dqscalar\(dq)) line_comment = \(dqthis is a scalar\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] 5\f[I] # this is a scalar\f[R]
  c\f[B]:\f[R] 3.2\f[I] # this is a scalar\f[R]
e\f[B]:\f[R] true\f[I] # this is a scalar\f[R]
f\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
g\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B]{}\f[R]
h\f[B]:\f[R] null\f[I] # this is a scalar\f[R]
.EE
.SH Length
Returns the lengths of the nodes.
Length is defined according to the type of the node.
.SS String length
returns length of string
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a | length\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
3
.EE
.SS null length
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] null
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a | length\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
0
.EE
.SS Map length
returns number of entries
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
c\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqlength\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
2
.EE
.SS Array length
returns number of elements
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] 4
\f[B]\-\f[R] 6
\f[B]\-\f[R] 8
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqlength\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
4
.EE
.SH Line
Returns the line of the matching node.
Starts from 1, 0 indicates there was no line data.
.SS Returns line of \f[I]value\f[R] node
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.b | line\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
3
.EE
.SS Returns line of \f[I]key\f[R] node
Pipe through the key operator to get the line of the key
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.b | key | line\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
2
.EE
.SS First line is 1
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a | line\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
1
.EE
.SS No line data is 0
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq{\(dqa\(dq: \(dqnew entry\(dq} | line\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
0
.EE
.SH Load
The load operators allows you to load in content from another file.
.PP
Note that you can use string operators like \f[CR]+\f[R] and
\f[CR]sub\f[R] to modify the value in the yaml file to a path that
exists in your system.
.PP
You can load files of the following supported types:
.PP
.TS
tab(@);
l l.
T{
Format
T}@T{
Load Operator
T}
_
T{
Yaml
T}@T{
load
T}
T{
XML
T}@T{
load_xml
T}
T{
Properties
T}@T{
load_props
T}
T{
Plain String
T}@T{
load_str
T}
T{
Base64
T}@T{
load_base64
T}
.TE
.PP
Note that load_base64 only works for base64 encoded utf\-8 strings.
.SS Samples files for tests:
.SS yaml
\f[CR]../../examples/thing.yml\f[R]:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] apple is included
b\f[B]:\f[R] cool
.EE
.SS xml
\f[CR]small.xml\f[R]:
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]this\f[R]>is some xml</\f[B]this\f[R]>
.EE
.SS properties
\f[CR]small.properties\f[R]:
.IP
.EX
this.is = a properties file
.EE
.SS base64
\f[CR]base64.txt\f[R]:
.IP
.EX
bXkgc2VjcmV0IGNoaWxsaSByZWNpcGUgaXMuLi4u
.EE
.SS Disabling file operators
If required, you can use the \f[CR]\-\-security\-disable\-file\-ops\f[R]
to disable file operations.
.SS Simple example
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
myFile\f[B]:\f[R] ../../examples/thing.yml
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqload(.myFile)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] apple is included
b\f[B]:\f[R] cool.
.EE
.SS Replace node with referenced file
Note that you can modify the filename in the load operator if needed.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
something\f[B]:\f[R]
  file\f[B]:\f[R] thing.yml
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.something |= load(\(dq../../examples/\(dq + .file)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
something\f[B]:\f[R]
  a\f[B]:\f[R] apple is included
  b\f[B]:\f[R] cool.
.EE
.SS Replace \f[I]all\f[R] nodes with referenced file
Recursively match all the nodes (\f[CR]..\f[R]) and then filter the ones
that have a `file' attribute.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
something\f[B]:\f[R]
  file\f[B]:\f[R] thing.yml
over\f[B]:\f[R]
  here\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] file\f[B]:\f[R] thing.yml
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq(.. | select(has(\(dqfile\(dq))) |= load(\(dq../../examples/\(dq + .file)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
something\f[B]:\f[R]
  a\f[B]:\f[R] apple is included
  b\f[B]:\f[R] cool.
over\f[B]:\f[R]
  here\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple is included
      b\f[B]:\f[R] cool.
.EE
.SS Replace node with referenced file as string
This will work for any text based file
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
something\f[B]:\f[R]
  file\f[B]:\f[R] thing.yml
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
