.SS Merge, deeply merging arrays
Merging arrays deeply means arrays are merged like objects, with indices
as their key.
In this case, we merge the first item in the array and do nothing with
the second.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] fred
    age\f[B]:\f[R] 12
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] bob
    age\f[B]:\f[R] 32
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] fred
    age\f[B]:\f[R] 34
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a *d .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] fred
  age\f[B]:\f[R] 34
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] bob
  age\f[B]:\f[R] 32
.EE
.SS Merge arrays of objects together, matching on a key
This is a fairly complex expression \- you can use it as is by providing
the environment variables as seen in the example below.
.PP
It merges in the array provided in the second file into the first \-
matching on equal keys.
.PP
Explanation:
.PP
The approach, at a high level, is to reduce into a merged map (keyed by
the unique key) and then convert that back into an array.
.PP
First the expression will create a map from the arrays keyed by the
idPath, the unique field we want to merge by.
The reduce operator is merging `({}; .
* $item )', so array elements with the matching key will be merged
together.
.PP
Next, we convert the map back to an array, using reduce again,
concatenating all the map values together.
.PP
Finally, we set the result of the merged array back into the first doc.
.PP
Thanks Kev from \c
.UR https://stackoverflow.com/a/70109529/1168223
stackoverflow
.UE \c
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
myArray\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
    b\f[B]:\f[R] appleB
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] kiwi
    b\f[B]:\f[R] kiwiB
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
    b\f[B]:\f[R] bananaB
something\f[B]:\f[R] else
.EE
.PP
And another sample another.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
newArray\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
    c\f[B]:\f[R] bananaC
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
    b\f[B]:\f[R] appleB2
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] dingo
    c\f[B]:\f[R] dingoC
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
idPath=\(dq.a\(dq  originalPath=\(dq.myArray\(dq  otherPath=\(dq.newArray\(dq yq eval\-all \(aq
(
  (( (eval(strenv(originalPath)) + eval(strenv(otherPath)))  | .[] | {(eval(strenv(idPath))):  .}) as $item ireduce ({}; . * $item )) as $uniqueMap
  | ( $uniqueMap  | to_entries | .[]) as $item ireduce([]; . + $item.value)
) as $mergedArray
| select(fi == 0) | (eval(strenv(originalPath))) = $mergedArray
\(aq sample.yml another.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
myArray\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
    b\f[B]:\f[R] appleB2
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] kiwi
    b\f[B]:\f[R] kiwiB
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
    b\f[B]:\f[R] bananaB
    c\f[B]:\f[R] bananaC
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] dingo
    c\f[B]:\f[R] dingoC
something\f[B]:\f[R] else
.EE
.SS Merge to prefix an element
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq. * {\(dqa\(dq: {\(dqc\(dq: .a}}\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.SS Merge with simple aliases
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] &cat
  c\f[B]:\f[R] frog
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  f\f[B]:\f[R] *cat
c\f[B]:\f[R]
  g\f[B]:\f[R] thongs
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.c * .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
g\f[B]:\f[R] thongs
f\f[B]:\f[R] *cat
.EE
.SS Merge copies anchor names
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  c\f[B]:\f[R] &cat frog
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  f\f[B]:\f[R] *cat
c\f[B]:\f[R]
  g\f[B]:\f[R] thongs
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.c * .a\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
g\f[B]:\f[R] thongs
c\f[B]:\f[R] &cat frog
.EE
.SS Merge with merge anchors
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
foo\f[B]:\f[R] &foo
  a\f[B]:\f[R] foo_a
  thing\f[B]:\f[R] foo_thing
  c\f[B]:\f[R] foo_c
bar\f[B]:\f[R] &bar
  b\f[B]:\f[R] bar_b
  thing\f[B]:\f[R] bar_thing
  c\f[B]:\f[R] bar_c
foobarList\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] foobarList_b
  !!merge <<\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] *foo
    \f[B]\-\f[R] *bar
  c\f[B]:\f[R] foobarList_c
foobar\f[B]:\f[R]
  c\f[B]:\f[R] foobar_c
  !!merge <<\f[B]:\f[R] *foo
  thing\f[B]:\f[R] foobar_thing
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.foobar * .foobarList\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
c\f[B]:\f[R] foobarList_c
!!merge <<\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] *foo
  \f[B]\-\f[R] *bar
thing\f[B]:\f[R] foobar_thing
b\f[B]:\f[R] foobarList_b
.EE
.SS Custom types: that are really numbers
When custom tags are encountered, yq will try to decode the underlying
type.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !horse 2
b\f[B]:\f[R] !goat 3
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a = .a * .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !horse 6
b\f[B]:\f[R] !goat 3
.EE
.SS Custom types: that are really maps
Custom tags will be maintained.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !horse
  cat\f[B]:\f[R] meow
b\f[B]:\f[R] !goat
  dog\f[B]:\f[R] woof
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a = .a * .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !horse
  cat\f[B]:\f[R] meow
  dog\f[B]:\f[R] woof
b\f[B]:\f[R] !goat
  dog\f[B]:\f[R] woof
.EE
.SS Custom types: clobber tags
Use the \f[CR]c\f[R] option to clobber custom tags.
Note that the second tag is now used.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !horse
  cat\f[B]:\f[R] meow
b\f[B]:\f[R] !goat
  dog\f[B]:\f[R] woof
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a *=c .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !goat
  cat\f[B]:\f[R] meow
  dog\f[B]:\f[R] woof
b\f[B]:\f[R] !goat
  dog\f[B]:\f[R] woof
.EE
.SS Merging a null with a map
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aqnull * {\(dqsome\(dq: \(dqthing\(dq}\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
some\f[B]:\f[R] thing
.EE
.SS Merging a map with null
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq{\(dqsome\(dq: \(dqthing\(dq} * null\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
some\f[B]:\f[R] thing
.EE
.SS Merging a null with an array
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aqnull * [\(dqsome\(dq]\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] some
.EE
.SS Merging an array with null
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq[\(dqsome\(dq] * null\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] some
.EE
.SH Omit
Works like \f[CR]pick\f[R], but instead you specify the keys/indices
that you \f[I]don\(cqt\f[R] want included.
.SS Omit keys from map
Note that non existent keys are skipped.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
myMap\f[B]:\f[R]
  cat\f[B]:\f[R] meow
  dog\f[B]:\f[R] bark
  thing\f[B]:\f[R] hamster
  hamster\f[B]:\f[R] squeak
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.myMap |= omit([\(dqhamster\(dq, \(dqcat\(dq, \(dqgoat\(dq])\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
myMap\f[B]:\f[R]
  dog\f[B]:\f[R] bark
  thing\f[B]:\f[R] hamster
.EE
.SS Omit indices from array
Note that non existent indices are skipped.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] leopard
\f[B]\-\f[R] lion
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqomit([2, 0, 734, \-5])\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] leopard
.EE
.SH Parent
Parent simply returns the parent nodes of the matching nodes.
.SS Simple example
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  nested\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.nested | parent\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
nested\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS Parent of nested matches
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  fruit\f[B]:\f[R] apple
  name\f[B]:\f[R] bob
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  fruit\f[B]:\f[R] banana
  name\f[B]:\f[R] sam
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.. | select(. == \(dqbanana\(dq) | parent\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
fruit\f[B]:\f[R] banana
name\f[B]:\f[R] sam
.EE
.SS Get parent attribute
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  fruit\f[B]:\f[R] apple
  name\f[B]:\f[R] bob
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  fruit\f[B]:\f[R] banana
  name\f[B]:\f[R] sam
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.. | select(. == \(dqbanana\(dq) | parent.name\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
sam
.EE
.SS Get parents
Match all parents
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.b.c | parents\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] b\f[B]:\f[R]
    c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R]
    b\f[B]:\f[R]
      c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS Get the top (root) parent
Use negative numbers to get the top parents.
You can think of this as indexing into the `parents' array above
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.b.c | parent(\-1)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS Root
Alias for parent(\-1), returns the top level parent.
This is usually the document node.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.b.c | root\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS N\-th parent
You can optionally supply the number of levels to go up for the parent,
the default being 1.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.b.c | parent(2)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS N\-th parent \- another level
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.b.c | parent(3)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS N\-th negative
Similarly, use negative numbers to index backwards from the parents
array
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.b.c | parent(\-2)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  c\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS No parent
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{}\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqparent\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
.EE
.SH Path
The \f[CR]path\f[R] operator can be used to get the traversal paths of
matching nodes in an expression.
The path is returned as an array, which if traversed in order will lead
to the matching node.
.PP
You can get the key/index of matching nodes by using the \f[CR]path\f[R]
operator to return the path array then piping that through
\f[CR].[\-1]\f[R] to get the last element of that array, the key.
.PP
Use \f[CR]setpath\f[R] to set a value to the path array returned by
\f[CR]path\f[R], and similarly \f[CR]delpaths\f[R] for an array of path
arrays.
.SS Map path
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.b | path\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a
\f[B]\-\f[R] b
.EE
.SS Get map key
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.b | path | .[\-1]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
b
.EE
.SS Array path
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.[] | select(. == \(dqdog\(dq) | path\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
.EE
.SS Get array index
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.[] | select(. == \(dqdog\(dq) | path | .[\-1]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
1
.EE
.SS Print path and value
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] dog
  \f[B]\-\f[R] frog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a[] | select(. == \(dq*og\(dq) | [{\(dqpath\(dq:path, \(dqvalue\(dq:.}]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] path\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] a
    \f[B]\-\f[R] 1
  value\f[B]:\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] path\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] a
    \f[B]\-\f[R] 2
  value\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.SS Set path
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqsetpath([\(dqa\(dq, \(dqb\(dq]; \(dqthings\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] things
.EE
.SS Set on empty document
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aqsetpath([\(dqa\(dq, \(dqb\(dq]; \(dqthings\(dq)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] things
.EE
.SS Set path to prune deep paths
Like pick but recursive.
This uses \f[CR]ireduce\f[R] to deeply set the selected paths into an
empty object.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX

parentA\f[B]:\f[R] bob
parentB\f[B]:\f[R]
  child1\f[B]:\f[R] i am child1
  child2\f[B]:\f[R] i am child2
parentC\f[B]:\f[R]
  child1\f[B]:\f[R] me child1
  child2\f[B]:\f[R] me child2
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq(.parentB.child2, .parentC.child1) as $i
  ireduce({}; setpath($i | path; $i))\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
parentB\f[B]:\f[R]
  child2\f[B]:\f[R] i am child2
parentC\f[B]:\f[R]
  child1\f[B]:\f[R] me child1
.EE
.SS Set array path
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] frog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqsetpath([\(dqa\(dq, 0]; \(dqthings\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] things
  \f[B]\-\f[R] frog
.EE
.SS Set array path empty
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aqsetpath([\(dqa\(dq, 0]; \(dqthings\(dq)\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] things
.EE
.SS Delete path
Notice delpaths takes an \f[I]array\f[R] of paths.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] cat
  c\f[B]:\f[R] dog
  d\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqdelpaths([[\(dqa\(dq, \(dqc\(dq], [\(dqa\(dq, \(dqd\(dq]])\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS Delete array path
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] frog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqdelpaths([[\(dqa\(dq, 0]])\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] frog
.EE
.SS Delete \- wrong parameter
delpaths does not work with a single path array
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] frog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqdelpaths([\(dqa\(dq, 0])\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Error: DELPATHS: expected entry [0] to be a sequence, but its a !!str. Note that delpaths takes an array of path arrays, e.g. [[\(dqa\(dq, \(dqb\(dq]]
.EE
.SH Pick
Filter a map by the specified list of keys.
Map is returned with the key in the order of the pick list.
.PP
Similarly, filter an array by the specified list of indices.
.SS Pick keys from map
Note that the order of the keys matches the pick order and non existent
keys are skipped.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
myMap\f[B]:\f[R]
  cat\f[B]:\f[R] meow
  dog\f[B]:\f[R] bark
  thing\f[B]:\f[R] hamster
  hamster\f[B]:\f[R] squeak
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.myMap |= pick([\(dqhamster\(dq, \(dqcat\(dq, \(dqgoat\(dq])\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
myMap\f[B]:\f[R]
  hamster\f[B]:\f[R] squeak
  cat\f[B]:\f[R] meow
.EE
.SS Pick keys from map, included all the keys
We create a map of the picked keys plus all the current keys, and run
that through unique
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
myMap\f[B]:\f[R]
  cat\f[B]:\f[R] meow
  dog\f[B]:\f[R] bark
  thing\f[B]:\f[R] hamster
  hamster\f[B]:\f[R] squeak
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.myMap |= pick( ([\(dqthing\(dq] + keys) | unique)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
myMap\f[B]:\f[R]
  thing\f[B]:\f[R] hamster
  cat\f[B]:\f[R] meow
  dog\f[B]:\f[R] bark
  hamster\f[B]:\f[R] squeak
.EE
.SS Pick indices from array
Note that the order of the indices matches the pick order and non
existent indices are skipped.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] leopard
\f[B]\-\f[R] lion
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqpick([2, 0, 734, \-5])\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] lion
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
.EE
.SH Pipe
Pipe the results of an expression into another.
Like the bash operator.
.SS Simple Pipe
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a | .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cat
.EE
.SS Multiple updates
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cow
b\f[B]:\f[R] sheep
c\f[B]:\f[R] same
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a = \(dqcat\(dq | .b = \(dqdog\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
c\f[B]:\f[R] same
.EE
.SH Pivot
Emulates the \f[CR]PIVOT\f[R] function supported by several popular
RDBMS systems.
.SS Pivot a sequence of sequences
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] foo
  \f[B]\-\f[R] bar
  \f[B]\-\f[R] baz
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] sis
  \f[B]\-\f[R] boom
  \f[B]\-\f[R] bah
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqpivot\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] foo
  \f[B]\-\f[R] sis
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] bar
  \f[B]\-\f[R] boom
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] baz
  \f[B]\-\f[R] bah
.EE
.SS Pivot sequence of heterogeneous sequences
Missing values are \(lqpadded\(rq to null.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] foo
  \f[B]\-\f[R] bar
  \f[B]\-\f[R] baz
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] sis
  \f[B]\-\f[R] boom
  \f[B]\-\f[R] bah
  \f[B]\-\f[R] blah
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqpivot\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] foo
  \f[B]\-\f[R] sis
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] bar
  \f[B]\-\f[R] boom
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] baz
  \f[B]\-\f[R] bah
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] blah
.EE
.SS Pivot sequence of maps
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] a
  bar\f[B]:\f[R] b
  baz\f[B]:\f[R] c
\f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] x
  bar\f[B]:\f[R] y
  baz\f[B]:\f[R] z
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqpivot\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
foo\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a
  \f[B]\-\f[R] x
bar\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] b
  \f[B]\-\f[R] y
baz\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] c
  \f[B]\-\f[R] z
.EE
.SS Pivot sequence of heterogeneous maps
Missing values are \(lqpadded\(rq to null.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] a
  bar\f[B]:\f[R] b
  baz\f[B]:\f[R] c
\f[B]\-\f[R] foo\f[B]:\f[R] x
  bar\f[B]:\f[R] y
  baz\f[B]:\f[R] z
  what\f[B]:\f[R] ever
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqpivot\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
foo\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a
  \f[B]\-\f[R] x
bar\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] b
  \f[B]\-\f[R] y
baz\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] c
  \f[B]\-\f[R] z
what\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] ever
.EE
.SH Recursive Descent (Glob)
This operator recursively matches (or globs) all children nodes given of
a particular element, including that node itself.
This is most often used to apply a filter recursively against all
matches.
.SS match values form \f[CR]..\f[R]
This will, like the \f[CR]jq\f[R] equivalent, recursively match all
\f[I]value\f[R] nodes.
Use it to find/manipulate particular values.
.PP
For instance to set the \f[CR]style\f[R] of all \f[I]value\f[R] nodes in
a yaml doc, excluding map keys:
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.. style= \(dqflow\(dq\(aq file.yaml
.EE
.SS match values and map keys form \f[CR]...\f[R]
The also includes map keys in the results set.
This is particularly useful in YAML as unlike JSON, map keys can have
their own styling and tags and also use anchors and aliases.
.PP
For instance to set the \f[CR]style\f[R] of all nodes in a yaml doc,
including the map keys:
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq... style= \(dqflow\(dq\(aq file.yaml
.EE
.SS Recurse map (values only)
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq..\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] frog
frog
.EE
.SS Recursively find nodes with keys
Note that this example has wrapped the expression in \f[CR][]\f[R] to
show that there are two matches returned.
You do not have to wrap in \f[CR][]\f[R] in your path expression.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  name\f[B]:\f[R] frog
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    name\f[B]:\f[R] blog
    age\f[B]:\f[R] 12
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq[.. | select(has(\(dqname\(dq))]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] frog
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    name\f[B]:\f[R] blog
    age\f[B]:\f[R] 12
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] blog
  age\f[B]:\f[R] 12
.EE
.SS Recursively find nodes with values
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  nameA\f[B]:\f[R] frog
  b\f[B]:\f[R]
    nameB\f[B]:\f[R] frog
    age\f[B]:\f[R] 12
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.. | select(. == \(dqfrog\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
frog
frog
.EE
.SS Recurse map (values and keys)
Note that the map key appears in the results
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq...\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] frog
a
frog
.EE
.SS Aliases are not traversed
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] &cat
  c\f[B]:\f[R] frog
b\f[B]:\f[R] *cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq[..]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] &cat
    c\f[B]:\f[R] frog
  b\f[B]:\f[R] *cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] &cat
  c\f[B]:\f[R] frog
\f[B]\-\f[R] frog
\f[B]\-\f[R] *cat
.EE
.SS Merge docs are not traversed
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
foo\f[B]:\f[R] &foo
  a\f[B]:\f[R] foo_a
  thing\f[B]:\f[R] foo_thing
  c\f[B]:\f[R] foo_c
bar\f[B]:\f[R] &bar
  b\f[B]:\f[R] bar_b
  thing\f[B]:\f[R] bar_thing
  c\f[B]:\f[R] bar_c
foobarList\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] foobarList_b
  !!merge <<\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] *foo
    \f[B]\-\f[R] *bar
  c\f[B]:\f[R] foobarList_c
foobar\f[B]:\f[R]
  c\f[B]:\f[R] foobar_c
  !!merge <<\f[B]:\f[R] *foo
  thing\f[B]:\f[R] foobar_thing
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.foobar | [..]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] c\f[B]:\f[R] foobar_c
  !!merge <<\f[B]:\f[R] *foo
  thing\f[B]:\f[R] foobar_thing
\f[B]\-\f[R] foobar_c
\f[B]\-\f[R] *foo
\f[B]\-\f[R] foobar_thing
.EE
.SH Reduce
Reduce is a powerful way to process a collection of data into a new
form.
.IP
.EX
<exp> as $<name> ireduce (<init>; <block>)
.EE
.PP
e.g.
.IP
.EX
\&.[] as $item ireduce (0; . + $item)
.EE
.PP
On the LHS we are configuring the collection of items that will be
reduced \f[CR]<exp>\f[R] as well as what each element will be called
\f[CR]$<name>\f[R].
Note that the array has been splatted into its individual elements.
.PP
On the RHS there is \f[CR]<init>\f[R], the starting value of the
accumulator and \f[CR]<block>\f[R], the expression that will update the
accumulator for each element in the collection.
Note that within the block expression, \f[CR].\f[R] will evaluate to the
current value of the accumulator.
.SS yq vs jq syntax
Reduce syntax in \f[CR]yq\f[R] is a little different from \f[CR]jq\f[R]
\- as \f[CR]yq\f[R] (currently) isn\(cqt as sophisticated as
\f[CR]jq\f[R] and its only supports infix notation (e.g.\ a + b, where
the operator is in the middle of the two parameters) \- where as
\f[CR]jq\f[R] uses a mix of infix notation with \f[I]prefix\f[R]
notation (e.g.\ \f[CR]reduce a b\f[R] is like writing \f[CR]+ a b\f[R]).
.PP
To that end, the reduce operator is called \f[CR]ireduce\f[R] for
backwards compatibility if a \f[CR]jq\f[R] like prefix version of
\f[CR]reduce\f[R] is ever added.
.SS Sum numbers
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 10
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] 5
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] as $item ireduce (0; . + $item)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
20
.EE
.SS Merge all yaml files together
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
And another sample another.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq eval\-all \(aq. as $item ireduce ({}; . * $item )\(aq sample.yml another.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.SS Convert an array to an object
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Cathy
  has\f[B]:\f[R] apples
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Bob
  has\f[B]:\f[R] bananas
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] as $item ireduce ({}; .[$item | .name] = ($item | .has) )\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Cathy\f[B]:\f[R] apples
Bob\f[B]:\f[R] bananas
.EE
.SH Reverse
Reverses the order of the items in an array
.SS Reverse
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqreverse\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
.EE
.SS Sort descending by string field
Use sort with reverse to sort in descending order.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqsort_by(.a) | reverse\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.SH Select
Select is used to filter arrays and maps by a boolean expression.
.SS Related Operators
.IP \(bu 2
equals / not equals (\f[CR]==\f[R], \f[CR]!=\f[R]) operators \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/equals
here
.UE \c
.IP \(bu 2
comparison (\f[CR]>=\f[R], \f[CR]<\f[R] etc) operators \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/compare
here
.UE \c
.IP \(bu 2
boolean operators (\f[CR]and\f[R], \f[CR]or\f[R], \f[CR]any\f[R] etc) \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/boolean-operators
here
.UE \c
.SS Select elements from array using wildcard prefix
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] goat
\f[B]\-\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | select(. == \(dq*at\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cat
goat
.EE
.SS Select elements from array using wildcard suffix
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] go\-kart
\f[B]\-\f[R] goat
\f[B]\-\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | select(. == \(dqgo*\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
go\-kart
goat
.EE
.SS Select elements from array using wildcard prefix and suffix
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] ago
\f[B]\-\f[R] go
\f[B]\-\f[R] meow
\f[B]\-\f[R] going
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | select(. == \(dq*go*\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
ago
go
going
.EE
.SS Select elements from array with regular expression
See more regular expression examples under the \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/string-operators
\f[CR]string\f[R] operator docs
.UE \c
\&.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] this_0
\f[B]\-\f[R] not_this
\f[B]\-\f[R] nor_0_this
\f[B]\-\f[R] thisTo_4
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | select(test(\(dq[a\-zA\-Z]+_[0\-9]$\(dq))\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
this_0
thisTo_4
.EE
.SS Select items from a map
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
things\f[B]:\f[R] cat
bob\f[B]:\f[R] goat
horse\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | select(. == \(dqcat\(dq or test(\(dqog$\(dq))\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cat
dog
.EE
.SS Use select and with_entries to filter map keys
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
name\f[B]:\f[R] bob
legs\f[B]:\f[R] 2
game\f[B]:\f[R] poker
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqwith_entries(select(.key | test(\(dqame$\(dq)))\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
name\f[B]:\f[R] bob
game\f[B]:\f[R] poker
.EE
.SS Select multiple items in a map and update
Note the brackets around the entire LHS.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  things\f[B]:\f[R] cat
  bob\f[B]:\f[R] goat
  horse\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq(.a.[] | select(. == \(dqcat\(dq or . == \(dqgoat\(dq)) |= \(dqrabbit\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  things\f[B]:\f[R] rabbit
  bob\f[B]:\f[R] rabbit
  horse\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.SH Shuffle
Shuffles an array.
Note that this command does \f[I]not\f[R] use a cryptographically secure
random number generator to randomise the array order.
.SS Shuffle array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
\f[B]\-\f[R] 4
\f[B]\-\f[R] 5
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqshuffle\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 5
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] 4
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
.EE
.SS Shuffle array in place
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
cool\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 1
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 2
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 3
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 4
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 5
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.cool |= shuffle\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cool\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 5
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 2
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 4
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 1
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 3
.EE
.SH Slice Array or String
The slice operator works on both arrays and strings.
Like the \f[CR]jq\f[R] equivalent, \f[CR].[10:15]\f[R] will return a
subarray (or substring) of length 5, starting from index 10 inclusive,
up to index 15 exclusive.
Negative numbers count backwards from the end of the array or string.
.PP
You may leave out the first or second number, which will refer to the
start or end of the array or string respectively.
.SS Slicing arrays
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] frog
\f[B]\-\f[R] cow
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[1:3]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] frog
.EE
.SS Slicing arrays \- without the first number
Starts from the start of the array
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] frog
\f[B]\-\f[R] cow
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[:2]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] dog
.EE
.SS Slicing arrays \- without the second number
Finishes at the end of the array
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] frog
\f[B]\-\f[R] cow
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[2:]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] frog
\f[B]\-\f[R] cow
.EE
.SS Slicing arrays \- use negative numbers to count backwards from the end
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] frog
\f[B]\-\f[R] cow
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[1:\-1]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] frog
.EE
.SS Inserting into the middle of an array
using an expression to find the index
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] frog
\f[B]\-\f[R] cow
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq(.[] | select(. == \(dqdog\(dq) | key + 1) as $pos | .[0:($pos)] + [\(dqrabbit\(dq] + .[$pos:]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] rabbit
\f[B]\-\f[R] frog
\f[B]\-\f[R] cow
.EE
.SS Slicing strings
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
country\f[B]:\f[R] Australia
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.country[0:5]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Austr
.EE
.SS Slicing strings \- without the second number
Finishes at the end of the string
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
country\f[B]:\f[R] Australia
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.country[5:]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
alia
.EE
.SS Slicing strings \- without the first number
Starts from the start of the string
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
country\f[B]:\f[R] Australia
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.country[:5]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Austr
.EE
.SS Slicing strings \- use negative numbers to count backwards from the end
Negative indices count from the end of the string
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
country\f[B]:\f[R] Australia
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.country[\-5:]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
ralia
.EE
.SS Slicing strings \- Unicode
Indices are rune\-based, so multi\-byte characters are handled correctly
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
greeting\f[B]:\f[R] héllo
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.greeting[1:3]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
él
.EE
.SH Sort Keys
The Sort Keys operator sorts maps by their keys (based on their string
value).
This operator does not do anything to arrays or scalars (so you can
easily recursively apply it to all maps).
.PP
Sort is particularly useful for diffing two different yaml documents:
.IP
.EX
yq \-i \-P \(aqsort_keys(..)\(aq file1.yml
yq \-i \-P \(aqsort_keys(..)\(aq file2.yml
diff file1.yml file2.yml
.EE
.PP
Note that \f[CR]yq\f[R] does not yet consider anchors when sorting by
keys \- this may result in invalid yaml documents if you are using merge
anchors.
.PP
For more advanced sorting, you can use the \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/sort
sort_by
.UE \c
\ function on a map, and give it a custom function like
\f[CR]sort_by(key | downcase)\f[R].
.SS Sort keys of map
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
c\f[B]:\f[R] frog
a\f[B]:\f[R] blah
b\f[B]:\f[R] bing
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqsort_keys(.)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] blah
b\f[B]:\f[R] bing
c\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.SS Sort keys recursively
Note the array elements are left unsorted, but maps inside arrays are
sorted
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
bParent\f[B]:\f[R]
  c\f[B]:\f[R] dog
  array\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] 3
    \f[B]\-\f[R] 1
    \f[B]\-\f[R] 2
aParent\f[B]:\f[R]
  z\f[B]:\f[R] donkey
  x\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] c\f[B]:\f[R] yum
      b\f[B]:\f[R] delish
    \f[B]\-\f[R] b\f[B]:\f[R] ew
      a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqsort_keys(..)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
aParent\f[B]:\f[R]
  x\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] b\f[B]:\f[R] delish
      c\f[B]:\f[R] yum
    \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
      b\f[B]:\f[R] ew
  z\f[B]:\f[R] donkey
bParent\f[B]:\f[R]
  array\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] 3
    \f[B]\-\f[R] 1
    \f[B]\-\f[R] 2
  c\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.SH Sort
Sorts an array.
Use \f[CR]sort\f[R] to sort an array as is, or \f[CR]sort_by(exp)\f[R]
to sort by a particular expression (e.g.\ subfield).
.PP
To sort by descending order, pipe the results through the
\f[CR]reverse\f[R] operator after sorting.
.PP
Note that at this stage, \f[CR]yq\f[R] only sorts scalar fields.
.SS Sort by string field
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqsort_by(.a)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS Sort by multiple fields
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
  b\f[B]:\f[R] banana
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
  b\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqsort_by(.a, .b)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
  b\f[B]:\f[R] apple
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
  b\f[B]:\f[R] banana
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.SS Sort descending by string field
Use sort with reverse to sort in descending order.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqsort_by(.a) | reverse\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.SS Sort array in place
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
cool\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.cool |= sort_by(.a)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cool\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS Sort array of objects by key
Note that you can give sort_by complex expressions, not just paths
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
cool\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] b\f[B]:\f[R] banana
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
  \f[B]\-\f[R] c\f[B]:\f[R] banana
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.cool |= sort_by(keys | .[0])\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cool\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
  \f[B]\-\f[R] b\f[B]:\f[R] banana
  \f[B]\-\f[R] c\f[B]:\f[R] banana
.EE
.SS Sort a map
Sorting a map, by default this will sort by the values
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
y\f[B]:\f[R] b
z\f[B]:\f[R] a
x\f[B]:\f[R] c
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqsort\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
z\f[B]:\f[R] a
y\f[B]:\f[R] b
x\f[B]:\f[R] c
.EE
.SS Sort a map by keys
Use sort_by to sort a map using a custom function
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
Y\f[B]:\f[R] b
z\f[B]:\f[R] a
x\f[B]:\f[R] c
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqsort_by(key | downcase)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
x\f[B]:\f[R] c
Y\f[B]:\f[R] b
z\f[B]:\f[R] a
.EE
.SS Sort is stable
Note the order of the elements in unchanged when equal in sorting.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
  b\f[B]:\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
  b\f[B]:\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
  b\f[B]:\f[R] 3
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
  b\f[B]:\f[R] 4
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqsort_by(.a)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
  b\f[B]:\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
  b\f[B]:\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
  b\f[B]:\f[R] 3
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
  b\f[B]:\f[R] 4
.EE
.SS Sort by numeric field
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] 10
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] 100
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] 1
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqsort_by(.a)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] 10
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] 100
.EE
.SS Sort by custom date field
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] 12\-Jun\-2011
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] 23\-Dec\-2010
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] 10\-Aug\-2011
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqwith_dtf(\(dq02\-Jan\-2006\(dq; sort_by(.a))\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] 23\-Dec\-2010
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] 12\-Jun\-2011
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] 10\-Aug\-2011
.EE
.SS Sort, nulls come first
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 8
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
\f[B]\-\f[R] null
\f[B]\-\f[R] 6
\f[B]\-\f[R] true
\f[B]\-\f[R] false
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqsort\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] null
\f[B]\-\f[R] false
\f[B]\-\f[R] true
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
\f[B]\-\f[R] 6
\f[B]\-\f[R] 8
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
.EE
.SH Split into Documents
This operator splits all matches into separate documents
.SS Split empty
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aqsplit_doc\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
.EE
.SS Split array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | split_doc\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\-\-\-
b\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.SH String Operators
.SS RegEx
This uses Golang\(cqs native regex functions under the hood \- See their
\c
.UR https://github.com/google/re2/wiki/Syntax
docs
.UE \c
\ for the supported syntax.
.PP
Case insensitive tip: prefix the regex with \f[CR](?i)\f[R] \-
e.g.\ \f[CR]test(\(dq(?i)cats\(dq)\f[R].
.SS match(regEx)
This operator returns the substring match details of the given regEx.
.SS capture(regEx)
Capture returns named RegEx capture groups in a map.
Can be more convenient than \f[CR]match\f[R] depending on what you are
doing.
.SS test(regEx)
Returns true if the string matches the RegEx, false otherwise.
.SS sub(regEx, replacement)
Substitutes matched substrings.
The first parameter is the regEx to match substrings within the original
string.
The second parameter specifies what to replace those matches with.
This can refer to capture groups from the first RegEx.
.SS String blocks, bash and newlines
Bash is notorious for chomping on precious trailing newline characters,
making it tricky to set strings with newlines properly.
In particular, the \f[CR]$( exp )\f[R] \f[I]will trim trailing
newlines\f[R].
.PP
For instance to get this yaml:
.IP
.EX
a: |
  cat
.EE
.PP
Using \f[CR]$( exp )\f[R] wont work, as it will trim the trailing
newline.
.IP
.EX
m=$(echo \(dqcat\(rsn\(dq) yq \-n \(aq.a = strenv(m)\(aq
a: cat
.EE
.PP
However, using printf works:
.IP
.EX
printf \-v m \(dqcat\(rsn\(dq ; m=\(dq$m\(dq yq \-n \(aq.a = strenv(m)\(aq
a: |
  cat
.EE
.PP
As well as having multiline expressions:
.IP
.EX
m=\(dqcat
\(dq  yq \-n \(aq.a = strenv(m)\(aq
a: |
  cat
.EE
.PP
Similarly, if you\(cqre trying to set the content from a file, and want
a trailing newline:
.IP
.EX
IFS= read \-rd \(aq\(aq output < <(cat my_file)
output=$output ./yq \(aq.data.values = strenv(output)\(aq first.yml
.EE
.SS Interpolation
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
value\f[B]:\f[R] things
another\f[B]:\f[R] stuff
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.message = \(dqI like \(rs(.value) and \(rs(.another)\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
value\f[B]:\f[R] things
another\f[B]:\f[R] stuff
message\f[B]:\f[R] I like things and stuff
.EE
.SS Interpolation \- not a string
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
value\f[B]:\f[R]
  an\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.message = \(dqI like \(rs(.value)\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
value\f[B]:\f[R]
  an\f[B]:\f[R] apple
message\f[B]:\f[R] \(aqI like an: apple\(aq
.EE
.SS To up (upper) case
Works with unicode characters
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
água
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqupcase\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
ÁGUA
.EE
.SS To down (lower) case
Works with unicode characters
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
ÁgUA
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqdowncase\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
água
.EE
.SS Join strings
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] meow
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] null
\f[B]\-\f[R] true
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqjoin(\(dq; \(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cat; meow; 1; ; true
.EE
.SS Trim strings
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(aq cat\(aq
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(aqdog \(aq
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(aq cow cow \(aq
\f[B]\-\f[R] horse
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | trim\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cat
dog
cow cow
horse
.EE
.SS Match string
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
foo bar foo
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqmatch(\(dqfoo\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
string\f[B]:\f[R] foo
offset\f[B]:\f[R] 0
length\f[B]:\f[R] 3
captures\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.SS Match string, case insensitive
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
foo bar FOO
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq[match(\(dq(?i)foo\(dq; \(dqg\(dq)]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] string\f[B]:\f[R] foo
  offset\f[B]:\f[R] 0
  length\f[B]:\f[R] 3
  captures\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
\f[B]\-\f[R] string\f[B]:\f[R] FOO
  offset\f[B]:\f[R] 8
  length\f[B]:\f[R] 3
  captures\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.SS Match with global capture group
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
abc abc
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq[match(\(dq(ab)(c)\(dq; \(dqg\(dq)]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] string\f[B]:\f[R] abc
  offset\f[B]:\f[R] 0
  length\f[B]:\f[R] 3
  captures\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] string\f[B]:\f[R] ab
      offset\f[B]:\f[R] 0
      length\f[B]:\f[R] 2
    \f[B]\-\f[R] string\f[B]:\f[R] c
      offset\f[B]:\f[R] 2
      length\f[B]:\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] string\f[B]:\f[R] abc
  offset\f[B]:\f[R] 4
  length\f[B]:\f[R] 3
  captures\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] string\f[B]:\f[R] ab
      offset\f[B]:\f[R] 4
      length\f[B]:\f[R] 2
    \f[B]\-\f[R] string\f[B]:\f[R] c
      offset\f[B]:\f[R] 6
      length\f[B]:\f[R] 1
.EE
.SS Match with named capture groups
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
foo bar foo foo  foo
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq[match(\(dqfoo (?P<bar123>bar)? foo\(dq; \(dqg\(dq)]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] string\f[B]:\f[R] foo bar foo
  offset\f[B]:\f[R] 0
  length\f[B]:\f[R] 11
  captures\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] string\f[B]:\f[R] bar
      offset\f[B]:\f[R] 4
      length\f[B]:\f[R] 3
      name\f[B]:\f[R] bar123
\f[B]\-\f[R] string\f[B]:\f[R] foo  foo
  offset\f[B]:\f[R] 12
  length\f[B]:\f[R] 8
  captures\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] string\f[B]:\f[R] null
      offset\f[B]:\f[R] \-1
      length\f[B]:\f[R] 0
      name\f[B]:\f[R] bar123
.EE
.SS Capture named groups into a map
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
xyzzy\-14
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqcapture(\(dq(?P<a>[a\-z]+)\-(?P<n>[0\-9]+)\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] xyzzy
n\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq14\(dq
.EE
.SS Match without global flag
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
cat cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqmatch(\(dqcat\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
string\f[B]:\f[R] cat
offset\f[B]:\f[R] 0
length\f[B]:\f[R] 3
captures\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.SS Match with global flag
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
cat cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq[match(\(dqcat\(dq; \(dqg\(dq)]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] string\f[B]:\f[R] cat
  offset\f[B]:\f[R] 0
  length\f[B]:\f[R] 3
  captures\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
\f[B]\-\f[R] string\f[B]:\f[R] cat
  offset\f[B]:\f[R] 4
  length\f[B]:\f[R] 3
  captures\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.SS Test using regex
Like jq\(cqs equivalent, this works like match but only returns
true/false instead of full match details
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | test(\(dqat\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
true
false
.EE
.SS Substitute / Replace string
This uses Golang\(cqs regex, described \c
.UR https://github.com/google/re2/wiki/Syntax
here
.UE \c
\&.
Note the use of \f[CR]|=\f[R] to run in context of the current string
value.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] dogs are great
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a |= sub(\(dqdogs\(dq, \(dqcats\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cats are great
.EE
.SS Substitute / Replace string with regex
This uses Golang\(cqs regex, described \c
.UR https://github.com/google/re2/wiki/Syntax
here
.UE \c
\&.
Note the use of \f[CR]|=\f[R] to run in context of the current string
value.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] heat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] |= sub(\(dq(a)\(dq, \(dq${1}r\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cart
b\f[B]:\f[R] heart
.EE
.SS Custom types: that are really strings
When custom tags are encountered, yq will try to decode the underlying
type.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !horse cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] !goat heat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] |= sub(\(dq(a)\(dq, \(dq${1}r\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !horse cart
b\f[B]:\f[R] !goat heart
.EE
.SS Split strings
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
cat; meow; 1; ; true
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqsplit(\(dq; \(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] meow
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(dq1\(dq
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(dq\(dq
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(dqtrue\(dq
.EE
.SS Split strings one match
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
word
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqsplit(\(dq; \(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] word
.EE
.SS To string
Note that you may want to force \f[CR]yq\f[R] to leave scalar values
wrapped by passing in \f[CR]\-\-unwrapScalar=false\f[R] or
\f[CR]\-r=f\f[R]
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] true
\f[B]\-\f[R] null
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(ti
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] an\f[B]:\f[R] object
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] array
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 2
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] |= to_string\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(dq1\(dq
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(dqtrue\(dq
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(dqnull\(dq
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(dq\(ti\(dq
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(dqan: object\(dq
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(dq\- array\(rsn\- 2\(dq
.EE
.SH Style
The style operator can be used to get or set the style of nodes
(e.g.\ string style, yaml style).
Use this to control the formatting of the document in yaml.
.SS Update and set style of a particular node (simple)
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] thing
  c\f[B]:\f[R] something
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.b = \(dqnew\(dq | .a.b style=\(dqdouble\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqnew\(dq
  c\f[B]:\f[R] something
.EE
.SS Update and set style of a particular node using path variables
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] thing
  c\f[B]:\f[R] something
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqwith(.a.b ; . = \(dqnew\(dq | . style=\(dqdouble\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqnew\(dq
  c\f[B]:\f[R] something
.EE
.SS Set tagged style
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] 5
c\f[B]:\f[R] 3.2
e\f[B]:\f[R] true
f\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 1
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 2
  \f[B]\-\f[R] 3
g\f[B]:\f[R]
  something\f[B]:\f[R] cool
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.. style=\(dqtagged\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
!!map
a\f[B]:\f[R] !!str cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] !!int 5
c\f[B]:\f[R] !!float 3.2
e\f[B]:\f[R] !!bool true
f\f[B]:\f[R] !!seq
  \f[B]\-\f[R] !!int 1
  \f[B]\-\f[R] !!int 2
  \f[B]\-\f[R] !!int 3
g\f[B]:\f[R] !!map
  something\f[B]:\f[R] !!str cool
.EE
.SS Set double quote style
Given a sample.yml file of:
