.SH Subtract
You can use subtract to subtract numbers as well as remove elements from
an array.
.SS Array subtraction
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq[1,2] \- [2,3]\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
.EE
.SS Array subtraction with nested array
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq[[1], 1, 2] \- [[1], 3]\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
.EE
.SS Array subtraction with nested object
Note that order of the keys does not matter
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] b
  c\f[B]:\f[R] d
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] b
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq. \- [{\(dqc\(dq: \(dqd\(dq, \(dqa\(dq: \(dqb\(dq}]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] b
.EE
.SS Number subtraction \- float
If the lhs or rhs are floats then the expression will be calculated with
floats.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 3
b\f[B]:\f[R] 4.5
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a = .a \- .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] \-1.5
b\f[B]:\f[R] 4.5
.EE
.SS Number subtraction \- int
If both the lhs and rhs are ints then the expression will be calculated
with ints.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 3
b\f[B]:\f[R] 4
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a = .a \- .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] \-1
b\f[B]:\f[R] 4
.EE
.SS Decrement numbers
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 3
b\f[B]:\f[R] 5
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] \-= 1\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 2
b\f[B]:\f[R] 4
.EE
.SS Date subtraction
You can subtract durations from dates.
Assumes RFC3339 date time format, see \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/date-time-operators
date\-time operators
.UE \c
\ for more information.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 2021\-01\-01T03:10:00Z
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a \-= \(dq3h10m\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 2021\-01\-01T00:00:00Z
.EE
.SS Date subtraction \- custom format
Use with_dtf to specify your datetime format.
See \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/date-time-operators
date\-time operators
.UE \c
\ for more information.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] Saturday, 15\-Dec\-01 at 6:00AM GMT
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqwith_dtf(\(dqMonday, 02\-Jan\-06 at 3:04PM MST\(dq, .a \-= \(dq3h1m\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] Saturday, 15\-Dec\-01 at 2:59AM GMT
.EE
.SS Custom types: that are really numbers
When custom tags are encountered, yq will try to decode the underlying
type.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !horse 2
b\f[B]:\f[R] !goat 1
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a \-= .b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !horse 1
b\f[B]:\f[R] !goat 1
.EE
.SH System Operators
The \f[CR]system\f[R] operator allows you to run an external command and
use its output as a value in your expression.
.PP
\f[B]Security warning\f[R]: The system operator is disabled by default.
You must explicitly pass
\f[CR]\-\-security\-enable\-system\-operator\f[R] to use it.
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] When enabled, the system operator can replicate the
functionality of \f[CR]env\f[R] and \f[CR]load\f[R] operators via
external commands.
Enabling it effectively overrides
\f[CR]\-\-security\-disable\-env\-ops\f[R] and
\f[CR]\-\-security\-disable\-file\-ops\f[R].
.SS Usage
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-security\-enable\-system\-operator \-\-null\-input \(aq.field = system(\(dqcommand\(dq; \(dqarg1\(dq)\(aq
.EE
.PP
The operator takes: \- A command string (required) \- An argument (or an
array of arguments), separated from the command by \f[CR];\f[R]
(optional)
.PP
The current matched node\(cqs value is serialised and piped to the
command via stdin.
The command\(cqs stdout (with trailing newline stripped) is returned as
a string.
.SS Disabling the system operator
The system operator is disabled by default.
When disabled, an error is returned instead of running the command,
consistent with \f[CR]\-\-security\-disable\-env\-ops\f[R] and
\f[CR]\-\-security\-disable\-file\-ops\f[R].
.PP
Use \f[CR]\-\-security\-enable\-system\-operator\f[R] flag to enable it.
.SS system operator returns error when disabled
Use \f[CR]\-\-security\-enable\-system\-operator\f[R] to enable the
system operator.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
country\f[B]:\f[R] Australia
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.country = system(\(dq/usr/bin/echo\(dq; \(dqtest\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Error: system operations are disabled, use \-\-security\-enable\-system\-operator to enable
.EE
.SS Run a command with an argument
Use \f[CR]\-\-security\-enable\-system\-operator\f[R] to enable the
system operator.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
country\f[B]:\f[R] Australia
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-security\-enable\-system\-operator \(aq.country = system(\(dq/bin/echo\(dq; \(dqtest\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
country\f[B]:\f[R] test
.EE
.SS Run a command without arguments
Omit the semicolon and args to run the command with no extra arguments.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] hello
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-security\-enable\-system\-operator \(aq.a = system(\(dq/bin/echo\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq\(dq
.EE
.SH Tag
The tag operator can be used to get or set the tag of nodes
(e.g.\ \f[CR]!!str\f[R], \f[CR]!!int\f[R], \f[CR]!!bool\f[R]).
.SS Get tag
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] 5
c\f[B]:\f[R] 3.2
e\f[B]:\f[R] true
f\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.. | tag\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
!!map
!!str
!!int
!!float
!!bool
!!seq
.EE
.SS type is an alias for tag
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] 5
c\f[B]:\f[R] 3.2
e\f[B]:\f[R] true
f\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.. | type\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
!!map
!!str
!!int
!!float
!!bool
!!seq
.EE
.SS Set custom tag
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] str
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a tag = \(dq!!mikefarah\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] !!mikefarah str
.EE
.SS Find numbers and convert them to strings
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] 5
c\f[B]:\f[R] 3.2
e\f[B]:\f[R] true
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq(.. | select(tag == \(dq!!int\(dq)) tag= \(dq!!str\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
b\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq5\(dq
c\f[B]:\f[R] 3.2
e\f[B]:\f[R] true
.EE
.SH To Number
Parses the input as a number.
yq will try to parse values as an int first, failing that it will try
float.
Values that already ints or floats will be left alone.
.SS Converts strings to numbers
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(dq3\(dq
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(dq3.1\(dq
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(dq\-1e3\(dq
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | to_number\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
3
3.1
\-1e3
.EE
.SS Doesn\(cqt change numbers
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3.1
\f[B]\-\f[R] \-1e3
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | to_number\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
3
3.1
\-1e3
.EE
.SS Cannot convert null
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq.a.b | to_number\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Error: cannot convert node value [null] at path a.b of tag !!null to number
.EE
.SH Traverse (Read)
This is the simplest (and perhaps most used) operator.
It is used to navigate deeply into yaml structures.
.SS NOTE \(enyaml\-fix\-merge\-anchor\-to\-spec flag
\f[CR]yq\f[R] doesn\(cqt merge anchors \f[CR]<<:\f[R] to spec, in some
circumstances it incorrectly overrides existing keys when the spec
documents not to do that.
.PP
To minimise disruption while still fixing the issue, a flag has been
added to toggle this behaviour.
This will first default to false; and log warnings to users.
Then it will default to true (and still allow users to specify false if
needed)
.PP
See examples of the flag differences below, where LEGACY is the flag
off; and FIXED is with the flag on.
.SS Simple map navigation
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
b\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.SS Splat
Often used to pipe children into other operators
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] b\f[B]:\f[R] apple
\f[B]\-\f[R] c\f[B]:\f[R] banana
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
b\f[B]:\f[R] apple
c\f[B]:\f[R] banana
.EE
.SS Optional Splat
Just like splat, but won\(cqt error if you run it against scalars
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
.EE
.SS Special characters
Use quotes with square brackets around path elements with special
characters
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\(dq{}\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[\(dq{}\(dq]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
frog
.EE
.SS Nested special characters
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  \(dqkey.withdots\(dq\f[B]:\f[R]
    \(dqanother.key\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] apple
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a[\(dqkey.withdots\(dq][\(dqanother.key\(dq]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
apple
.EE
.SS Keys with spaces
Use quotes with square brackets around path elements with special
characters
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\(dqred rabbit\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[\(dqred rabbit\(dq]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
frog
.EE
.SS Dynamic keys
Expressions within [] can be used to dynamically lookup / calculate keys
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
b\f[B]:\f[R] apple
apple\f[B]:\f[R] crispy yum
banana\f[B]:\f[R] soft yum
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[.b]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
crispy yum
.EE
.SS Children don\(cqt exist
Nodes are added dynamically while traversing
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
c\f[B]:\f[R] banana
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
null
.EE
.SS Optional identifier
Like jq, does not output an error when the yaml is not an array or
object as expected
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a?\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
.EE
.SS Wildcard matching
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  cat\f[B]:\f[R] apple
  mad\f[B]:\f[R] things
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.\(dq*a*\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
apple
things
.EE
.SS Aliases
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] &cat
  c\f[B]:\f[R] frog
b\f[B]:\f[R] *cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.b\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
*cat
.EE
.SS Traversing aliases with splat
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] &cat
  c\f[B]:\f[R] frog
b\f[B]:\f[R] *cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.b[]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
frog
.EE
.SS Traversing aliases explicitly
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] &cat
