.SH Union
This operator is used to combine different results together.
.SS Combine scalars
Running
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-null\-input \(aq1, true, \(dqcat\(dq\(aq
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
1
true
cat
.EE
.SS Combine selected paths
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] fieldA
b\f[B]:\f[R] fieldB
c\f[B]:\f[R] fieldC
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a, .c\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
fieldA
fieldC
.EE
.SH Unique
This is used to filter out duplicated items in an array.
Note that the original order of the array is maintained.
.SS Unique array of scalars (string/numbers)
Note that unique maintains the original order of the array.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqunique\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] 2
\f[B]\-\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] 3
.EE
.SS Unique nulls
Unique works on the node value, so it considers different
representations of nulls to be different
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(ti
\f[B]\-\f[R] null
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(ti
\f[B]\-\f[R] null
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqunique\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(ti
\f[B]\-\f[R] null
.EE
.SS Unique all nulls
Run against the node tag to unique all the nulls
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(ti
\f[B]\-\f[R] null
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(ti
\f[B]\-\f[R] null
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqunique_by(tag)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \(ti
.EE
.SS Unique array objects
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] harry
  pet\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] billy
  pet\f[B]:\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] harry
  pet\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqunique\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] harry
  pet\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] billy
  pet\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.SS Unique array of objects by a field
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] harry
  pet\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] billy
  pet\f[B]:\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] harry
  pet\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqunique_by(.name)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] harry
  pet\f[B]:\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] billy
  pet\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.SS Unique array of arrays
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] sheep
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqunique\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] sheep
.EE
.SH Variable Operators
Like the \f[CR]jq\f[R] equivalents, variables are sometimes required for
the more complex expressions (or swapping values between fields).
.PP
Note that there is also an additional \f[CR]ref\f[R] operator that holds
a reference (instead of a copy) of the path, allowing you to make
multiple changes to the same path.
.SS Single value variable
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a as $foo | $foo\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cat
.EE
.SS Multi value variable
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] cat
\f[B]\-\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] as $foo | $foo\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cat
dog
.EE
.SS Using variables as a lookup
Example taken from \c
.UR https://stedolan.github.io/jq/manual/#Variable/SymbolicBindingOperator:...as$identifier%7C...
jq
.UE \c
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\(dqposts\(dq\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] \(dqtitle\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] First post
    \(dqauthor\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] anon
  \f[B]\-\f[R] \(dqtitle\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] A well\-written article
    \(dqauthor\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] person1
\(dqrealnames\(dq\f[B]:\f[R]
  \(dqanon\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] Anonymous Coward
  \(dqperson1\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] Person McPherson
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.realnames as $names | .posts[] | {\(dqtitle\(dq:.title, \(dqauthor\(dq: $names[.author]}\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
title\f[B]:\f[R] First post
author\f[B]:\f[R] Anonymous Coward
title\f[B]:\f[R] A well\-written article
author\f[B]:\f[R] Person McPherson
.EE
.SS Using variables to swap values
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] a_value
b\f[B]:\f[R] b_value
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a as $x  | .b as $y | .b = $x | .a = $y\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] b_value
b\f[B]:\f[R] a_value
.EE
.SS Use ref to reference a path repeatedly
Note: You may find the \f[CR]with\f[R] operator more useful.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] thing
  c\f[B]:\f[R] something
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.a.b ref $x | $x = \(dqnew\(dq | $x style=\(dqdouble\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqnew\(dq
  c\f[B]:\f[R] something
.EE
.SH With
Use the \f[CR]with\f[R] operator to conveniently make multiple updates
to a deeply nested path, or to update array elements relatively to each
other.
The first argument expression sets the root context, and the second
expression runs against that root context.
.SS Update and style
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  deeply\f[B]:\f[R]
    nested\f[B]:\f[R] value
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqwith(.a.deeply.nested; . = \(dqnewValue\(dq | . style=\(dqsingle\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  deeply\f[B]:\f[R]
    nested\f[B]:\f[R] \(aqnewValue\(aq
.EE
.SS Update multiple deeply nested properties
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  deeply\f[B]:\f[R]
    nested\f[B]:\f[R] value
    other\f[B]:\f[R] thing
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqwith(.a.deeply; .nested = \(dqnewValue\(dq | .other= \(dqnewThing\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  deeply\f[B]:\f[R]
    nested\f[B]:\f[R] newValue
    other\f[B]:\f[R] newThing
.EE
.SS Update array elements relatively
The second expression runs with each element of the array as it\(cqs
contextual root.
This allows you to make updates relative to the element.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
myArray\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqwith(.myArray[]; .b = .a + \(dq yum\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
myArray\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] apple
    b\f[B]:\f[R] apple yum
  \f[B]\-\f[R] a\f[B]:\f[R] banana
    b\f[B]:\f[R] banana yum
.EE
.SH Base64
Encode and decode to and from Base64.
.PP
Base64 assumes \c
.UR https://rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc4648.html
RFC4648
.UE \c
\ encoding.
Encoding and decoding both assume that the content is a UTF\-8 string
and not binary content.
.PP
See below for examples
.SS Decode base64: simple
Decoded data is assumed to be a string.
.PP
Given a sample.txt file of:
.IP
.EX
YSBzcGVjaWFsIHN0cmluZw==
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-p=base64 \-oy \(aq.\(aq sample.txt
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a special string
.EE
.SS Decode base64: UTF\-8
Base64 decoding supports UTF\-8 encoded strings.
.PP
Given a sample.txt file of:
.IP
.EX
V29ya3Mgd2l0aCBVVEYtMTYg8J+Yig==
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-p=base64 \-oy \(aq.\(aq sample.txt
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Works with UTF\-16 😊
.EE
.SS Decode with extra spaces
Extra leading/trailing whitespace is stripped
.PP
Given a sample.txt file of:
.IP
.EX

 YSBzcGVjaWFsIHN0cmluZw==  
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-p=base64 \-oy \(aq.\(aq sample.txt
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a special string
.EE
.SS Encode base64: string
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\(dqa special string\(dq
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=base64 \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
YSBzcGVjaWFsIHN0cmluZw==\(ga\(ga\(ga

## Encode base64: string from document
Extract a string field and encode it to base64.

Given a sample.yml file of:
\(ga\(ga\(gayaml
coolData: \(dqa special string\(dq
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=base64 \(aq.coolData\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
YSBzcGVjaWFsIHN0cmluZw==\(ga\(ga\(ga

# JSON

Encode and decode to and from JSON. Supports multiple JSON documents in a single file (e.g. NDJSON).

Note that YAML is a superset of (single document) JSON \- so you don\(aqt have to use the JSON parser to read JSON when there is only one JSON document in the input. You will probably want to pretty print the result in this case, to get idiomatic YAML styling.


## Parse json: simple
JSON is a subset of yaml, so all you need to do is prettify the output

Given a sample.json file of:
\(ga\(ga\(gajson
{\(dqcat\(dq: \(dqmeow\(dq}
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-p=json sample.json
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
cat\f[B]:\f[R] meow
.EE
.SS Parse json: complex
JSON is a subset of yaml, so all you need to do is prettify the output
.PP
Given a sample.json file of:
.IP
.EX
{\(dqa\(dq:\(dqEasy! as one two three\(dq,\(dqb\(dq:{\(dqc\(dq:2,\(dqd\(dq:[3,4]}}
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-p=json sample.json
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] Easy! as one two three
b\f[B]:\f[R]
  c\f[B]:\f[R] 2
  d\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] 3
    \f[B]\-\f[R] 4
.EE
.SS Encode json: simple
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
cat\f[B]:\f[R] meow
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=json \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
{
  \(dqcat\(dq: \(dqmeow\(dq
}
.EE
.SS Encode json: simple \- in one line
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
cat\f[B]:\f[R] meow\f[I] # this is a comment, and it will be dropped.\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=json \-I=0 \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
{\(dqcat\(dq:\(dqmeow\(dq}
.EE
.SS Encode json: comments
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
cat\f[B]:\f[R] meow\f[I] # this is a comment, and it will be dropped.\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=json \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
{
  \(dqcat\(dq: \(dqmeow\(dq
}
.EE
.SS Encode json: anchors
Anchors are dereferenced
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
cat\f[B]:\f[R] &ref meow
anotherCat\f[B]:\f[R] *ref
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=json \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
{
  \(dqcat\(dq: \(dqmeow\(dq,
  \(dqanotherCat\(dq: \(dqmeow\(dq
}
.EE
.SS Encode json: multiple results
Each matching node is converted into a json doc.
This is best used with 0 indent (json document per line)
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
things\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][{\f[R]stuff\f[B]:\f[R] cool\f[B]},\f[R] \f[B]{\f[R]whatever\f[B]:\f[R] cat\f[B]}]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=json \-I=0 \(aq.things[]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
{\(dqstuff\(dq:\(dqcool\(dq}
{\(dqwhatever\(dq:\(dqcat\(dq}
.EE
.SS Encode json: preserve floats with trailing zero
Whole\-number floats keep their decimal point so downstream consumers
see a JSON number with a fractional part (matches Go\(cqs encoding/json,
Python\(cqs json, and jq).
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
percentiles\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]50.0\f[B],\f[R] 95.0\f[B],\f[R] 99.0\f[B],\f[R] 99.9\f[B]]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=json \-I=0 \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
{\(dqpercentiles\(dq:[50.0,95.0,99.0,99.9]}
.EE
.SS Roundtrip JSON Lines / NDJSON
Given a sample.json file of:
.IP
.EX
{\(dqthis\(dq: \(dqis a multidoc json file\(dq}
{\(dqeach\(dq: [\(dqline is a valid json document\(dq]}
{\(dqa number\(dq: 4}
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-p=json \-o=json \-I=0 sample.json
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{\f[R]\(dqthis\(dq:\(dqis a multidoc json file\(dq\f[B]}\f[R]
\f[B]{\f[R]\(dqeach\(dq:[\(dqline is a valid json document\(dq]\f[B]}\f[R]
\f[B]{\f[R]\(dqa number\(dq:4\f[B]}\f[R]
.EE
.SS Roundtrip multi\-document JSON
The parser can also handle multiple multi\-line json documents in a
single file (despite this not being in the JSON Lines / NDJSON spec).
Typically you would have one entire JSON document per line, but the
parser also supports multiple multi\-line json documents
.PP
Given a sample.json file of:
.IP
.EX
{
    \(dqthis\(dq: \(dqis a multidoc json file\(dq
}
{
    \(dqit\(dq: [
        \(dqhas\(dq,
        \(dqconsecutive\(dq,
        \(dqjson documents\(dq
    ]
}
{
    \(dqa number\(dq: 4
}
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-p=json \-o=json \-I=2 sample.json
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{\f[R]
  \(dqthis\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqis a multidoc json file\(dq
\f[B]}\f[R]
\f[B]{\f[R]
  \(dqit\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]
    \(dqhas\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
    \(dqconsecutive\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
    \(dqjson documents\(dq
  \f[B]]\f[R]
\f[B]}\f[R]
\f[B]{\f[R]
  \(dqa number\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] 4
\f[B]}\f[R]
.EE
.SS Update a specific document in a multi\-document json
Documents are indexed by the \f[CR]documentIndex\f[R] or \f[CR]di\f[R]
operator.
.PP
Given a sample.json file of:
.IP
.EX
{\(dqthis\(dq: \(dqis a multidoc json file\(dq}
{\(dqeach\(dq: [\(dqline is a valid json document\(dq]}
{\(dqa number\(dq: 4}
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-p=json \-o=json \-I=0 \(aq(select(di == 1) | .each ) += \(dqcool\(dq\(aq sample.json
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{\f[R]\(dqthis\(dq:\(dqis a multidoc json file\(dq\f[B]}\f[R]
\f[B]{\f[R]\(dqeach\(dq:[\(dqline is a valid json document\(dq\f[B],\f[R]\(dqcool\(dq]\f[B]}\f[R]
\f[B]{\f[R]\(dqa number\(dq:4\f[B]}\f[R]
.EE
.SS Find and update a specific document in a multi\-document json
Use expressions as you normally would.
.PP
Given a sample.json file of:
.IP
.EX
{\(dqthis\(dq: \(dqis a multidoc json file\(dq}
{\(dqeach\(dq: [\(dqline is a valid json document\(dq]}
{\(dqa number\(dq: 4}
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-p=json \-o=json \-I=0 \(aq(select(has(\(dqeach\(dq)) | .each ) += \(dqcool\(dq\(aq sample.json
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{\f[R]\(dqthis\(dq:\(dqis a multidoc json file\(dq\f[B]}\f[R]
\f[B]{\f[R]\(dqeach\(dq:[\(dqline is a valid json document\(dq\f[B],\f[R]\(dqcool\(dq]\f[B]}\f[R]
\f[B]{\f[R]\(dqa number\(dq:4\f[B]}\f[R]
.EE
.SS Decode JSON Lines / NDJSON
Given a sample.json file of:
.IP
.EX
{\(dqthis\(dq: \(dqis a multidoc json file\(dq}
{\(dqeach\(dq: [\(dqline is a valid json document\(dq]}
{\(dqa number\(dq: 4}
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-p=json sample.json
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
this\f[B]:\f[R] is a multidoc json file
\-\-\-
each\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] line is a valid json document
\-\-\-
a number\f[B]:\f[R] 4
.EE
.SH CSV
Encode/Decode/Roundtrip CSV and TSV files.
.SS Encode
Currently supports arrays of homogeneous flat objects, that is: no
nesting and it assumes the \f[I]first\f[R] object has all the keys
required:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Bobo
  type\f[B]:\f[R] dog
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Fifi
  type\f[B]:\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
As well as arrays of arrays of scalars (strings/numbers/booleans):
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]Bobo\f[B],\f[R] dog\f[B]]\f[R]
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]Fifi\f[B],\f[R] cat\f[B]]\f[R]
.EE
.SS Decode
Decode assumes the first CSV/TSV row is the header row, and all rows
beneath are the entries.
The data will be coded into an array of objects, using the header rows
as keys.
.IP
.EX
name,type
Bobo,dog
Fifi,cat
.EE
.SS Encode CSV simple
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]i\f[B],\f[R] like\f[B],\f[R] csv\f[B]]\f[R]
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]because\f[B],\f[R] excel\f[B],\f[R] is\f[B],\f[R] cool\f[B]]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=csv sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
i,like,csv
because,excel,is,cool
.EE
.SS Encode TSV simple
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]i\f[B],\f[R] like\f[B],\f[R] csv\f[B]]\f[R]
\f[B]\-\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]because\f[B],\f[R] excel\f[B],\f[R] is\f[B],\f[R] cool\f[B]]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=tsv sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
i   like    csv
because excel   is  cool
.EE
.SS Encode array of objects to csv
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Gary
  numberOfCats\f[B]:\f[R] 1
  likesApples\f[B]:\f[R] true
  height\f[B]:\f[R] 168.8
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Samantha\(aqs Rabbit
  numberOfCats\f[B]:\f[R] 2
  likesApples\f[B]:\f[R] false
  height\f[B]:\f[R] \-188.8
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=csv sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
name,numberOfCats,likesApples,height
Gary,1,true,168.8
Samantha\(aqs Rabbit,2,false,\-188.8
.EE
.SS Encode array of objects to custom csv format
Add the header row manually, then the we convert each object into an
array of values \- resulting in an array of arrays.
Pick the columns and call the header whatever you like.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Gary
  numberOfCats\f[B]:\f[R] 1
  likesApples\f[B]:\f[R] true
  height\f[B]:\f[R] 168.8
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Samantha\(aqs Rabbit
  numberOfCats\f[B]:\f[R] 2
  likesApples\f[B]:\f[R] false
  height\f[B]:\f[R] \-188.8
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=csv \(aq[[\(dqName\(dq, \(dqNumber of Cats\(dq]] +  [.[] | [.name, .numberOfCats ]]\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
Name,Number of Cats
Gary,1
Samantha\(aqs Rabbit,2
.EE
.SS Encode array of objects to csv \- missing fields behaviour
First entry is used to determine the headers, and it is missing
`likesApples', so it is not included in the csv.
Second entry does not have `numberOfCats' so that is blank
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Gary
  numberOfCats\f[B]:\f[R] 1
  height\f[B]:\f[R] 168.8
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Samantha\(aqs Rabbit
  height\f[B]:\f[R] \-188.8
  likesApples\f[B]:\f[R] false
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=csv sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
name,numberOfCats,height
Gary,1,168.8
Samantha\(aqs Rabbit,,\-188.8
.EE
.SS Parse CSV into an array of objects
First row is assumed to be the header row.
By default, entries with YAML/JSON formatting will be parsed!
.PP
Given a sample.csv file of:
.IP
.EX
name,numberOfCats,likesApples,height,facts
Gary,1,true,168.8,cool: true
Samantha\(aqs Rabbit,2,false,\-188.8,tall: indeed
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-p=csv sample.csv
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Gary
  numberOfCats\f[B]:\f[R] 1
  likesApples\f[B]:\f[R] true
  height\f[B]:\f[R] 168.8
  facts\f[B]:\f[R]
    cool\f[B]:\f[R] true
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Samantha\(aqs Rabbit
  numberOfCats\f[B]:\f[R] 2
  likesApples\f[B]:\f[R] false
  height\f[B]:\f[R] \-188.8
  facts\f[B]:\f[R]
    tall\f[B]:\f[R] indeed
.EE
.SS Parse CSV into an array of objects, no auto\-parsing
First row is assumed to be the header row.
Entries with YAML/JSON will be left as strings.
.PP
Given a sample.csv file of:
.IP
.EX
name,numberOfCats,likesApples,height,facts
Gary,1,true,168.8,cool: true
Samantha\(aqs Rabbit,2,false,\-188.8,tall: indeed
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-p=csv \-\-csv\-auto\-parse=f sample.csv
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Gary
  numberOfCats\f[B]:\f[R] 1
  likesApples\f[B]:\f[R] true
  height\f[B]:\f[R] 168.8
  facts\f[B]:\f[R] \(aqcool: true\(aq
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Samantha\(aqs Rabbit
  numberOfCats\f[B]:\f[R] 2
  likesApples\f[B]:\f[R] false
  height\f[B]:\f[R] \-188.8
  facts\f[B]:\f[R] \(aqtall: indeed\(aq
.EE
.SS Parse TSV into an array of objects
First row is assumed to be the header row.
.PP
Given a sample.tsv file of:
.IP
.EX
name    numberOfCats    likesApples height
Gary    1   true    168.8
Samantha\(aqs Rabbit   2   false   \-188.8
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-p=tsv sample.tsv
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Gary
  numberOfCats\f[B]:\f[R] 1
  likesApples\f[B]:\f[R] true
  height\f[B]:\f[R] 168.8
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Samantha\(aqs Rabbit
  numberOfCats\f[B]:\f[R] 2
  likesApples\f[B]:\f[R] false
  height\f[B]:\f[R] \-188.8
.EE
.SS Round trip
Given a sample.csv file of:
.IP
.EX
name,numberOfCats,likesApples,height
Gary,1,true,168.8
Samantha\(aqs Rabbit,2,false,\-188.8
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-p=csv \-o=csv \(aq(.[] | select(.name == \(dqGary\(dq) | .numberOfCats) = 3\(aq sample.csv
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
name,numberOfCats,likesApples,height
Gary,3,true,168.8
Samantha\(aqs Rabbit,2,false,\-188.8
.EE
.SH Formatting Expressions
\f[CR]From version v4.41+\f[R]
.PP
You can put expressions into \f[CR].yq\f[R] files, use whitespace and
comments to break up complex expressions and explain what\(cqs going on.
.SS Using expression files and comments
Note that you can execute the file directly \- but make sure you make
the expression file executable.
.PP
Given a sample.yaml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] old
.EE
.PP
And an `update.yq' expression file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]#! yq\f[R]

\f[I]# This is a yq expression that updates the map\f[R]
\f[I]# for several great reasons outlined here.\f[R]

\&.a.b = \(dqnew\(dq \f[I]# line comment here\f[R]
\f[B]|\f[R] .a.c = \(dqfrog\(dq

\f[I]# Now good things will happen.\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
\&./update.yq sample.yaml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] new
  c\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.SS Flags in expression files
You can specify flags on the shebang line, this only works when
executing the file directly.
.PP
Given a sample.yaml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] old
.EE
.PP
And an `update.yq' expression file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]#! yq \-oj\f[R]

\f[I]# This is a yq expression that updates the map\f[R]
\f[I]# for several great reasons outlined here.\f[R]

\&.a.b = \(dqnew\(dq \f[I]# line comment here\f[R]
\f[B]|\f[R] .a.c = \(dqfrog\(dq

\f[I]# Now good things will happen.\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
\&./update.yq sample.yaml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{\f[R]
  \(dqa\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B]{\f[R]
    \(dqb\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqnew\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
    \(dqc\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqfrog\(dq
  \f[B]}\f[R]
\f[B]}\f[R]
.EE
.SS Commenting out yq expressions
Note that \f[CR]c\f[R] is no longer set to `frog'.
In this example we\(cqre calling yq directly and passing the expression
file into \f[CR]\-\-from\-file\f[R], this is no different from executing
the expression file directly.
.PP
Given a sample.yaml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] old
.EE
.PP
And an `update.yq' expression file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]#! yq\f[R]
\f[I]# This is a yq expression that updates the map\f[R]
\f[I]# for several great reasons outlined here.\f[R]

\&.a.b = \(dqnew\(dq \f[I]# line comment here\f[R]
\f[I]# | .a.c = \(dqfrog\(dq\f[R]

\f[I]# Now good things will happen.\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-from\-file update.yq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] new
.EE
.SH HCL
Encode and decode to and from \c
.UR https://github.com/hashicorp/hcl
HashiCorp Configuration Language (HCL)
.UE \c
\&.
.PP
HCL is commonly used in HashiCorp tools like Terraform for configuration
files.
The yq HCL encoder and decoder support: \- Blocks and attributes \-
String interpolation and expressions (preserved without quotes) \-
Comments (leading, head, and line comments) \- Nested structures (maps
and lists) \- Syntax colorisation when enabled
.SS Parse HCL
Given a sample.hcl file of:
.IP
.EX
io_mode = \(dqasync\(dq
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-oy sample.hcl
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
io_mode\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqasync\(dq
.EE
.SS Roundtrip: Sample Doc
Given a sample.hcl file of:
.IP
.EX
service \(dqcat\(dq {
  process \(dqmain\(dq {
    command = [\(dq/usr/local/bin/awesome\-app\(dq, \(dqserver\(dq]
  }

  process \(dqmanagement\(dq {
    command = [\(dq/usr/local/bin/awesome\-app\(dq, \(dqmanagement\(dq]
  }
}
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq sample.hcl
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
service \(dqcat\(dq {
  process \(dqmain\(dq {
    command = [\(dq/usr/local/bin/awesome\-app\(dq, \(dqserver\(dq]
  }
  process \(dqmanagement\(dq {
    command = [\(dq/usr/local/bin/awesome\-app\(dq, \(dqmanagement\(dq]
  }
}
.EE
.SS Roundtrip: With an update
Given a sample.hcl file of:
.IP
.EX
service \(dqcat\(dq {
  process \(dqmain\(dq {
    command = [\(dq/usr/local/bin/awesome\-app\(dq, \(dqserver\(dq]
  }

  process \(dqmanagement\(dq {
    command = [\(dq/usr/local/bin/awesome\-app\(dq, \(dqmanagement\(dq]
  }
}
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.service.cat.process.main.command += \(dqmeow\(dq\(aq sample.hcl
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
service \(dqcat\(dq {
  process \(dqmain\(dq {
    command = [\(dq/usr/local/bin/awesome\-app\(dq, \(dqserver\(dq, \(dqmeow\(dq]
  }
  process \(dqmanagement\(dq {
    command = [\(dq/usr/local/bin/awesome\-app\(dq, \(dqmanagement\(dq]
  }
}
.EE
.SS Parse HCL: Sample Doc
Given a sample.hcl file of:
.IP
.EX
service \(dqcat\(dq {
  process \(dqmain\(dq {
    command = [\(dq/usr/local/bin/awesome\-app\(dq, \(dqserver\(dq]
  }

  process \(dqmanagement\(dq {
    command = [\(dq/usr/local/bin/awesome\-app\(dq, \(dqmanagement\(dq]
  }
}
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-oy sample.hcl
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
service\f[B]:\f[R]
  cat\f[B]:\f[R]
    process\f[B]:\f[R]
      main\f[B]:\f[R]
        command\f[B]:\f[R]
          \f[B]\-\f[R] \(dq/usr/local/bin/awesome\-app\(dq
          \f[B]\-\f[R] \(dqserver\(dq
      management\f[B]:\f[R]
        command\f[B]:\f[R]
          \f[B]\-\f[R] \(dq/usr/local/bin/awesome\-app\(dq
          \f[B]\-\f[R] \(dqmanagement\(dq
.EE
.SS Parse HCL: with comments
Given a sample.hcl file of:
.IP
.EX
# Configuration
port = 8080 # server port
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-oy sample.hcl
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# Configuration\f[R]
port\f[B]:\f[R] 8080\f[I] # server port\f[R]
.EE
.SS Roundtrip: with comments
Given a sample.hcl file of:
.IP
.EX
# Configuration
port = 8080
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq sample.hcl
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
# Configuration
port = 8080
.EE
.SS Roundtrip: With templates, functions and arithmetic
Given a sample.hcl file of:
.IP
.EX
# Arithmetic with literals and application\-provided variables
sum = 1 + addend

# String interpolation and templates
message = \(dqHello, ${name}!\(dq

# Application\-provided functions
shouty_message = upper(message)
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq sample.hcl
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
# Arithmetic with literals and application\-provided variables
sum = 1 + addend
# String interpolation and templates
message = \(dqHello, ${name}!\(dq
# Application\-provided functions
shouty_message = upper(message)
.EE
.SS Roundtrip: Separate blocks with same name.
Given a sample.hcl file of:
.IP
.EX
resource \(dqaws_instance\(dq \(dqweb\(dq {
  ami = \(dqami\-12345\(dq
}
resource \(dqaws_instance\(dq \(dqdb\(dq {
  ami = \(dqami\-67890\(dq
}
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq sample.hcl
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
resource \(dqaws_instance\(dq \(dqweb\(dq {
  ami = \(dqami\-12345\(dq
}
resource \(dqaws_instance\(dq \(dqdb\(dq {
  ami = \(dqami\-67890\(dq
}
.EE
.SH KYaml
Encode and decode to and from KYaml (a restricted subset of YAML that
uses flow\-style collections).
.PP
KYaml is useful when you want YAML data rendered in a compact,
JSON\-like form while still supporting YAML features like comments.
.PP
Notes: \- Strings are always double\-quoted in KYaml output.
\- Anchors and aliases are expanded (KYaml output does not emit them).
.SS Encode kyaml: plain string scalar
Strings are always double\-quoted in KYaml output.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=kyaml \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\(dqcat\(dq
.EE
.SS encode flow mapping and sequence
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] b
c\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] d
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=kyaml \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{\f[R]
  a\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqb\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
  c\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]
    \(dqd\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
  \f[B]],\f[R]
\f[B]}\f[R]
.EE
.SS encode non\-string scalars
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] 12
b\f[B]:\f[R] true
c\f[B]:\f[R] null
d\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqtrue\(dq
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=kyaml \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{\f[R]
  a\f[B]:\f[R] 12\f[B],\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] true\f[B],\f[R]
  c\f[B]:\f[R] null\f[B],\f[R]
  d\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqtrue\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
\f[B]}\f[R]
.EE
.SS quote non\-identifier keys
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\(dq1a\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] b
\(dqhas space\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] c
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=kyaml \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{\f[R]
  \(dq1a\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqb\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
  \(dqhas space\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqc\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
\f[B]}\f[R]
.EE
.SS escape quoted strings
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqline1\(rsnline2\(rst\(rs\(dqq\(rs\(dq\(dq
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=kyaml \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{\f[R]
  a\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqline1\(rsnline2\(rst\(rs\(dqq\(rs\(dq\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
\f[B]}\f[R]
.EE
.SS preserve comments when encoding
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# leading\f[R]
a\f[B]:\f[R] 1\f[I] # a line\f[R]
\f[I]# head b\f[R]
b\f[B]:\f[R] 2
c\f[B]:\f[R]
\f[I]  # head d\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] d\f[I] # d line\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] e
\f[I]# trailing\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=kyaml \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# leading\f[R]
\f[B]{\f[R]
  a\f[B]:\f[R] 1\f[B],\f[R]\f[I] # a line\f[R]
\f[I]  # head b\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] 2\f[B],\f[R]
  c\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]
\f[I]    # head d\f[R]
    \(dqd\(dq\f[B],\f[R]\f[I] # d line\f[R]
    \(dqe\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
  \f[B]],\f[R]
\f[I]  # trailing\f[R]
\f[B]}\f[R]
.EE
.SS Encode kyaml: anchors and aliases
KYaml output does not support anchors/aliases; they are expanded to
concrete values.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
base\f[B]:\f[R] &base
  a\f[B]:\f[R] b
copy\f[B]:\f[R] *base
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=kyaml \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{\f[R]
  base\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B]{\f[R]
    a\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqb\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
  \f[B]},\f[R]
  copy\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B]{\f[R]
    a\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqb\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
  \f[B]},\f[R]
\f[B]}\f[R]
.EE
.SS Encode kyaml: yaml to kyaml shows formatting differences
KYaml uses flow\-style collections (braces/brackets) and explicit
commas.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
person\f[B]:\f[R]
  name\f[B]:\f[R] John
  pets\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
    \f[B]\-\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=kyaml \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{\f[R]
  person\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B]{\f[R]
    name\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqJohn\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
    pets\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]
      \(dqcat\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
      \(dqdog\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
    \f[B]],\f[R]
  \f[B]},\f[R]
\f[B]}\f[R]
.EE
.SS Encode kyaml: nested lists of objects
Lists and objects can be nested arbitrarily; KYaml always uses
flow\-style collections.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] a
  items\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] id\f[B]:\f[R] 1
      tags\f[B]:\f[R]
        \f[B]\-\f[R] k\f[B]:\f[R] x
          v\f[B]:\f[R] y
        \f[B]\-\f[R] k\f[B]:\f[R] x2
          v\f[B]:\f[R] y2
    \f[B]\-\f[R] id\f[B]:\f[R] 2
      tags\f[B]:\f[R]
        \f[B]\-\f[R] k\f[B]:\f[R] z
          v\f[B]:\f[R] w
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=kyaml \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B][\f[R]
  \f[B]{\f[R]
    name\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqa\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
    items\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]
      \f[B]{\f[R]
        id\f[B]:\f[R] 1\f[B],\f[R]
        tags\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]
          \f[B]{\f[R]
            k\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqx\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
            v\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqy\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
          \f[B]},\f[R]
          \f[B]{\f[R]
            k\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqx2\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
            v\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqy2\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
          \f[B]},\f[R]
        \f[B]],\f[R]
      \f[B]},\f[R]
      \f[B]{\f[R]
        id\f[B]:\f[R] 2\f[B],\f[R]
        tags\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]
          \f[B]{\f[R]
            k\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqz\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
            v\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqw\(dq\f[B],\f[R]
          \f[B]},\f[R]
        \f[B]],\f[R]
      \f[B]},\f[R]
    \f[B]],\f[R]
  \f[B]},\f[R]
\f[B]]\f[R]
.EE
.SS Basic input example
Given a sample.lua file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]return\f[R] {
    [\(dqcountry\(dq] = \(dqAustralia\(dq; \f[I]\-\- this place\f[R]
    [\(dqcities\(dq] = {
        \(dqSydney\(dq,
        \(dqMelbourne\(dq,
        \(dqBrisbane\(dq,
        \(dqPerth\(dq,
    };
};
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-oy \(aq.\(aq sample.lua
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
country\f[B]:\f[R] Australia
cities\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] Sydney
  \f[B]\-\f[R] Melbourne
  \f[B]\-\f[R] Brisbane
  \f[B]\-\f[R] Perth
.EE
.SS Basic output example
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\-\-\-
country\f[B]:\f[R] Australia\f[I] # this place\f[R]
cities\f[B]:\f[R]
\f[B]\-\f[R] Sydney
\f[B]\-\f[R] Melbourne
\f[B]\-\f[R] Brisbane
\f[B]\-\f[R] Perth
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=lua \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]return\f[R] {
    [\(dqcountry\(dq] = \(dqAustralia\(dq; \f[I]\-\- this place\f[R]
    [\(dqcities\(dq] = {
        \(dqSydney\(dq,
        \(dqMelbourne\(dq,
        \(dqBrisbane\(dq,
        \(dqPerth\(dq,
    };
};
.EE
.SS Unquoted keys
Uses the \f[CR]\-\-lua\-unquoted\f[R] option to produce a nicer\-looking
output.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\-\-\-
country\f[B]:\f[R] Australia\f[I] # this place\f[R]
cities\f[B]:\f[R]
\f[B]\-\f[R] Sydney
\f[B]\-\f[R] Melbourne
\f[B]\-\f[R] Brisbane
\f[B]\-\f[R] Perth
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=lua \-\-lua\-unquoted \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]return\f[R] {
    country = \(dqAustralia\(dq; \f[I]\-\- this place\f[R]
    cities = {
        \(dqSydney\(dq,
        \(dqMelbourne\(dq,
        \(dqBrisbane\(dq,
        \(dqPerth\(dq,
    };
};
.EE
.SS Globals
Uses the \f[CR]\-\-lua\-globals\f[R] option to export the values into
the global scope.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\-\-\-
country\f[B]:\f[R] Australia\f[I] # this place\f[R]
cities\f[B]:\f[R]
\f[B]\-\f[R] Sydney
\f[B]\-\f[R] Melbourne
\f[B]\-\f[R] Brisbane
\f[B]\-\f[R] Perth
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=lua \-\-lua\-globals \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
country = \(dqAustralia\(dq; \f[I]\-\- this place\f[R]
cities = {
    \(dqSydney\(dq,
    \(dqMelbourne\(dq,
    \(dqBrisbane\(dq,
    \(dqPerth\(dq,
};
.EE
.SS Elaborate example
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\-\-\-
hello\f[B]:\f[R] world
tables\f[B]:\f[R]
  like\f[B]:\f[R] this
  keys\f[B]:\f[R] values
  \f[B]?\f[R] look\f[B]:\f[R] non\-string keys
  \f[B]:\f[R] True
numbers\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] decimal\f[B]:\f[R] 12345
  \f[B]\-\f[R] hex\f[B]:\f[R] 0x7fabc123
  \f[B]\-\f[R] octal\f[B]:\f[R] 0o30
  \f[B]\-\f[R] float\f[B]:\f[R] 123.45
  \f[B]\-\f[R] infinity\f[B]:\f[R] .inf
    plus_infinity\f[B]:\f[R] +.inf
    minus_infinity\f[B]:\f[R] \-.inf
  \f[B]\-\f[R] not\f[B]:\f[R] .nan
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=lua \(aq.\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]return\f[R] {
    [\(dqhello\(dq] = \(dqworld\(dq;
    [\(dqtables\(dq] = {
        [\(dqlike\(dq] = \(dqthis\(dq;
        [\(dqkeys\(dq] = \(dqvalues\(dq;
        [{
            [\(dqlook\(dq] = \(dqnon\-string keys\(dq;
        }] = \f[B]true\f[R];
    };
    [\(dqnumbers\(dq] = {
        {
            [\(dqdecimal\(dq] = 12345;
        },
        {
            [\(dqhex\(dq] = 0x7fabc123;
        },
        {
            [\(dqoctal\(dq] = 24;
        },
        {
            [\(dqfloat\(dq] = 123.45;
        },
        {
            [\(dqinfinity\(dq] = (1/0);
            [\(dqplus_infinity\(dq] = (1/0);
            [\(dqminus_infinity\(dq] = (\-1/0);
        },
        {
            [\(dqnot\(dq] = (0/0);
        },
    };
};
.EE
.SH Properties
Encode/Decode/Roundtrip to/from a property file.
Line comments on value nodes will be copied across.
.PP
By default, empty maps and arrays are not encoded \- see below for an
example on how to encode a value for these.
.SS Encode properties
Note that empty arrays and maps are not encoded by default.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# block comments come through\f[R]
person\f[B]:\f[R]\f[I] # neither do comments on maps\f[R]
    name\f[B]:\f[R] Mike Wazowski\f[I] # comments on values appear\f[R]
    pets\f[B]:\f[R] 
    \f[B]\-\f[R] cat\f[I] # comments on array values appear\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] nested\f[B]:\f[R]
        \f[B]\-\f[R] list entry
    food\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]pizza\f[B]]\f[R]\f[I] # comments on arrays do not\f[R]
emptyArray\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
emptyMap\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=props sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
# block comments come through
# comments on values appear
person.name = Mike Wazowski

# comments on array values appear
person.pets.0 = cat
person.pets.1.nested.0 = list entry
person.food.0 = pizza
.EE
.SS Encode properties with array brackets
Declare the \(enproperties\-array\-brackets flag to give array paths in
brackets (e.g.\ SpringBoot).
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# block comments come through\f[R]
person\f[B]:\f[R]\f[I] # neither do comments on maps\f[R]
    name\f[B]:\f[R] Mike Wazowski\f[I] # comments on values appear\f[R]
    pets\f[B]:\f[R] 
    \f[B]\-\f[R] cat\f[I] # comments on array values appear\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] nested\f[B]:\f[R]
        \f[B]\-\f[R] list entry
    food\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]pizza\f[B]]\f[R]\f[I] # comments on arrays do not\f[R]
emptyArray\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
emptyMap\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=props \-\-properties\-array\-brackets sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
# block comments come through
# comments on values appear
person.name = Mike Wazowski

# comments on array values appear
person.pets[0] = cat
person.pets[1].nested[0] = list entry
person.food[0] = pizza
.EE
.SS Encode properties \- custom separator
Use the \(enproperties\-separator flag to specify your own key/value
separator.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# block comments come through\f[R]
person\f[B]:\f[R]\f[I] # neither do comments on maps\f[R]
    name\f[B]:\f[R] Mike Wazowski\f[I] # comments on values appear\f[R]
    pets\f[B]:\f[R] 
    \f[B]\-\f[R] cat\f[I] # comments on array values appear\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] nested\f[B]:\f[R]
        \f[B]\-\f[R] list entry
    food\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]pizza\f[B]]\f[R]\f[I] # comments on arrays do not\f[R]
emptyArray\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
emptyMap\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=props \-\-properties\-separator=\(dq :\(at \(dq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
# block comments come through
# comments on values appear
person.name :\(at Mike Wazowski

# comments on array values appear
person.pets.0 :\(at cat
person.pets.1.nested.0 :\(at list entry
person.food.0 :\(at pizza
.EE
.SS Encode properties: scalar encapsulation
Note that string values with blank characters in them are encapsulated
with double quotes
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# block comments come through\f[R]
person\f[B]:\f[R]\f[I] # neither do comments on maps\f[R]
    name\f[B]:\f[R] Mike Wazowski\f[I] # comments on values appear\f[R]
    pets\f[B]:\f[R] 
    \f[B]\-\f[R] cat\f[I] # comments on array values appear\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] nested\f[B]:\f[R]
        \f[B]\-\f[R] list entry
    food\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]pizza\f[B]]\f[R]\f[I] # comments on arrays do not\f[R]
emptyArray\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
emptyMap\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=props \-\-unwrapScalar=false sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
# block comments come through
# comments on values appear
person.name = \(dqMike Wazowski\(dq

# comments on array values appear
person.pets.0 = cat
person.pets.1.nested.0 = \(dqlist entry\(dq
person.food.0 = pizza
.EE
.SS Encode properties: no comments
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# block comments come through\f[R]
person\f[B]:\f[R]\f[I] # neither do comments on maps\f[R]
    name\f[B]:\f[R] Mike Wazowski\f[I] # comments on values appear\f[R]
    pets\f[B]:\f[R] 
    \f[B]\-\f[R] cat\f[I] # comments on array values appear\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] nested\f[B]:\f[R]
        \f[B]\-\f[R] list entry
    food\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]pizza\f[B]]\f[R]\f[I] # comments on arrays do not\f[R]
emptyArray\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
emptyMap\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=props \(aq... comments = \(dq\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
person.name = Mike Wazowski
person.pets.0 = cat
person.pets.1.nested.0 = list entry
person.food.0 = pizza
.EE
.SS Encode properties: include empty maps and arrays
Use a yq expression to set the empty maps and sequences to your desired
value.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# block comments come through\f[R]
person\f[B]:\f[R]\f[I] # neither do comments on maps\f[R]
    name\f[B]:\f[R] Mike Wazowski\f[I] # comments on values appear\f[R]
    pets\f[B]:\f[R] 
    \f[B]\-\f[R] cat\f[I] # comments on array values appear\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] nested\f[B]:\f[R]
        \f[B]\-\f[R] list entry
    food\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R]pizza\f[B]]\f[R]\f[I] # comments on arrays do not\f[R]
emptyArray\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
emptyMap\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=props \(aq(.. | select( (tag == \(dq!!map\(dq or tag ==\(dq!!seq\(dq) and length == 0)) = \(dq\(dq\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
# block comments come through
# comments on values appear
person.name = Mike Wazowski

# comments on array values appear
person.pets.0 = cat
person.pets.1.nested.0 = list entry
person.food.0 = pizza
emptyArray = 
emptyMap = 
.EE
.SS Decode properties
Given a sample.properties file of:
.IP
.EX
# block comments come through
# comments on values appear
person.name = Mike Wazowski

# comments on array values appear
person.pets.0 = cat
person.pets.1.nested.0 = list entry
person.food.0 = pizza
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-p=props sample.properties
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
person\f[B]:\f[R]
\f[I]  # block comments come through\f[R]
\f[I]  # comments on values appear\f[R]
  name\f[B]:\f[R] Mike Wazowski
  pets\f[B]:\f[R]
\f[I]    # comments on array values appear\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
    \f[B]\-\f[R] nested\f[B]:\f[R]
        \f[B]\-\f[R] list entry
  food\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] pizza
.EE
.SS Decode properties: numbers
All values are assumed to be strings when parsing properties, but you
can use the \f[CR]from_yaml\f[R] operator on all the strings values to
autoparse into the correct type.
.PP
Given a sample.properties file of:
.IP
.EX
a.b = 10
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-p=props \(aq (.. | select(tag == \(dq!!str\(dq)) |= from_yaml\(aq sample.properties
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
a\f[B]:\f[R]
  b\f[B]:\f[R] 10
.EE
.SS Decode properties \- array should be a map
If you have a numeric map key in your property files, use array_to_map
to convert them to maps.
.PP
Given a sample.properties file of:
.IP
.EX
things.10 = mike
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-p=props \(aq.things |= array_to_map\(aq sample.properties
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
things\f[B]:\f[R]
  10\f[B]:\f[R] mike
.EE
.SS Roundtrip
Given a sample.properties file of:
.IP
.EX
# block comments come through
# comments on values appear
person.name = Mike Wazowski

# comments on array values appear
person.pets.0 = cat
person.pets.1.nested.0 = list entry
person.food.0 = pizza
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-p=props \-o=props \(aq.person.pets.0 = \(dqdog\(dq\(aq sample.properties
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
# block comments come through
# comments on values appear
person.name = Mike Wazowski

# comments on array values appear
person.pets.0 = dog
person.pets.1.nested.0 = list entry
person.food.0 = pizza
.EE
.SH Recipes
These examples are intended to show how you can use multiple operators
together so you get an idea of how you can perform complex data
manipulation.
.PP
Please see the details \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators
operator docs
.UE \c
\ for details on each individual operator.
.SS Find items in an array
We have an array and we want to find the elements with a particular
name.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Foo
  numBuckets\f[B]:\f[R] 0
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Bar
  numBuckets\f[B]:\f[R] 0
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] | select(.name == \(dqFoo\(dq)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
name\f[B]:\f[R] Foo
numBuckets\f[B]:\f[R] 0
.EE
.SS Explanation:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR].[]\f[R] splats the array, and puts all the items in the context.
.IP \(bu 2
These items are then piped (\f[CR]|\f[R]) into
\f[CR]select(.name == \(dqFoo\(dq)\f[R] which will select all the nodes
that have a name property set to `Foo'.
.IP \(bu 2
See the \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/select
select
.UE \c
\ operator for more information.
.SS Find and update items in an array
We have an array and we want to \f[I]update\f[R] the elements with a
particular name.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Foo
  numBuckets\f[B]:\f[R] 0
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Bar
  numBuckets\f[B]:\f[R] 0
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq(.[] | select(.name == \(dqFoo\(dq) | .numBuckets) |= . + 1\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Foo
  numBuckets\f[B]:\f[R] 1
\f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Bar
  numBuckets\f[B]:\f[R] 0
.EE
.SS Explanation:
.IP \(bu 2
Following from the example above\f[CR].[]\f[R] splats the array, selects
filters the items.
.IP \(bu 2
We then pipe (\f[CR]|\f[R]) that into \f[CR].numBuckets\f[R], which will
select that field from all the matching items
.IP \(bu 2
Splat, select and the field are all in brackets, that whole expression
is passed to the \f[CR]|=\f[R] operator as the left hand side
expression, with \f[CR]. + 1\f[R] as the right hand side expression.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]|=\f[R] is the operator that updates fields relative to their own
value, which is referenced as dot (\f[CR].\f[R]).
.IP \(bu 2
The expression \f[CR]. + 1\f[R] increments the numBuckets counter.
.IP \(bu 2
See the \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/assign-update
assign
.UE \c
\ and \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/add
add
.UE \c
\ operators for more information.
.SS Deeply prune a tree
Say we are only interested in child1 and child2, and want to filter
everything else out.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
parentA\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] bob
parentB\f[B]:\f[R]
  child1\f[B]:\f[R] i am child1
  child3\f[B]:\f[R] hiya
parentC\f[B]:\f[R]
  childX\f[B]:\f[R] cool
  child2\f[B]:\f[R] me child2
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq(
  .. | # recurse through all the nodes
  select(has(\(dqchild1\(dq) or has(\(dqchild2\(dq)) | # match parents that have either child1 or child2
  (.child1, .child2) | # select those children
  select(.) # filter out nulls
) as $i ireduce({};  # using that set of nodes, create a new result map
  setpath($i | path; $i) # and put in each node, using its original path
)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
parentB\f[B]:\f[R]
  child1\f[B]:\f[R] i am child1
parentC\f[B]:\f[R]
  child2\f[B]:\f[R] me child2
.EE
.SS Explanation:
.IP \(bu 2
Find all the matching child1 and child2 nodes
.IP \(bu 2
Using ireduce, create a new map using just those nodes
.IP \(bu 2
Set each node into the new map using its original path
.SS Multiple or complex updates to items in an array
We have an array and we want to \f[I]update\f[R] the elements with a
particular name in reference to its type.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
myArray\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Foo
    type\f[B]:\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Bar
    type\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aqwith(.myArray[]; .name = .name + \(dq \- \(dq + .type)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
myArray\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Foo \- cat
    type\f[B]:\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Bar \- dog
    type\f[B]:\f[R] dog
.EE
.SS Explanation:
.IP \(bu 2
The with operator will effectively loop through each given item in the
first given expression, and run the second expression against it.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR].myArray[]\f[R] splats the array in \f[CR]myArray\f[R].
So \f[CR]with\f[R] will run against each item in that array
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR].name = .name + \(dq \- \(dq + .type\f[R] this expression is run
against every item, updating the name to be a concatenation of the
original name as well as the type.
.IP \(bu 2
See the \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/with
with
.UE \c
\ operator for more information and examples.
.SS Sort an array by a field
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
myArray\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Foo
    numBuckets\f[B]:\f[R] 1
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Bar
    numBuckets\f[B]:\f[R] 0
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.myArray |= sort_by(.numBuckets)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
myArray\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Bar
    numBuckets\f[B]:\f[R] 0
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] Foo
    numBuckets\f[B]:\f[R] 1
.EE
.SS Explanation:
.IP \(bu 2
We want to resort \f[CR].myArray\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]sort_by\f[R] works by piping an array into it, and it pipes out a
sorted array.
.IP \(bu 2
So, we use \f[CR]|=\f[R] to update \f[CR].myArray\f[R].
This is the same as doing
\f[CR].myArray = (.myArray | sort_by(.numBuckets))\f[R]
.SS Filter, flatten, sort and unique
Lets find the unique set of names from the document.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] type\f[B]:\f[R] foo
  names\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] Fred
    \f[B]\-\f[R] Catherine
\f[B]\-\f[R] type\f[B]:\f[R] bar
  names\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] Zelda
\f[B]\-\f[R] type\f[B]:\f[R] foo
  names\f[B]:\f[R] Fred
\f[B]\-\f[R] type\f[B]:\f[R] foo
  names\f[B]:\f[R] Ava
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq[.[] | select(.type == \(dqfoo\(dq) | .names] | flatten | sort | unique\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] Ava
\f[B]\-\f[R] Catherine
\f[B]\-\f[R] Fred
.EE
.SS Explanation:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR].[] | select(.type == \(dqfoo\(dq) | .names\f[R] will select the
array elements of type \(lqfoo\(rq
.IP \(bu 2
Splat \f[CR].[]\f[R] will unwrap the array and match all the items.
We need to do this so we can work on the child items, for instance,
filter items out using the \f[CR]select\f[R] operator.
.IP \(bu 2
But we still want the final results back into an array.
So after we\(cqre doing working on the children, we wrap everything back
into an array using square brackets around the expression.
\f[CR][.[] | select(.type == \(dqfoo\(dq) | .names]\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
Now have have an array of all the `names' values.
Which includes arrays of strings as well as strings on their own.
.IP \(bu 2
Pipe \f[CR]|\f[R] this array through \f[CR]flatten\f[R].
This will flatten nested arrays.
So now we have a flat list of all the name value strings
.IP \(bu 2
Next we pipe \f[CR]|\f[R] that through \f[CR]sort\f[R] and then
\f[CR]unique\f[R] to get a sorted, unique list of the names!
.IP \(bu 2
See the \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/flatten
flatten
.UE \c
, \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/sort
sort
.UE \c
\ and \c
.UR https://mikefarah.gitbook.io/yq/operators/unique
unique
.UE \c
\ for more information and examples.
.SS Export as environment variables (script), or any custom format
Given a yaml document, lets output a script that will configure
environment variables with that data.
This same approach can be used for exporting into custom formats.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
var0\f[B]:\f[R] string0
var1\f[B]:\f[R] string1
fruit\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] apple
  \f[B]\-\f[R] banana
  \f[B]\-\f[R] peach
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.[] |(
    ( select(kind == \(dqscalar\(dq) | key + \(dq=\(aq\(rs\(aq\(aq\(dq + . + \(dq\(aq\(rs\(aq\(aq\(dq),
    ( select(kind == \(dqseq\(dq) | key + \(dq=(\(dq + (map(\(dq\(aq\(rs\(aq\(aq\(dq + . + \(dq\(aq\(rs\(aq\(aq\(dq) | join(\(dq,\(dq)) + \(dq)\(dq)
)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
var0=\(aqstring0\(aq
var1=\(aqstring1\(aq
fruit=(\(aqapple\(aq,\(aqbanana\(aq,\(aqpeach\(aq)
.EE
.SS Explanation:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR].[]\f[R] matches all top level elements
.IP \(bu 2
We need a string expression for each of the different types that will
produce the bash syntax, we\(cqll use the union operator, to join them
together
.IP \(bu 2
Scalars, we just need the key and quoted value:
\f[CR]( select(kind == \(dqscalar\(dq) | key + \(dq=\(aq\(dq + . + \(dq\(aq\(dq)\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
Sequences (or arrays) are trickier, we need to quote each value and
\f[CR]join\f[R] them with \f[CR],\f[R]:
\f[CR]map(\(dq\(aq\(dq + . + \(dq\(aq\(dq) | join(\(dq,\(dq)\f[R]
.SS Custom format with nested data
Like the previous example, but lets handle nested data structures.
In this custom example, we\(cqre going to join the property paths with
_.
The important thing to keep in mind is that our expression is not
recursive (despite the data structure being so).
Instead we match \f[I]all\f[R] elements on the tree and operate on them.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
simple\f[B]:\f[R] string0
simpleArray\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] apple
  \f[B]\-\f[R] banana
  \f[B]\-\f[R] peach
deep\f[B]:\f[R]
  property\f[B]:\f[R] value
  array\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \(aq.. |(
    ( select(kind == \(dqscalar\(dq and parent | kind != \(dqseq\(dq) | (path | join(\(dq_\(dq)) + \(dq=\(aq\(rs\(aq\(aq\(dq + . + \(dq\(aq\(rs\(aq\(aq\(dq),
    ( select(kind == \(dqseq\(dq) | (path | join(\(dq_\(dq)) + \(dq=(\(dq + (map(\(dq\(aq\(rs\(aq\(aq\(dq + . + \(dq\(aq\(rs\(aq\(aq\(dq) | join(\(dq,\(dq)) + \(dq)\(dq)
)\(aq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
simple=\(aqstring0\(aq
deep_property=\(aqvalue\(aq
simpleArray=(\(aqapple\(aq,\(aqbanana\(aq,\(aqpeach\(aq)
deep_array=(\(aqcat\(aq)
.EE
.SS Explanation:
.IP \(bu 2
You\(cqll need to understand how the previous example works to
understand this extension.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]..\f[R] matches \f[I]all\f[R] elements, instead of \f[CR].[]\f[R]
from the previous example that just matches top level elements.
.IP \(bu 2
Like before, we need a string expression for each of the different types
that will produce the bash syntax, we\(cqll use the union operator, to
join them together
.IP \(bu 2
This time, however, our expression matches every node in the data
structure.
.IP \(bu 2
We only want to print scalars that are not in arrays (because we handle
the separately), so well add \f[CR]and parent | kind != \(dqseq\(dq\f[R]
to the select operator expression for scalars
.IP \(bu 2
We don\(cqt just want the key any more, we want the full path.
So instead of \f[CR]key\f[R] we have \f[CR]path | join(\(dq_\(dq)\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
The expression for sequences follows the same logic
.SS Encode shell variables
Note that comments are dropped and values will be enclosed in single
quotes as needed.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# comment\f[R]
name\f[B]:\f[R] Mike Wazowski
eyes\f[B]:\f[R]
  color\f[B]:\f[R] turquoise
  number\f[B]:\f[R] 1
friends\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] James P. Sullivan
  \f[B]\-\f[R] Celia Mae
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=shell sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
name=\(aqMike Wazowski\(aq
eyes_color=turquoise
eyes_number=1
friends_0=\(aqJames P. Sullivan\(aq
friends_1=\(aqCelia Mae\(aq
.EE
.SS Encode shell variables: illegal variable names as key.
Keys that would be illegal as variable keys are adapted.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
ascii_=_symbols\f[B]:\f[R] replaced with _
\(dqascii_ _controls\(dq\f[B]:\f[R] dropped (this example uses \(rst)
nonascii_א_characters\f[B]:\f[R] dropped
effort_expeñded_tò_preserve_accented_latin_letters\f[B]:\f[R] moderate (via unicode NFKD)
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=shell sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
ascii___symbols=\(aqreplaced with _\(aq
ascii__controls=\(aqdropped (this example uses \(rst)\(aq
nonascii__characters=dropped
effort_expended_to_preserve_accented_latin_letters=\(aqmoderate (via unicode NFKD)\(aq
.EE
.SS Encode shell variables: empty values, arrays and maps
Empty values are encoded to empty variables, but empty arrays and maps
are skipped.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
empty\f[B]:\f[R]
  value\f[B]:\f[R]
  array\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][]\f[R]
  map\f[B]:\f[R]   \f[B]{}\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=shell sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
empty_value=
.EE
.SS Encode shell variables: single quotes in values
Single quotes in values are encoded as `\(lq'\(lq\(cq (close single
quote, double\-quoted single quote, open single quote).
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
name\f[B]:\f[R] Miles O\(aqBrien
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=shell sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
name=\(aqMiles O\(aq\(dq\(aq\(dq\(aqBrien\(aq
.EE
.SS Encode shell variables: custom separator
Use \(enshell\-key\-separator to specify a custom separator between
keys.
This is useful when the original keys contain underscores.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
my_app\f[B]:\f[R]
  db_config\f[B]:\f[R]
    host\f[B]:\f[R] localhost
    port\f[B]:\f[R] 5432
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=shell \-\-shell\-key\-separator=\(dq__\(dq sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
my_app__db_config__host=localhost
my_app__db_config__port=5432
.EE
.SH TOML
Decode from TOML.
Note that \f[CR]yq\f[R] does not yet support outputting in TOML format
(and therefore it cannot roundtrip)
.SS Parse: Simple
Given a sample.toml file of:
.IP
.EX
A = \(dqhello\(dq
B = 12
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-oy \(aq.\(aq sample.toml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
A\f[B]:\f[R] hello
B\f[B]:\f[R] 12
.EE
.SS Parse: Deep paths
Given a sample.toml file of:
.IP
.EX
person.name = \(dqhello\(dq
person.address = \(dq12 cat st\(dq
.EE
