.SH XML
Encode and decode to and from XML.
Whitespace is not conserved for round trips \- but the order of the
fields are.
.PP
Consecutive xml nodes with the same name are assumed to be arrays.
.PP
XML content data, attributes processing instructions and directives are
all created as plain fields.
.PP
This can be controlled by:
.PP
.TS
tab(@);
lw(23.3n) lw(23.3n) lw(23.3n).
T{
Flag
T}@T{
Default
T}@T{
Sample XML
T}
_
T{
\f[CR]\-\-xml\-attribute\-prefix\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]+\f[R] (changing to \f[CR]+\(at\f[R] soon)
T}@T{
Legs in \f[CR]<cat legs=\(dq4\(dq/>\f[R]
T}
T{
\f[CR]\-\-xml\-content\-name\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]+content\f[R]
T}@T{
Meow in \f[CR]<cat>Meow <fur>true</true></cat>\f[R]
T}
T{
\f[CR]\-\-xml\-directive\-name\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]+directive\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]<!DOCTYPE config system \(dqblah\(dq>\f[R]
T}
T{
\f[CR]\-\-xml\-proc\-inst\-prefix\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]+p_\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]<?xml version=\(dq1\(dq?>\f[R]
T}
.TE
.PP
{% hint style=\(lqwarning\(rq %} Default Attribute Prefix will be
changing in v4.30!
In order to avoid name conflicts (e.g.\ having an attribute named
\(lqcontent\(rq will create a field that clashes with the default
content name of \(lq+content\(rq) the attribute prefix will be changing
to \(lq+\(at\(rq.
.PP
This will affect users that have not set their own prefix and are not
roundtripping XML changes.
.PP
{% endhint %}
.SS Encoder / Decoder flag options
In addition to the above flags, there are the following xml
encoder/decoder options controlled by flags:
.PP
.TS
tab(@);
lw(23.3n) lw(23.3n) lw(23.3n).
T{
Flag
T}@T{
Default
T}@T{
Description
T}
_
T{
\f[CR]\-\-xml\-strict\-mode\f[R]
T}@T{
false
T}@T{
Strict mode enforces the requirements of the XML specification.
When switched off the parser allows input containing common mistakes.
See \c
.UR https://pkg.go.dev/encoding/xml#Decoder
the Golang xml decoder
.UE \c
\ for more details.
T}
T{
\f[CR]\-\-xml\-keep\-namespace\f[R]
T}@T{
true
T}@T{
Keeps the namespace of attributes
T}
T{
\f[CR]\-\-xml\-raw\-token\f[R]
T}@T{
true
T}@T{
Does not verify that start and end elements match and does not translate
name space prefixes to their corresponding URLs.
T}
T{
\f[CR]\-\-xml\-skip\-proc\-inst\f[R]
T}@T{
false
T}@T{
Skips over processing instructions,
e.g.\ \f[CR]<?xml version=\(dq1\(dq?>\f[R]
T}
T{
\f[CR]\-\-xml\-skip\-directives\f[R]
T}@T{
false
T}@T{
Skips over directives,
e.g.\ \f[CR]<!DOCTYPE config system \(dqblah\(dq>\f[R]
T}
.TE
.PP
See below for examples
.SS Parse xml: simple
Notice how all the values are strings, see the next example on how you
can fix that.
.PP
Given a sample.xml file of:
.IP
.EX
<?xml version=\(dq1.0\(dq encoding=\(dqUTF\-8\(dq?>
<\f[B]cat\f[R]>
  <\f[B]says\f[R]>meow</\f[B]says\f[R]>
  <\f[B]legs\f[R]>4</\f[B]legs\f[R]>
  <\f[B]cute\f[R]>true</\f[B]cute\f[R]>
</\f[B]cat\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-oy sample.xml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
+p_xml\f[B]:\f[R] version=\(dq1.0\(dq encoding=\(dqUTF\-8\(dq
cat\f[B]:\f[R]
  says\f[B]:\f[R] meow
  legs\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq4\(dq
  cute\f[B]:\f[R] \(dqtrue\(dq
.EE
.SS Parse xml: number
All values are assumed to be strings when parsing XML, but you can use
the \f[CR]from_yaml\f[R] operator on all the strings values to autoparse
into the correct type.
.PP
Given a sample.xml file of:
.IP
.EX
<?xml version=\(dq1.0\(dq encoding=\(dqUTF\-8\(dq?>
<\f[B]cat\f[R]>
  <\f[B]says\f[R]>meow</\f[B]says\f[R]>
  <\f[B]legs\f[R]>4</\f[B]legs\f[R]>
  <\f[B]cute\f[R]>true</\f[B]cute\f[R]>
</\f[B]cat\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-oy \(aq (.. | select(tag == \(dq!!str\(dq)) |= from_yaml\(aq sample.xml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
+p_xml\f[B]:\f[R] version=\(dq1.0\(dq encoding=\(dqUTF\-8\(dq
cat\f[B]:\f[R]
  says\f[B]:\f[R] meow
  legs\f[B]:\f[R] 4
  cute\f[B]:\f[R] true
.EE
.SS Parse xml: array
Consecutive nodes with identical xml names are assumed to be arrays.
.PP
Given a sample.xml file of:
.IP
.EX
<?xml version=\(dq1.0\(dq encoding=\(dqUTF\-8\(dq?>
<\f[B]animal\f[R]>cat</\f[B]animal\f[R]>
<\f[B]animal\f[R]>goat</\f[B]animal\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-oy sample.xml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
+p_xml\f[B]:\f[R] version=\(dq1.0\(dq encoding=\(dqUTF\-8\(dq
animal\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
  \f[B]\-\f[R] goat
.EE
.SS Parse xml: force as an array
In XML, if your array has a single item, then yq doesn\(cqt know its an
array.
This is how you can consistently force it to be an array.
This handles the 3 scenarios of having nothing in the array, having a
single item and having multiple.
.PP
Given a sample.xml file of:
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]zoo\f[R]><\f[B]animal\f[R]>cat</\f[B]animal\f[R]></\f[B]zoo\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-oy \(aq.zoo.animal |= ([] + .)\(aq sample.xml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
zoo\f[B]:\f[R]
  animal\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] cat
.EE
.SS Parse xml: force all as an array
Given a sample.xml file of:
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]zoo\f[R]><\f[B]thing\f[R]><\f[B]frog\f[R]>boing</\f[B]frog\f[R]></\f[B]thing\f[R]></\f[B]zoo\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-oy \(aq.. |= [] + .\(aq sample.xml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] zoo\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] thing\f[B]:\f[R]
        \f[B]\-\f[R] frog\f[B]:\f[R]
            \f[B]\-\f[R] boing
.EE
.SS Parse xml: attributes
Attributes are converted to fields, with the default attribute prefix
`+'.
Use \(cq\(enxml\-attribute\-prefix\(ga to set your own.
.PP
Given a sample.xml file of:
.IP
.EX
<?xml version=\(dq1.0\(dq encoding=\(dqUTF\-8\(dq?>
<\f[B]cat\f[R] legs=\(dq4\(dq>
  <\f[B]legs\f[R]>7</\f[B]legs\f[R]>
</\f[B]cat\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-oy sample.xml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
+p_xml\f[B]:\f[R] version=\(dq1.0\(dq encoding=\(dqUTF\-8\(dq
cat\f[B]:\f[R]
  +\(atlegs\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq4\(dq
  legs\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq7\(dq
.EE
.SS Parse xml: attributes with content
Content is added as a field, using the default content name of
\f[CR]+content\f[R].
Use \f[CR]\-\-xml\-content\-name\f[R] to set your own.
.PP
Given a sample.xml file of:
.IP
.EX
<?xml version=\(dq1.0\(dq encoding=\(dqUTF\-8\(dq?>
<\f[B]cat\f[R] legs=\(dq4\(dq>meow</\f[B]cat\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-oy sample.xml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
+p_xml\f[B]:\f[R] version=\(dq1.0\(dq encoding=\(dqUTF\-8\(dq
cat\f[B]:\f[R]
  +content\f[B]:\f[R] meow
  +\(atlegs\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq4\(dq
.EE
.SS Parse xml: content split between comments/children
Multiple content texts are collected into a sequence.
.PP
Given a sample.xml file of:
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]root\f[R]>  value  \f[I]<!\-\- comment\-\->\f[R]anotherValue <\f[B]a\f[R]>frog</\f[B]a\f[R]> cool!</\f[B]root\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-oy sample.xml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
root\f[B]:\f[R]
  +content\f[B]:\f[R]\f[I] # comment\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] value
    \f[B]\-\f[R] anotherValue
    \f[B]\-\f[R] cool!
  a\f[B]:\f[R] frog
.EE
.SS Parse xml: custom dtd
DTD entities are processed as directives.
.PP
Given a sample.xml file of:
.IP
.EX

<?xml version=\(dq1.0\(dq?>
<!DOCTYPE root [
<!ENTITY writer \(dqBlah.\(dq>
<!ENTITY copyright \(dqBlah\(dq>
]>
<\f[B]root\f[R]>
    <\f[B]item\f[R]>&writer;&copyright;</\f[B]item\f[R]>
</\f[B]root\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq sample.xml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
<?xml version=\(dq1.0\(dq?>
<!DOCTYPE root [
<!ENTITY writer \(dqBlah.\(dq>
<!ENTITY copyright \(dqBlah\(dq>
]>
<\f[B]root\f[R]>
  <\f[B]item\f[R]>&amp;writer;&amp;copyright;</\f[B]item\f[R]>
</\f[B]root\f[R]>
.EE
.SS Parse xml: skip custom dtd
DTDs are directives, skip over directives to skip DTDs.
.PP
Given a sample.xml file of:
.IP
.EX

<?xml version=\(dq1.0\(dq?>
<!DOCTYPE root [
<!ENTITY writer \(dqBlah.\(dq>
<!ENTITY copyright \(dqBlah\(dq>
]>
<\f[B]root\f[R]>
    <\f[B]item\f[R]>&writer;&copyright;</\f[B]item\f[R]>
</\f[B]root\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-xml\-skip\-directives sample.xml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
<?xml version=\(dq1.0\(dq?>
<\f[B]root\f[R]>
  <\f[B]item\f[R]>&amp;writer;&amp;copyright;</\f[B]item\f[R]>
</\f[B]root\f[R]>
.EE
.SS Parse xml: with comments
A best attempt is made to preserve comments.
.PP
Given a sample.xml file of:
.IP
.EX

\f[I]<!\-\- before cat \-\->\f[R]
<\f[B]cat\f[R]>
    \f[I]<!\-\- in cat before \-\->\f[R]
    <\f[B]x\f[R]>3\f[I]<!\-\- multi\f[R]
\f[I]line comment \f[R]
\f[I]for x \-\->\f[R]</\f[B]x\f[R]>
    \f[I]<!\-\- before y \-\->\f[R]
    <\f[B]y\f[R]>
        \f[I]<!\-\- in y before \-\->\f[R]
        <\f[B]d\f[R]>\f[I]<!\-\- in d before \-\->\f[R]z\f[I]<!\-\- in d after \-\->\f[R]</\f[B]d\f[R]>
        
        \f[I]<!\-\- in y after \-\->\f[R]
    </\f[B]y\f[R]>
    \f[I]<!\-\- in_cat_after \-\->\f[R]
</\f[B]cat\f[R]>
\f[I]<!\-\- after cat \-\->\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-oy sample.xml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# before cat\f[R]
cat\f[B]:\f[R]
\f[I]  # in cat before\f[R]
  x\f[B]:\f[R] \(dq3\(dq\f[I] # multi\f[R]
\f[I]  # line comment \f[R]
\f[I]  # for x\f[R]
\f[I]  # before y\f[R]

  y\f[B]:\f[R]
\f[I]    # in y before\f[R]
\f[I]    # in d before\f[R]
    d\f[B]:\f[R] z\f[I] # in d after\f[R]
\f[I]    # in y after\f[R]
\f[I]  # in_cat_after\f[R]
\f[I]# after cat\f[R]
.EE
.SS Parse xml: keep attribute namespace
Defaults to true
.PP
Given a sample.xml file of:
.IP
.EX
<?xml version=\(dq1.0\(dq?>
<\f[B]map\f[R] xmlns=\(dqsome\-namespace\(dq xmlns:xsi=\(dqsome\-instance\(dq xsi:schemaLocation=\(dqsome\-url\(dq>
  <\f[B]item\f[R] foo=\(dqbar\(dq>baz</\f[B]item\f[R]>
  <\f[B]xsi:item\f[R]>foobar</\f[B]xsi:item\f[R]>
</\f[B]map\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-xml\-keep\-namespace=false sample.xml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
<?xml version=\(dq1.0\(dq?>
<\f[B]map\f[R] xmlns=\(dqsome\-namespace\(dq xsi=\(dqsome\-instance\(dq schemaLocation=\(dqsome\-url\(dq>
  <\f[B]item\f[R] foo=\(dqbar\(dq>baz</\f[B]item\f[R]>
  <\f[B]item\f[R]>foobar</\f[B]item\f[R]>
</\f[B]map\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
instead of
.IP
.EX
<?xml version=\(dq1.0\(dq?>
<\f[B]map\f[R] xmlns=\(dqsome\-namespace\(dq xmlns:xsi=\(dqsome\-instance\(dq xsi:schemaLocation=\(dqsome\-url\(dq>
  <\f[B]item\f[R] foo=\(dqbar\(dq>baz</\f[B]item\f[R]>
  <\f[B]xsi:item\f[R]>foobar</\f[B]xsi:item\f[R]>
</\f[B]map\f[R]>
.EE
.SS Parse xml: keep raw attribute namespace
Defaults to true
.PP
Given a sample.xml file of:
.IP
.EX
<?xml version=\(dq1.0\(dq?>
<\f[B]map\f[R] xmlns=\(dqsome\-namespace\(dq xmlns:xsi=\(dqsome\-instance\(dq xsi:schemaLocation=\(dqsome\-url\(dq>
  <\f[B]item\f[R] foo=\(dqbar\(dq>baz</\f[B]item\f[R]>
  <\f[B]xsi:item\f[R]>foobar</\f[B]xsi:item\f[R]>
</\f[B]map\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-\-xml\-raw\-token=false sample.xml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
<?xml version=\(dq1.0\(dq?>
<\f[B]some\-namespace:map\f[R] xmlns=\(dqsome\-namespace\(dq xmlns:xsi=\(dqsome\-instance\(dq some\-instance:schemaLocation=\(dqsome\-url\(dq>
  <\f[B]some\-namespace:item\f[R] foo=\(dqbar\(dq>baz</\f[B]some\-namespace:item\f[R]>
  <\f[B]some\-instance:item\f[R]>foobar</\f[B]some\-instance:item\f[R]>
</\f[B]some\-namespace:map\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
instead of
.IP
.EX
<?xml version=\(dq1.0\(dq?>
<\f[B]map\f[R] xmlns=\(dqsome\-namespace\(dq xmlns:xsi=\(dqsome\-instance\(dq xsi:schemaLocation=\(dqsome\-url\(dq>
  <\f[B]item\f[R] foo=\(dqbar\(dq>baz</\f[B]item\f[R]>
  <\f[B]xsi:item\f[R]>foobar</\f[B]xsi:item\f[R]>
</\f[B]map\f[R]>
.EE
.SS Encode xml: simple
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
cat\f[B]:\f[R] purrs
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=xml sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]cat\f[R]>purrs</\f[B]cat\f[R]>
.EE
.SS Encode xml: array
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
pets\f[B]:\f[R]
  cat\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] purrs
    \f[B]\-\f[R] meows
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=xml sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]pets\f[R]>
  <\f[B]cat\f[R]>purrs</\f[B]cat\f[R]>
  <\f[B]cat\f[R]>meows</\f[B]cat\f[R]>
</\f[B]pets\f[R]>
.EE
.SS Encode xml: attributes
Fields with the matching xml\-attribute\-prefix are assumed to be
attributes.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
cat\f[B]:\f[R]
  +\(atname\f[B]:\f[R] tiger
  meows\f[B]:\f[R] true
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=xml sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]cat\f[R] name=\(dqtiger\(dq>
  <\f[B]meows\f[R]>true</\f[B]meows\f[R]>
</\f[B]cat\f[R]>
.EE
.SS Encode xml: attributes with content
Fields with the matching xml\-content\-name is assumed to be content.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
cat\f[B]:\f[R]
  +\(atname\f[B]:\f[R] tiger
  +content\f[B]:\f[R] cool
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=xml sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]cat\f[R] name=\(dqtiger\(dq>cool</\f[B]cat\f[R]>
.EE
.SS Encode xml: comments
A best attempt is made to copy comments to xml.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]#\f[R]
\f[I]# header comment\f[R]
\f[I]# above_cat\f[R]
\f[I]#\f[R]
cat\f[B]:\f[R]\f[I] # inline_cat\f[R]
\f[I]  # above_array\f[R]
  array\f[B]:\f[R]\f[I] # inline_array\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] val1\f[I] # inline_val1\f[R]
\f[I]    # above_val2\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] val2\f[I] # inline_val2\f[R]
\f[I]# below_cat\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=xml sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[I]<!\-\-\f[R]
\f[I]header comment\f[R]
\f[I]above_cat\f[R]
\f[I]\-\->\f[R]
\f[I]<!\-\- inline_cat \-\->\f[R]
<\f[B]cat\f[R]>\f[I]<!\-\- above_array inline_array \-\->\f[R]
  <\f[B]array\f[R]>val1\f[I]<!\-\- inline_val1 \-\->\f[R]</\f[B]array\f[R]>
  <\f[B]array\f[R]>\f[I]<!\-\- above_val2 \-\->\f[R]val2\f[I]<!\-\- inline_val2 \-\->\f[R]</\f[B]array\f[R]>
</\f[B]cat\f[R]>\f[I]<!\-\- below_cat \-\->\f[R]
.EE
.SS Encode: doctype and xml declaration
Use the special xml names to add/modify proc instructions and
directives.
.PP
Given a sample.yml file of:
.IP
.EX
+p_xml\f[B]:\f[R] version=\(dq1.0\(dq
+directive\f[B]:\f[R] \(aqDOCTYPE config SYSTEM \(dq/etc/iwatch/iwatch.dtd\(dq \(aq
apple\f[B]:\f[R]
  +p_coolioo\f[B]:\f[R] version=\(dq1.0\(dq
  +directive\f[B]:\f[R] \(aqCATYPE meow purr puss \(aq
  b\f[B]:\f[R] things
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq \-o=xml sample.yml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
<?xml version=\(dq1.0\(dq?>
<!DOCTYPE config SYSTEM \(dq/etc/iwatch/iwatch.dtd\(dq >
<\f[B]apple\f[R]><?coolioo version=\(dq1.0\(dq?>\f[B]<\f[R]!CATYPE meow purr puss >
  <\f[B]b\f[R]>things</\f[B]b\f[R]>
</\f[B]apple\f[R]>
.EE
.SS Round trip: with comments
A best effort is made, but comment positions and white space are not
preserved perfectly.
.PP
Given a sample.xml file of:
.IP
.EX

\f[I]<!\-\- before cat \-\->\f[R]
<\f[B]cat\f[R]>
    \f[I]<!\-\- in cat before \-\->\f[R]
    <\f[B]x\f[R]>3\f[I]<!\-\- multi\f[R]
\f[I]line comment \f[R]
\f[I]for x \-\->\f[R]</\f[B]x\f[R]>
    \f[I]<!\-\- before y \-\->\f[R]
    <\f[B]y\f[R]>
        \f[I]<!\-\- in y before \-\->\f[R]
        <\f[B]d\f[R]>\f[I]<!\-\- in d before \-\->\f[R]z\f[I]<!\-\- in d after \-\->\f[R]</\f[B]d\f[R]>
        
        \f[I]<!\-\- in y after \-\->\f[R]
    </\f[B]y\f[R]>
    \f[I]<!\-\- in_cat_after \-\->\f[R]
</\f[B]cat\f[R]>
\f[I]<!\-\- after cat \-\->\f[R]
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq sample.xml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
\f[I]<!\-\- before cat \-\->\f[R]
<\f[B]cat\f[R]>\f[I]<!\-\- in cat before \-\->\f[R]
  <\f[B]x\f[R]>3\f[I]<!\-\- multi\f[R]
\f[I]line comment \f[R]
\f[I]for x \-\->\f[R]</\f[B]x\f[R]>\f[I]<!\-\- before y \-\->\f[R]
  <\f[B]y\f[R]>\f[I]<!\-\- in y before\f[R]
\f[I]in d before \-\->\f[R]
    <\f[B]d\f[R]>z\f[I]<!\-\- in d after \-\->\f[R]</\f[B]d\f[R]>\f[I]<!\-\- in y after \-\->\f[R]
  </\f[B]y\f[R]>\f[I]<!\-\- in_cat_after \-\->\f[R]
</\f[B]cat\f[R]>\f[I]<!\-\- after cat \-\->\f[R]
.EE
.SS Roundtrip: with doctype and declaration
yq parses XML proc instructions and directives into nodes.
Unfortunately the underlying XML parser loses whitespace information.
.PP
Given a sample.xml file of:
.IP
.EX
<?xml version=\(dq1.0\(dq?>
<!DOCTYPE config SYSTEM \(dq/etc/iwatch/iwatch.dtd\(dq >
<\f[B]apple\f[R]>
  <?coolioo version=\(dq1.0\(dq?>
  \f[B]<\f[R]!CATYPE meow purr puss >
  <\f[B]b\f[R]>things</\f[B]b\f[R]>
</\f[B]apple\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
then
.IP
.EX
yq sample.xml
.EE
.PP
will output
.IP
.EX
<?xml version=\(dq1.0\(dq?>
<!DOCTYPE config SYSTEM \(dq/etc/iwatch/iwatch.dtd\(dq >
<\f[B]apple\f[R]><?coolioo version=\(dq1.0\(dq?>\f[B]<\f[R]!CATYPE meow purr puss >
  <\f[B]b\f[R]>things</\f[B]b\f[R]>
</\f[B]apple\f[R]>
.EE
